or corrupt data, transcription errors, a copyright or other
intellectual property infringement, a defective or damaged disk or
other medium, a computer virus, or computer codes that damage or
cannot be read by your equipment.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/23673'),
    array('title' => 'Let our lips his glory tell.', 'author' => 'Lorenz, Edmund S. (Edmund Simon)', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "2 Gracious Lord! we love this day,
When we hear thy holy word;
When we sing thy praise, and pray,
Earth can no such joys afford;
But a better rest remains,
Heav'nly Sabbaths, happier days,
Rest from sin, and rest from pains,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/16455'),
    array('title' => 'That God is love.', 'author' => 'Lorenz, Edmund S. (Edmund Simon)', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "2 Oh, tell us to earth's remotest bound,
God is love;
In Christ we have redemption found,
God is love;
His blood has washed our sins away,
His Spirit turned our night to day,
And now we can rejoice to say", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/16455'),
    array('title' => 'To receive their heavenly King.', 'author' => 'Lorenz, Edmund S. (Edmund Simon)', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "2 Who is this that comes in glory,
With the trump of jubilee?
Lord of battles, God of armies,
He has gained the victory;
He, who on the cross did suffer,
He, who from the grave arose,
He has vanquished sin and Satan,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/16455'),
    array('title' => 'He by death has spoiled his foes.', 'author' => 'Lorenz, Edmund S. (Edmund Simon)', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "3 Thou hast raised our human nature,
On the clouds to God's right hand;
There we sit in heavenly places,
There with thee in glory stand;
Jesus reigns, adored by angels;
Man with God is on the throne;
Mighty Lord! in thine ascension,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/16455'),
    array('title' => 'Enter every trembling heart.', 'author' => 'Lorenz, Edmund S. (Edmund Simon)', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "2 Breathe, oh, breathe thy Holy Spirit
Into every troubled breast,
Let us all thy grace inherit;
Let us find thy promised rest;
Take away the love of sinning;
Take our load of guilt away;
End the work of thy beginning;", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/16455'),
    array('title' => 'If Jesus would dwell with me there.', 'author' => 'Lorenz, Edmund S. (Edmund Simon)', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "4 Dear Lord, if indeed I am thine,
If thou art my sun and my song,
Say, why do I languish and pine?
And why are my winters so long?
O, drive these dark clouds from my sky;
Thy soul-cheering presence restore;
Or take me unto thee on high,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/16455'),
    array('title' => 'I shall see, whom unseen I adored.', 'author' => 'Lorenz, Edmund S. (Edmund Simon)', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "3 And then, nevermore shall the fears,
The trials, temptations, and woes,
Which darken this valley of tears,
Intrude on my blissful repose;
To Jesus, the crown of my hope,
My soul is in haste to be gone;
Oh! bear me, ye cherubim, up,
And waft me away to his throne!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/16455'),
    array('title' => 'And I will walk with him.', 'author' => 'Lorenz, Edmund S. (Edmund Simon)', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "3 Green pastures are before me,
Which yet I have not seen;
Bright skies will soon be o'er me,
Where darkest clouds have been;
My hope I cannot measure,
My path to life is free;
My Savior has my treasure,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/16455'),
    array('title' => 'The distant scene; one step enough for me.', 'author' => 'Lorenz, Edmund S. (Edmund Simon)', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "2 I was not ever thus, nor prayed that thou
Shouldst lead me on;
I loved to choose and see my path, but now
Lead thou me on;
I loved the garish day, and spite of fears,
Pride ruled my will. Remember not past years.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/16455'),
    array('title' => 'While the days are going by.', 'author' => 'Lorenz, Edmund S. (Edmund Simon)', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "2 There's no time for idle scorning,
While the days are going by;
Let your face be like the morning,
While the days are going by;
Oh, the world is full of sighs,
Full of sad and weeping eyes;
Help your fallen brother rise,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/16455'),
    array('title' => 'Never fails from age to age.', 'author' => 'Lorenz, Edmund S. (Edmund Simon)', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "3 Round each habitation hovering,
See the cloud and tire appear,
For a glory and a covering,
Showing that the Lord is near!
Thus deriving from their banner,
Light by night, and shade by day,
Safe they feed upon the manna", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/16455'),
    array('title' => 'Who dwell with us at home.', 'author' => 'Lorenz, Edmund S. (Edmund Simon)', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "2 Where blooms the broad savanna,
Where mighty waters roll,
There let the gospel banner
Beam hope on every soul;
Go where the west is teeming,
And yet behold they come!
The fields all ripe are gleaming
For those who reap at home!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/16455'),
    array('title' => 'By and by, by and by.', 'author' => 'Lorenz, Edmund S. (Edmund Simon)', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "3 We shall see and be like Jesus,
By and by, by and by;
Who a crown of life will give us,
By and by, by and by;
And the angels who fulfill
All the mandates of his will
Shall attend, and love us still,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/16455'),
    array('title' => 'Savior, keep my heart with thee.', 'author' => 'Lorenz, Edmund S. (Edmund Simon)', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "2 Shall I be at work, for Jesus,
Whilst he leads me by the hand,
And to those around be saying,
Come and join this happy band?
Come, for all things now are ready,
Come, his faithful foll'wer be;
Oh, where'er my path be leading,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/16455'),
    array('title' => 'Rushes on to our view, and eternity\'s near.', 'author' => 'Lorenz, Edmund S. (Edmund Simon)', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "3 Oh, that each, in the day
Of his coming, may say,
\"I have fought my way through;
I have finished the work thou didst give me to do;\"
Oh, that each from his Lord
May receive the glad word,
\"Well and faithfully done;
Enter into my joy and sit down on my throne\"", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/16455'),
    array('title' => 'From _The Academy of Compliments_, 1650.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "IF[2] my lady bid begin,
Shall I say \"No: 'tis a sin\"?
If she bid me kiss and play,
Shall I shrink, cold fool, away?
If she clap my cheeks and spy
Little Cupids in my eye,
Gripe my hand and stroke my hair,
Shall I like a faint heart fear?
No, no, no: let those that lie
In dismal prison, and would die,
Despair and fear; let those that cry
They are forsaken and would fly,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'That\'s the only Cupid now.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Whilst the world continued good,
And men loved for flesh and blood,
Men about them wore a dart
Which did win a woman's heart;
And the women, great and small,
With a certain thing they call
_Kiss Me, Kiss Me, Kiss Me_, caught the men:", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'And sigh\'d away for Phillis\' sake.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "This, Phillis, this shall be our talk
Whilst hand in hand we gently walk;
Then down we'll sit in yonder shade
A myrtle has for lovers made;
And when I've called thee duck and dear,
And wooed thee with a sigh or tear,
If love, or pity on thy swain,
Move Phillis' heart to cure my pain,
Then like two billing turtles we", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'A pretty riddle I\'ll to thee unfold:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "These leaves shut in as close as cloistered nun,
Yet will they open when they see the sun.\"
\"What mean you by this riddle, sir?\" she said;
\"I pray expound it.\" Then I thus begun:
\"Are not men made for maids and maids for men?\"", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'Makes drowsy love to play bopeep.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "How prettily his feathers blow
Those fleshy shuttings to and fro!
O how he makes me Tantalise
With those fair apples of thine eyes!
Equivocates and cheats me still,
Opening and shutting at his will,
Now both, now one! the doting god", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'To her glad lover she more kindness shows.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Oft had Amyntas with her tresses play'd
When the sun's vigour, drove 'em to a shade;
And many a time had given her a green gown,
And oft he kissed her when he had her down;
With sighs and motions he to her made known
What fain he would have done: then with a frown
She would forbid him, till the minute came", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'She smiled, she frown\'d, she would and would not do.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "At length o'ercome she suffers with a sigh
Her ravish'd lover use his victory,
And gave him leave to punish her delay
With double vigour in the am'rous play;
But then, alas! soon ended the delight;
For too much love had hastened[15] its flight,
And _every_ ravish'd sense too soon awake,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'What \'twas you took so wondrous ill--', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "A kiss. But with a coy disdain
You view'd my sighings and my pain;
'Twas but a civil small request,
Yet with proud looks and hand on breast,
You cried \"I'm not so eager to be kiss'd,\"
Put case[17] that I had loosed your gown,
And then by force had laid you down,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'This would have been provoking matter.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "But I, poor harmless civil I,
Begg'd for the meanest coolest joy,
And saw denial in your eye;
For with a squeamish glance you cried
\"I hate the nauseous bliss.\"
\"'Tis well,\" said I; \"since I'm denied,
For rocks of diamonds I'll not kiss.\"", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'Let me ha\'t, sir.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "I'd ha' thee, quoth he. Would you ha' me, quoth she?
But where, sir?
To my chamber, quoth he. To your chamber, quoth she?
Why there, sir?
I'd kiss thee, quoth he. Would you kiss me, quoth she?
But when, sir?
Why now, quoth he. Neither now, quoth she,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'Not a touch, sir.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "I am sickish, quoth he. Are you sickish, quoth she?
But why, sir?
'Cause you slight me, quoth he. Do I slight you, quoth she?
'Tis a lie, sir.
I'm dying, quoth he. O dying, quoth she?
Are you sure on't?
'Tis certain, quoth he. Is't certain, quoth she?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'DEAR, I must do.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "_Phillis._ O I dare not.
_Strephon._ 'Twill not hurt you.
_Phillis._ No, I care not.
_Strephon._ Then I prithee, sweet, tell me the reason.
_Phillis._ Will you marry?
_Strephon._ Yes, to-morrow.
_Phillis._ Till then tarry.
_Strephon._ I would borrow.
_Phillis._ Fruit is best when gathered in season.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'A very charm for Argus\' eyes.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "Now pray then tell me, and withal
Pray be not too-too partial,
Doth not one feature[21] now in mine
Appear more lovely than all thine?
No airy objects will me[22] move,
It is the sober black I love:
I love't so well that I protest
I love the blackest parts the best.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'To make me think the rest of like perfection,--', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "The rest where all rest lies that blesseth man,
That Indian mine, that straight of Magellan,
That world-dividing gulf where whoso venters
With swelling sails and ravish'd senses enters
Into a world of bliss. Pardon, I pray,
If my rude muse doth seem here to display
Secrets unknown, or hath her bounds o'erpast", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'From ROBERT JONES\' _Second Book of Songs and Airs_, 1601.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "METHOUGHT[24] the other night
I saw a pretty sight
That pleased me much;
A fair and comely maid,
Not squeamish nor afraid
To let me touch,
Our lips most sweetly kissing,
Each other never missing;
Her smiling looks did show content", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'I mean not long to tarry.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "When I was fifteen years of age
Then I had suitors many,
But I, a wanton peevish wench,
Would not sport with any;
Till at the last, I sleeping fast,
Cupid came to woo me,
And like a lad that was stark mad", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'From ROBERT JONES\' _First Book of Songs and Airs_, 1601.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "SWEET Philomel in groves and desarts haunting
Oft glads my heart and ears with her sweet chaunting,
But then her tunes delight me best,
When perched with prick against her breast
She sings \"Fy, fy!\" as if she suffered wrong,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'It was Saint Valentine.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "In fields by Phoebus great with young
Of flowers and hopeful buds,
Resembling thoughts that freshly sprung
In lovers' lively bloods,
A damsel fair and fine I saw,
So fair and finely dight,
As put my heart almost in awe", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'I gave my Valentine.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Subscribed with a line of love,
My name for her I wrote;
In silk for me her name she wove
Whereto this was her mot,[42]
\"As shall this year thy truth appear,
I still, my dear, am thine\";
\"Your mate today, and love for aye,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'When you did vow to live and die a maid:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "O if you knew what chance to them befell
That dance about with bobtail apes in hell,
Yourself your virgin girdle would divide
And put aside the maiden veil that hides
The chiefest gem of nature; and would lie
Prostrate to every peasant that goes by,
Rather than undergo such shame: no tongue can tell", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'The sun\'s heat they defied and cool\'d their own.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Children\'s songs', 'lyrics' => "Whilst they did embrace unspied,
The conscious willow seem'd to smile,
That them[62] with privacy supplied,
Holding the door, as 'twere, the while;
And when their dalliances were o'er,
The willows, to oblige them more,
Bowing, did seem to say, as they withdrew,
\"We can supply you with a cradle too.\"", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'Ere they so long would tarry.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "The wench that is most coy of all,
If she had time and leisure,
Would lay by all her several thoughts
And turn to love and pleasure;
For even the wisest heads sometimes
Put on the face of folly,
And maids do nevermore repent", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'Than when they are too holy.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Winter nights are long, you know,
And bitter cold the weather;
Then who's so fond to lie alone
When two may lie together?
And is't not brave when summer's robes
Have all the fields encowled
To have a green gown on the grass
And wear it uncontroul'd?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'TO FLORA.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "WHAT though Flora frowns on me?
'Tis but a chance of destiny.
The wisest I have heard to say,
'Tis dusk before the break of day.
Why should I curse that hour of night
That brings the day to light?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'Shew thee fearful of thy joy.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "What is man that thou shouldst dread
To change with him a maidenhead?
At first all virgins fear to do it
And but trifle away their time,
And still unwilling to come to it
In foolish whining spend their time;
But when they once have found the way,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'The temple, but the goddess more.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "If then my soul you would confine
To prison, tie your heart to mine;
Your noble virtues, constant love,
The only pow'rful chains will prove
To bind me ever; such as those
The bands of death shall ne'er unloose,
Until I such a prisoner be", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46359'),
    array('title' => 'Be nuh  Je sus  tuh gwish in.', 'author' => 'Anonymous', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "4 'Nuh  ke guh shuh gush ke tah goog
Na yaub  ba mah de ze jig;
O! keen  ba mah je e wa yun
Kah ge nig  ash puh be yun,
Oo dah pe nun
E newh  oo ge mah win un.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/33128'),
    array('title' => 'Che ge see be ge ne yun.', 'author' => 'Anonymous', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "4 Uh pe  ish quah na sa yon,
Nuh guh duh mon  ewh  uh kee,
Nin guh wah bun don  we kah
Kah be wah bun duh se won
Nin dah zhe be koom  Je sus,
Kah zhe shin  suh  ke yuh wing.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/33128'),
    array('title' => 'Nin guh aung wah me ze min.', 'author' => 'Anonymous', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "3 Uh pe  dush  puh gum me uh yaug
Uh ke  che nuh guh duh maung,
Uh pe  an je nug  ish pe ming
E zhe we zhe yun gid wah,
Mah noo  moon zhug
Nin guh  oo ge mah we min.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/33128'),
    array('title' => 'By thy return, sweet hour of prayer.', 'author' => 'Anonymous', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "2 Sweet hour of prayer! sweet hour of prayer!
Thy wings shall my petition bear,
To him whose truth and faithfulness,
Engage the waiting soul to bless;
And since he bids me seek his face,
Believe his word, and trust his grace,
I'll cast on him my every care,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/33128'),
    array('title' => 'E mah  uh nuh me ah we ning.', 'author' => 'Anonymous', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "3 We shko bun  uh nuh me ah win!
Ewh  won duh mah go yon  noon goom
O mah  uh keeng  oon zah be yon,
Nin da bah bun don,  ka da yon;
Ka e zhah yon,  kee ne boo yon,
Kah ge nig,  ka duh nuh kee yon,
Nin guh sah sah qua,  ke zhe goong,
Uh pe  nuh guh duh mon  uh kee.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/33128'),
    array('title' => 'E gewh  ke ning wee guh nug.', 'author' => 'Anonymous', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "3 Ke wee doo kah ga win ing,
Ning uh  oon je  noo je moosh;
Wain je  noo je mwah bah waing
Ning uh  be pee ne e goon;
Keen  mah  pe mah de ze win,
Wa ne puzh  nin dah  uh yon;
Um ba,  nin da ing  uh toon,
Kah ge ga  pe mahd' ze win.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/33128'),
    array('title' => 'In praise of Robin Hood, his outlaws, and their trade.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "An hundred valiant men had this brave Robin Hood,
Still ready at his call, that bowmen were right good,
All clad in Lincoln green (16), with caps of red and blue,
His fellow’s winded horn not one of them but knew,
When setting to their lips their little beugles shrill,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/56926'),
    array('title' => 'To him before he went, but for his pass must pay:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "The widow in distress he graciously reliev’d,
And remedied the wrongs of many a virgin griev’d: (17)
He from the husband’s bed no married woman wan,
But to his mistress dear, his loved Marian,
Was ever constant known, which wheresoe’er she came,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/56926'),
    array('title' => 'And many more I will not speake of here.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Good God! how glad hath been this hart of mine,
To see that towne, which hath, in former time,
So flourish’d and so gloried in her name,
Famous by th’ pindar who first rais’d the same!
Yea, I have paced ore that greene and ore
And th’ more I saw’t I tooke delight the more, {xxviii}
For where we take contentment in a place,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/56926'),
    array('title' => 'A whole daies walke seemes as a cinquepace.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Yet as there is no solace upon earth
Which is attended evermore with mirth,
But when we are transported most with gladnesse,
Then suddenly our joy’s reduc’d to sadnesse;
So far’d with me to see the pindar gone,
And of those jolly laddes that were not one", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/56926'),
    array('title' => 'The ground whereon our historie is laied.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "_Trumpets sounde_, [1] _enter first King Richard with drum and
auncient, giving Ely a purse and sceptre, his mother and brother
John, Chester, Lester, Lacie, others at the king’s appointment,
doing reverence. The king goes in: presently Ely ascends the
chaire, Chester, John, and the queene part displeasantly._ [2]
Enter ROBERT, EARLE OF HUNTINGTON, _leading Marian; followes him
Warman, and after Warman, the prior; Warman ever flattering and
making curtsie, taking gifts of the prior behinde and his master
before. Prince John enters, offereth to take Marian; Queen Elinor
enters, offering to pull Robin from her; but they infolde each
other, and sit downe within the curteines._ [3] _Warman with the
prior, Sir Hugh Lacy, Lord Sentloe, and Sir Gilbert Broghton folde
hands, and drawing the curteins, all_ (_but the prior_) _enter,
and are kindely received by_ Robin Hoode.”", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/56926'),
    array('title' => 'Hood.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Since graves may not their dead containe,
Nor in their peacefull sleepes remaine,
But triumphes and great showes must use them,
And we unable to refuse them;
It joyes me that earle Robert Hood,
Fetcht from the forrest of merrie Shirwood,
With these my yeomen tight and tall,
Brave huntsmen and good archers all,
Must in this joviall day partake,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/56926'),
    array('title' => 'The deed performed with the word.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "For Robin and his bow-men bold,
Religiously did ever holde,
Not emptie-handed to be seene,
Were’t but at feasting on a greene; {lxviii}
Much more then, when so high a day
Calls our attendance: all we may
Is all too little, tis your grace", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/56926'),
    array('title' => 'Nay, nay, for there is no reason why.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "For is it not as good to say playnly
Gyf me a spade,
As gyf me a spa ve va ve va ve vade?
But yf thou wylt have a song that is good,
I have one of Robyn Hode,
The best that ever was made. {lxxx}", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/56926'),
    array('title' => 'And Bevis of Southampton, to seek the matter out.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Suffer all slander against God and his truth,
And praise the old fashion in king Arthur’s days,
Of abbays and monasteries how it is great ruth
To have them plucked down, and so the eldest says;
And how it was merry when Robin Hood’s plays
Was in every town, the morrice and the fool,
The maypole and the drum, to bring the calf from school,
With Midge, Madge and Marion, about the pole to dance,
And Stephen, that tall stripling, to lead Volans dance,
With roguing Gangweeke, a goodly remembrance,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/56926'),
    array('title' => 'All the ingenious ‘yeomen’ of the bow.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "To read how Robin Hood and Little John,
Brave Scarlet, Stutely, valiant, bold and free,
Each of them bravely, fairly play’d the man,
While they did reign beneath the green-wood tree;
Bishops, friars, likewise many more,
Parted with their gold, for to increase their store,
But never would they rob or wrong the poor.”", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/56926'),
    array('title' => 'For to cease that tyme mente he.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Mersadage kinge of Barbarye
He did carye to his tente,
And beryed him by right of Sarsenye,
With brennynge fire riche oynemente ;
And songe the _dirige_ of ALKARON,
_That bibill is of here laye_ ;
And wayled his deth everychon,
Seven nyghtis and seven dayes.”", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/56926'),
    array('title' => 'Alcoran); in the following passage it is that of a GOD:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "“Now shall ye here of Laban :
Whan tidynges to him were comen,
Tho was he a fulle sory man,
Whan he herde howe his vitaile were nomen,
And howe his men were slayne,
And Gye was go safe hem froo ;
He defyed _Mahounde_, and _Apolyne_,
_Jubiter_, _Astarol_, and ALCARON also.”", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/56926'),
    array('title' => 'Wyfe had I never none.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "This cannot I denye,
But if thou be a good felowe,
I wil sel mi horse, mi harneis, pottes and paniers to,
Thou shalt have the one halfe and I will have the other ;
If thou be not so content,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/56926'),
    array('title' => 'Oh fine Arthur of Bradley, oh, &c.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Arthur had got him a lass,
A bonnier never was ; {361}
The chief youths of the parish
Came dancing of the morris ;
With country lasses trounsing,
And lusty lads bounsing,
Jumping with mickle pride,
And each his wench by his side ;
They all were fine and gay,
For the honour of Arthur of Bradley,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/56926'),
    array('title' => 'Oh fine, &c.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Richard he did lead it,
And Margery did tread it,
Francis followed them,
And after courteous Jane ;
Thus every one after another,
As if they had been sister and brother ;
That ’twas great joy to see
How well they did agree ;
And then they all did say,
Hay for Arthur of Bradley !", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/56926'),
    array('title' => 'For the honour of his Peg :', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "But Kister in cambrick ruffe,
He took that all in snuffe ;
For he against that day
Had made himself fine and gay,
His ruffe was whipt with blew, {364}
And he cried, A new dance, a new,
Then strike up a round-delay,
For the honour of Arthur of Bradley,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/56926'),
    array('title' => 'HALL is changed from “xlv” to “xiv”.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Page xxi. The Pedigree of Robin Hood in the printed book was a
complicated chart, which cannot be represented properly in this
simple text edition. Therefore a transcription has been provided,
based on the geneological numbering system of Robert B. Henry—see
for example wikipedia.org, search for Ahnentafel_with_generation.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/56926'),
    array('title' => 'I apologize for any errors you might find in this transcription.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Children\'s songs', 'lyrics' => "The Henry system starts with a progenitor, numbered 1, his/her
children, numbered 11, 12, etc, followed by grandchildren 111, 112,
etc. The system ordinarily depends on knowing the order of birth
of children to parents, but that is not provided in our book, so
our Henry numbers are, in that respect, arbitrary, showing only
parentage. Also, the abbreviation m. is used in this transcription,
ordinarily meaning “married”, but in this case indicating only
parentage.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/56926'),
    array('title' => 'A dimple in his chin.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "He’s ne mair learning,
Than tells his weekly earning,
Yet reet frae wrang discerning,
Tho’ brave, ne bruiser he;
Tho’ he no worth a plack is,
His awn coat on his back is,
And nane can say that black is", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Fal lal, &c.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "The gale blew stranger an’ stranger,
When they cam beside the Muck House,
The skipper cry’d out--“Jemmy Swinger,”
But still was as fear’d as a mouse;
P.D. ran to clear th’ anchor,
“It’s raffl’d!” right loudly he roar’d,--
They a’ said the gale wad sink her,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Ye Britons and _Sons_ of the _Tyne_.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Though Nelson is dead, yet we ought not to mourn;
The laurels that deck his magnificent Urn,
Are sufficient for mortals that dwell here below;
Let Heaven’s great King other laurels bestow
On him we adore,
Who fought off the shore,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'At Trafalgar’s great battle, and died.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "Drink a toast, then, my friends, to his dear honour’d shade,
Each widow, each wife, every matron, and maid,
And though you lament for the loss of his blood,
Drink a health to our own, our brave Collingwood,
Who fought with that _great man_,
That bother’d the Frenchmen,
At Trafalgar’s great battle, and died.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Their nectar was nothing to Newcastle beer.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "The great god of war, to encourage the fun,
And humour the taste of his whimsical guest,
Sent a message that moment to Moor’s[2] for a tun
Of stingo, the stoutest, the brightest and best;
No gods, they all swore,
Regal’d so before,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'And smoke o’er a tankard of Newcastle beer.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Ye fanciful folk, for whom Physic prescribes,
Whom bolus and potion have harrass’d to death!
Ye wretches, whom Law and her ill-looking tribes,
Have hunted about ’till you’re quite out of breath!
Here’s shelter and ease,
No craving for fees,
No danger--no doctor--no bailiff is near!
Your spirits this raises,
It cures your diseases,
There’s freedom and health in our Newcastle beer.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'All waiting and gaping to see my _Lord ’Size_.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Oft stretch’d were their necks, oft erected their ears,
Still fancying they heard of the trumpets the sound,
When tidings arriv’d, which disolv’d them in tears,
That my Lord at the dead-house was then lying drown’d!
Straight left _tête a tête_ were the jailor and thief;
The horror-struck crowd to the dead-house quick hies;
Ev’n the lawyers, forgetful of fee and of brief,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'By JOHN SHIELD, of Newcastle.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "Fareweel, fareweel, ma comely pet!
Aw’s fourc’d three weeks to leave thee;
Aw’s doon for _parm’ent duty_ set,
O dinna let it grieve thee!
Ma hinny! wipe them e’en, sae breet,
That mine wi’ love did dazzle;
When thy heart’s sad can mine be leet!
Come, ho’way get a jill o’ beer,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'An’ sair the drums they’re skelpin.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Fareweel, ma comely! aw mun gang,
The Gen’ral’s een to dazzle;
But, hinny! if the time seems lang,
And thou freets about me neet an’ day;
Then come away,
Seek out the yell-house where aw stay,
An’ we’ll kiss and cuddle;
An’ mony a fuddle
Sall drive the langsome hours away,
When sougering at Newcassel.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'For him they would spend their last crown.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "The liquor beginning to warm them,
In friendship the closer they knit,
And tell and hear jokes--and, to charm them,
Comes ROBIN, from Denton-Bourn pit;
An odd witty, comical fellow,
At either a jest or a tale,
Especially when he was mellow", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'With drinking stout Newcastle ale.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "With bousing, and laughing, and smoking,
The time slippeth swiftly away;
And while they are ranting and joking
The church-clock proclaims it mid-day;
And now for black-puddings, long measure,
They go to TIB TROLLIBAG’S stand,
And away bear the glossy rich treasure,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'With joy, like curl’d bugles in hand.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "And now a choice house they agreed on,
Not far from the head of the Quay;
Where they their black puddings might feed on
And spend the remains of the day;
Where pipers and fiddlers resorted,
To pick up the straggling pence,
And where the pit lads often sported", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Thou cannot go home with bare groins.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "How the warfaring companies parted,
The Muse chuseth not to proclaim;
But, ’tis thought, that, being rather down-hearted,
They quietly went--“toddling hame.”
Now ye Collier callants, so clever,
Residing ’tween Tyne and the Wear,
Beware, when you fuddle together,
Of making too free with strong beer.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Go flocking with beards they have seven days worn.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "And round the small grate, Sir, in crowds they all wait, Sir,
To get themselves shav’d in a rotative turn;
Old soldiers on sticks, Sir, about politics, Sir,
Debate--till at length they quite heated have grown;
May nothing escape, Sir, until _Madame Scrape_, Sir,
Cries, “Gentlemen, who is the next to sit down?”", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Discourse about nought but whee puts and hews best:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "There keelmen, just landed, swear may they be stranded,
If they’re not shav’d first while their keel’s at the _Fest_;
With a face of coal dust, would frighten one almost,
Thro’ off hat and wig, while they usurp the chair;
While others stand looking, and think it provoking,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'With lather, she whitens them up to the eyes.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "No sooner the razor is laid on the face, Sir,
Then painful distortions take place on the brow;
But if they complain, Sir, they’ll find it in vain, Sir,
She’ll tell them there’s nought but what _Patience_ can do;
And as she scrapes round ’em, if she by chance wound ’em,
They’ll cry out as tho’ she’d bereav’d them of life,
“’Od smash your brains, woman! I find the blood’s coming,
“I’d rather been shav’d with an au’d gully knife!”", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'The fleeting rover to pursue.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "Yet as she has an itching still,
To mount the great Parnassus hill,
I straightway thither did repair,
But found she never had been there;
That being too divine a place,
For her to chant unhallow’d lays;
When turning quick my eye around
On Tindale’s shore, the wand’rer found,
Where she was taking a survey,
Of all that in her compass lay;
A medley of such objects rose,
Which pen but faintly can disclose;
But being in a merry pin,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'To make them crowdies once a day.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "These are your pranks, you murd’ring rogue,
That every day you have in vogue;
And if you do not mend your course,
I must go beg--or else do worse.”
Tom out his hand at last did stretch,
“What ails you now? you grumbling bitch,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Peace! or your hide I’ll soundly switch.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Do not I almost ev’ry day,
At the _lang hinney’s_ o’er the way,
See Geordy Jenkin’s wife and you,
Drinking clove waters till you spue!
Go to the devil with your brats,
And vex me not with d----’d pit-rats,
That are not all of my begetting,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Until they’re pockets are quite bare.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Here mangy Scots from banks of Tay,
With scarce a plaid to bear away;
Half-starv’d, they from the frozen North,
Like swarms of locusts, sally forth,
Worse than before, on Pharaoh’s land,
Were sent by the Almighty hand;
Such hardness of their hearts to purge,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'And for their wickedness them scourge:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "This mugletonian blackguard breed,
Upon our very vitals feed;
And, like the whelps of Juno’s pack,
Of Scots infection bring a smack;
When hither come, they seldom fail
To scrape the scabs from off their tail;
By artful tricks, and well form’d lies,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'As if they sprung from noble stalk.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "At midnight these, and such like sots,
With noddles full, from stinking pots
Of rank geneva, and of rum,
They raise a scent where’er they come;
Reel, cursing, in a grumbling tone,
In some dark lane, where sun ne’er shone,
But darkness dire, surrounds the place,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'An emblem of their foul disgrace:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Oft in a house decay’d with age,
Which scarce will bear the winter’s rage;
Whose crazy outshots threat’ning hing
About their ears, a peal to ring;
They tumble in one common bed,
Where all are there promiscuous laid;
And ten to one, but as they fall,
They break their heads against the wall;
Nor do they mind to choose their wives,
With whom they’re bound to lead their lives;
But to the first they come do keep,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Where, if they’re drunk, they fall asleep.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "If not, there’s oft a general horning
Takes place before the next day morning.--
Gomorrah ne’er could fuller be
Than _Sandgate_ with impiety,
So cramm’d with immorality
Is every one, that if there be
A place on earth resembling hell,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Fever Hospital.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "The Watchmen, ’tis granted, correctly and clever,
Of the hour informs us, and state of the weather;
But doubly delightful, their _calling_ would be,
Were they all wise enough to take lessons from Me;
O when ding dong, ding dong, my Bell goes,
Each Taylor leaps up at the sound;
Off, to hear me, like roe bucks, they scampering set,
So delighted, I’m told, that they _cabbage_ forget,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'For what can so fire us, &c.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Haste, haste to partake on’t, ye men of grave faces,
Ye Quakers, and Methodist parsons likewise;
What tho’ ye seem lost to the flexible graces,
And dormant the risible faculty lies;
One quaff of the vapour
Will cause you to caper,
And swiftly relax your stiff solemniz’d jaws;
You’ll acknowledge the change too,
As pleasing as strange too,
And make the air ring with loud ha! ha! ha! ha’s!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Whose Bellman taught lays set the house in a roar:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Common sense stands aghast, thunder-struck and confounded,
While Dullness brays out from its Gall’ry, _Encore!_
Then, big with applause,
Crack’s Scotch ell of jaws[14]
Sets forth a hoarse bawling, so purely divine,
That hydras or bears
Might prick up their ears,
And howl out in concert with Bards of the Tyne.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'And all agreed a _Crocodile_ had got into the harbour.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Yet greatly Jack’s discovery his auditors did shock, Sir,
For they dreaded that the _Salmon_ would be eat up by the Croc. Sir:
When presently the _Crocodile_, their consternation crowning,
Raised its head above the waves, and cried, “_Help! O Lord, I’m
drowning!_”
Heavens! how their hair, Sir, stood on end, from the parson to
the barber;", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Nor foes, nor foul weather could alter her heart.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Their younglings, quite able to take distant flight,
Were told, by their parents, “_Good manners are right_.”
To their freedom admitted--they could do no less,
Than approach their kind patrons, with humble ADDRESS;
To thank them politely, without wanton joke,
For, so learned in _swallow_, they must learn to _croak_.--
In a trice----as if ÆSOP himself had inspir’d,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Why some _Merlin_, or _Shipton_, hath sure sent us here.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "“One thousand seven hundred, eighty and three,
For this town, a remarkable æra will be!
All folks will _think_ right, from grave age to smart youth,
Nor priests, nor disciples, _e’er_ wander from TRUTH;
Your rulers be loyal to great George the third,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Ralphs, Richardsons, Rogersons, uttered with ease.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "“No tailor will _cabbage_, no draper will _pinch_,
No shoemaker _squeeze_ a full nail from an inch;
No baker, or flourman, be short of his weight,
No forestaller _breed_ low designs in his pate;
No butcher, on _Bank_, keep prices too high,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'My lovely Mary of the Tyne.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "I lose, when near thee, all my care,
When from thee, I am all despair;
My bosom heaves with anxious pain,
Until I meet with thee again,
What are these adverse pangs of mine,
My lovely Mary of the Tyne?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Rum te idily, &c.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Then rising, aw went ma ways heame,
Aw knock’d at the door, an’ cry’d, Jenny;
Says she, Canny man, is’te lame,
Or been wadin in Tyne, ma hinny?
I’ troth, she was like for to dee,
An’ just by the way to relieve her,
The water’s been wadin through me,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Their right to _be Bankers_, and objections remove.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "The title, they presume, will command the esteem
Of those who at a distance, from hence, may have seen
Their elegant Notes; their clothes--they vow, and declare,
In London were made, as you may see by their air;
The skin on Sir _James_, is not so fit as his coat,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Whose finery often--has made us Bankers frown.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "They are not worth an hundred thousand it’s true,
But supposing they were, cou’d the public, and you
Their friends be assured they wou’d not exceed
Their capital _twice_, when their paper you need,
And _wisely prefer_ it, to hard silver and gold,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Because you don’t _weigh_ it, and it’s much sooner told.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "The notes of their brethern they will not refuse,
Let other bankers less _wise_, do that if they chuse;
The public they’ll serve, their cash take, and bills discount,
Except at Change hours, to any amount;
And when profusion and taxes, and of America the loss,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Old England has ruin’d--firm will stand the _Scale Cross_.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "The critics our doggrels will sneer at, we suppose,
But _Strap_, who’s a GENIUS, has measur’d them, and knows,
Like a shoe on a last they are fit, and convey
Our intention completely, and it’s needless to say,
Newcastle, Exchange, Tyne, or Commercial Bank,[34]
Must yield to us in writing, as well as in rank,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Which nature _e’er_ bestow’d on human race.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Through a long life, example bright thou shone!
By all belov’d:--Now each regrets thou’rt gone!
Thy suff’rings here were weigh’d; nor shall thy death
Be more than ceasing of thy mortal breath;
Thy Master calls, ripe for thy Master’s joy,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'That waves destruction o’er the smiling land.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "And ’midst the accents of her harsher lays,
Shall she forget to sound the good man’s praise?
Forbid it, every spark of social love,
That made, through life, his every passion move;
That taught his heart with sympathy to glow,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'And wash, with unfeign’d tears, thy hallow’d urn.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "No laurel wreath, nor high poetic lays
Need bloom, or live in song to sound thy praise;
For whilst thy loss our keenest sorrow moves,
O’er all the _past_, delighted fancy roves;
Each fond remembrance that reverts to thee,
Tells what our _present_ conduct ought to be;
And points, with heavenward aim, to that Dread Power,
Whose mystic means unfolds the _future_ hour;
Cheers the dark gloom of life’s last setting ray,
And leads us on to everlasting day!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Auld HEBSRIME and NORTHUMBERLAND.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Zit was our meeting meik enough,
Begun with mirriness and mows,
And at the brae abune the heugh
The clerk sat doun to call the rows,
And sum for ky and sum for ewis,
Callit in of DANDRIE HOB and JOCK,
I saw cum merching owre the knows,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'And he was fugitive that fled.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "CARMICHAEL bad them speik out plainly,
And cloke nae cause for ill nor gude,
The uther answering him full vainly,
Begouth to reckon kin and blude,
He raise and rax’d him quhair he stude,
And bade him match him with his marrows;
Then TYNDAL hard these reseuns rude,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Culd cause nae cowards turn again.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Up raise the laird to red the cumber,
Quhilk wald not be for all his boist,
Quhat suld we do with sic a number,
Fyve thousand men into an hoist?
Then HENRIE PURDIE proud hes cost,
And verie narrowlie had mischiefd him,
And ther we had our WARDEN lost,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'And stude about him in the stour.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Then raisd the slogan with an schout,
Fy, TYNDALL to it, JEDBRUGH heir;
I trow he was not half sae stout,
But anes his stomach was a steir,
With gun and genzie, bow and spier,
He micht se mony a crakit crown,
But up amang the merchant gier,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Doun owre the brae lyke clogged beis.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Sir FRANCIS RUSSEL tane was thair,
And hurt, as we heir men reherse;
Proud WALLINGTOUN was wounded sair,
Albeit he was a Fennick ferss,
But gif ze wald a souldier serche
Amang them all was tane that night,
Was nane sae wordie of our verse", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'VERSES', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "_On a View of Roadley Castle, not far from Wallington, in
Northumberland, built by the late worthy Sir Walter Blackett, Bart,
with a small Description of its Situation, comprehending Codgy Fort,
the Lake, the noted Greenlighton Hill, &c. by Thomas Oliver, of
Hallington, Northumberland, taken before the Deer were destroyed in the
Park, wherein the Castle stands, soon after the Death of Sir Walter
Blackett._", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Than Ecky e’er had with his mear.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "The devil ne’er saw such a gelding
As this to be foal’d of a mear;
The size ont’s a shame to be teld on,
And yet it could skip like a deer;
For colour and size (I’m a sinner,
I scorn, as the folks say, to slide,)
’Twas just like Hob Trumble’s gimmer,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Which he sold for six-pence a side.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "It was a confounded bad liver,
Like Ferry the piper’s old cat;
It ne’er could be brought to behaviour,
Though it has got many a bat;
It had been so spoil’d in up-bringing,
It vext his poor heart every day;
Sometimes with biting and flinging,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'And knew not what way it was gone.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "A day or two after, have at it,
He north in pursuit on’t took chase,
And like a dub-skelper he trotted,
To many strange village and place;
All Rothbury forest he ranged,
From corner to corner like mad,
And still he admired and stranged,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Another thing was their intent.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Tom Fawdon soon knew what they wanted,
And straightway the table was set,
With bread, butter and cheese it was planted,
And good ale, as well as good meat;
Their grace took but little inditing,
’Twas short and they had it by heart;
And they took as little inviting,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Were drest like a pair of strait boots.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "With bellies top-full to the rigging,
I leave them to settle a bit,
’Till making good use of the midding,
‘Do’ bring them unto a right set.
Now come we to speak of the gelding,
Who knowing that he did offend,
Stay’d two or three days about Weldon,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'So slily himself he did clear.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "The town of Longframlington further
Can give an account what he is,
He came within acting of murder,
As near as a horse could to miss;
For unto a house he went scudding,
And seeing a child all alone,
If Providence had not withstood him,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'He’d struck it as dead as a stone.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "The rest of his acts are recorded,
’Tis nonsense to mention them here;
I’ll go back and fetch Geordy forward,
He’s tarri’d too long I do fear!
From Brinkburn he started and held on,
Directly to Framlington town,
And then to the miller’s at Weldon,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'His pad, as it once did Tom Thumb.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Then up to John Alders he drabbeth,
And there all the night did repose,
And then, the next day being Sabbath,
Away he to Whittingham goes;
Where he to revenge the miscarriage
Of his little scatter-brain’d nag,
He went to the clerk of the parish,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Suppose it were to the North pole.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "’Tis past a man’s giving account on,
What way he traversed with speed,
From Eslington, Whittingham, Thrunton,
He past the Broom-park and Hill-head,
To Learchild, to Barton, to Branton,
And from thence to Mount on the clay,
To Fawdon, the Clinch, and to Glanton,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'And several towns mist by the way.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "There’s Lemington, Abberwick, Bolton,
With Woodhall that stands on the fell,
And Titlington’s likewise untold on,
Where Jacob, of old, dig’d his well;
To Harup, to Hidgily and Beanly,
He past unto Callaly mill,
To Brandon, to Ingram, and Reavely,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'That when the pin turn’d did take wing.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Next day rising, rigging and starting,
He jogg’d on his journey with speed,
To Bewick, the Lilburns, Coldmartin,
From thence unto Woolerhaugh-head;
To Wooperton, Ilderton, Rodham,
And Rosedon, he scudded like mad,
Nothing fell by the way that withstood him,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'And court her by night and by day.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Joe Hepple, Will Crudders, Tom Liddle,
With twenty or thirty men more,
If I could their names but unriddle,
At least I might make out two score,
That all cast about for to catch her,
And make her their own during life;
With others that strive to debauch her,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'And then the king’s health by the by.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "The Millers Haugh, Heugh Nebb, and Haystack,
The Flowers, the New Close, and Decoy,
With places whose titles I know not,
Where they met to love and enjoy,
Would be but too far a digression,
And make our fond passions rebell;
But, oh! had these places expression,
What pretty love tales they could tell!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'And fully as fit for the horns as the breeks.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "It fell on a day, he may it remember,
Tho’ others rejoyced, yet so did not he,
When tidings was brought that Lisle did surrender,
It grieves me to think on’t, his wife took the gee,
These bitches still itches, and stretches commission,
And if they be crossed they’re still taking peeks,
And Sawney, poor man, he was out of condition,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'While I describe Carstairs.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "But first I must his pardon crave,
For making bold and free,
For William was his christian name,
And shall be so for me;
But manners must to rhymes give place,
Or else we spoil our wares;
And _Will_ and _William’s_ all one case,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'And equal to Carstairs.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "His face is like the midnight moon
And stars that shine so bright;
His nose is like a flaming fire,
That casts both heat and light;
It sparkles like the Syrian seas
When he gets in his airs,
A clown has not an heart to buy", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'A beak like Will Carstairs.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Without a magnifying glass,
His neck you cannot see;
But if you please to let it pass,
It shall be pass’d by me;
His shoulders are compact and strong,
Made up of rounds and squares,
And no small burden e’er could wrong", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'A back like Will Carstairs’.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Down from his shoulder-blades there springs
Two arms both stout and strong,
That flap just like a buzzard’s wings
As he marcheth along;
And from those arms there spring two hands,
Well skill’d in magic airs;
And William Lilley’s charter stands", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'As snod as you like.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "If you do not you’ll hip me,
My sweetheart will slip me,
And if I should smart for’t,
And break my poor heart for’t
Are you not to blame!
But if you’ll oblige me,
As gratitude guides me,
I’ll still be your servant,
Obedient and fervent,
Whilst WHITTLE’S my name.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'You’d let me carry double.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Poor Sandy was with riding daul’d,
He rues he saw their faces,
His back and sides they sorely gaul’d,
He pay’d for their embraces;
But if young Peter’s found her nest,
She’ll rue as well as Sandy;
And if she proves with child, she best", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'E’en where her spark was boarded.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Now whether ’twas for want of beds,
Or whether ’twas cold weather,
Or whether ’twas to measure legs,
That they lay both together;
But as they smuggl’d for a while,
And gave out they were marry’d,
Till she at length did prove with child,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'To get their grandy’s blessing.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "When in her presence they were come,
She rail’d at them like thunder,
For shame, cries she, what have you done,
That’s brought on you this blunder?
She call’d her slut and brazen fac’d,
Instead of kind caressing,
Our family you have disgrac’d,
Can you expect a blessing?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'No fortune he, but worth himself:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "This when her parents understood,
Hoping it would be for her good,
To hinder both their loves intent,
To Stokesley, to an uncle sent;
At parting, many a sigh and tear,
Of love, and truth, thro’ life sincere;
Nor death should part; for from the grave", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'He’d take her to her father dear.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Now when she got him up behind,
They travelled faster then the wind;
That in two hours, or little more,
They came unto her father’s door;
And as they did this great haste make,
He sore complain’d his head did ache;
Her handkerchief she then pull’d out,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Nor rack’d by Derwent’s hospitable lord.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "He stops his tale, involv’d in grief profound;
He sighs, he weeps, and feebly strikes the ground;
Cries, why rehearse these golden days of yore,
Since they to me, to me can be no more!
The clement heart, and curious, often calls", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'High Hezleyhurst, and Low.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "On wand’ring westward through Wardshill,
I there found the first three;
And heard the mass amissing still,
Had march’d towards the Lee;
I hir’d the herd, these to retain,
’Till in pursuit I went,
To bring the others back again,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'And lads league with lasses in mayor Millar’s mart.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Horn’d cattle, and horses, mules, asses, and swine,
And sheep of all kinds kept ’twixt _Tweed_ and the _Tyne_;
A skilful collection of choice Cheviot rams,
And also the best breed of bleak border lambs;
Hard hogs from the _Highlands_, some long, and some short,
And some sightly samples of Leicester sort;
Some _South Downs_, some _Dishleys_, some _Dorsets_, and _Harts_,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'These magnified monsters in mayor Millar’s mart.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "Their dimensions alive, and their density dead,
He measur’d and weigh’d with the eyes of his head,
From the tip of the tongue to the tip of the tail,
In ells and in inches, exact as a scale,
The girt of the sirloin, the centre and crop,
The breadth of the brisket, the bottom and top;
By practice made perfect, precise, and expert,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Surpris’d all the people in mayor Millar’s mart.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "A caravan crowded, came here from the east,
With _Bengal_ bred bipeds, and _Bot’ney Bay_ beasts;
Stage-tumblers, and walkers upon the slack wire,
And dancing dogs deck’d out in harlequin ’tire;
Eke, eight _British_ badgers brought back in a box,
The big and the beautiful _Berwickshire_ ox;
With all tricks by slight hand of nature and art,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Lest you be led astray.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Should you to marry be inclin’d,
I charge you to beware;
And caution you to change your mind,
Thus to escape that snare;
Be not decoy’d by age nor youth,
Whose aims are artful all;
But take my word as standard truth,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'One crop’d strong Samson’s crown.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Reflect that Adam’s innocence,
Was to Eve’s blunder blind;
Whose crafty crime caus’d to commence,
A curse upon mankind;
So you cannot too cautious be,
Of wormwood mix’d with gall;
Then friends pray be advis’d by me,
To wed with _none at all_!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'I wasn’t to starve, though in Limbo.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "Another poor fellow there happen’d to be,
Which they had confined in Limbo;
Brother prisoner, says I, how shall we get free,
For want of this thing called rhino?
The poor fellow sat like one was half dead,
Then I gave him claret to dye his nose red;
But I never knew yet how the reck’ning was paid;", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'For now I have got out of Limbo.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "With many a foul step then I stagger’d home,
And it happen’d to be without falling;
I got on my bed, and nothing I said,
But my wife she began with her bawling;
She rung me such a peal, though she’d been not well,
As if she would have rais’d all the devils in hell,
You might have heard her as far as the sound of Bow Bell;
Then I wish’d that I’d stay’d there in Limbo.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'In ancient Stockton’s commendation.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Upon the stately river Tees,
A goodly castle there was placed,
Nigh joining to the ocean seas,
Whereby our country was much graced;
Affording rich commodities,
With corn and lead, unto our nation;
Which makes me sing with chearful voice,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'In modern Stockton’s commendation.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "O what a scene for joy and laughter,
To see, as light as cork or feather,
Our pond’rous lead, and bulky rafter,
Sail down the smooth canal together!
Whilst coal and lime and cheese and butter,
Shall grace our famous navigation;
And we will make a wond’rous clutter,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'All speak fair Stockton’s commendation.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Fill then your jovial bumpers round,
Join chorus all in Stockton’s glory;
Let us but love our native town,
A fig for patriot, whig, or tory;
Whate’er they say, whate’er they do,
Their aim is but to fleece the nation;
Let us continue firm and true", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Fal lal lal la ral.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Yet ere we part, my comrades say,
Come, Stockhore[74], you’re the poet,
If e’er you pen’d a grateful lay,
’Tis now the time to show it.
Such usage fair in this good town,
We’ve met from age and youth, sirs,
Accept our grateful thanks, and own", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Embody’d to be, without stop or delay.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "What tho’ some cowards have betook them to flight,
And for their king and country scorn for to fight,
Yet we Durham boys, who jovial appear,
Right honest we’ll be, and we’ll banish all fear,
When head of the front, how martial we see", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Our Colonel so brave, so gallant, and free.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Whose generous heart, by experience we know,
Why need we then dread along with him to go?
Then farewell, dear wives, and each kind sweetheart,
Pray do not repine that from you we must part;
But hark! the drums beat, and the fifes sweetly play,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'When in numbers great, them advancing we see.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "If they do, they’re mista’en, we’ll boldly proceed;
And conquer or die, ere ignobly we’ll yield;
Then crowned with laurel, (for vent’ring our lives)
Home then we’ll return to our sweethearts and wives,
What joy will be greater, our fame shall abound,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'The bells then shall ring, and the trumpets shall sound.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "Let each loyal Briton then fill up his glass,
For to drive care away, so round let it pass,
Drink a health to king George, who sits on his throne,
(Whose power the French to their sorrow have known,)
May the Heavens above preserve him from harm,
And ever defend him from foreign alarm.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'In the Lass of Cockerton.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Now would the Gods but deign to hear,
An artless lover’s prayer;
This lovely nymph ’bove all I’d ask,
And scorn each other care;
True happiness I’d then possess,
Her love to share alone;
No mortals know what pleasures flow,
With the lass of Cockerton.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Are roaring company.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Come, landlady, fill us a bumper,
And take no thought for the shot,
It’s a sin, as I hope to be saved,
To part with an empty pot;
Let the glass go merrily round,
Our business is jolly to be,
And the wanton lasses of Sedgfield", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'The patriot, the loyal, the brave Volunteer.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Let the foes of old England unite to enslave
Her free bands, from whose fury so oft they have fled;
We’ll prove, by their ruin who escape the wild wave,
We can fight like our sires, who at Agincourt bled;
Their great deeds we’ll review,
And example pursue,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Our country, our laws, march each brave Volunteer.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Vain boasting Monsieur always lower’d his proud flag,
Whenever he met our bold tars on the sea;
And of conquest on shore let the Corsican brag;
Here the length of their graves their sole conquest shall be!
Let them vapour and threat,
Boast their armies so great,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'The last are only in your breast included:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "Subjects’ griefs known, are ne’er from you secluded;
From your most gracious grant we therefore pray,
That the fair sunshine of your brightest day,
Would smile upon your city, whose clear beams
Exhale the troubles of our former streams;
Let not, O Powerful Prince, our ancient state,
For one man’s will, to be depopulate!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'But oh! he’s far over the sea, O.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Should he fall by commotion,
Or sink in the ocean,
(May sick tidings ne’er come to the _Key_, O)
I could ne’er mair be glad,
For the loss of my lad
Wad break my poor heart, and I’d _dee_, O!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Blind Willy’s to play on the fiddle.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "And there’ll be pies and spice dumplings, and there’ll be bacon and peas;
Besides a great lump of beef boiled, and they may get crowdies who
please:
To eat such good things as these are, I’m sure ye’ve but seldom the luck;
Beside, for to make us some pottage, there’ll be a sheep’s head and a
pluck.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Prolonging these pastimes the space of three days.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "The stewards instructed the cash to collect,
Kept debtor and creditor scrolls quite correct;
To purchase such prizes as were preconcerted,
The coin was with consummate caution converted;
To furnish out fun for friends, strangers, and neighbours,
These gents to gymnastics gave gratis their labours;
Lest fair play, by precepts, might not be promoted,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'To run, gape, or grin for, as candidates choose.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "With multitudes mingled the turf was attended,
Like barley and beans, there the belles and beaux blended;
From town and the country such numbers assembled,
The race-ground a Newcastle meeting resembled;
Which cohorts all creeds and conditions comprised,
And dresses, distinctions, and deserts disguised;
By vintners made vivid, their views became various,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'But saw in the sequel their rotten reliance.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "By bribing that brigand, this son of deception
Receiv’d ready rhino, yet made his election;
This presto, his pupils to peasants prefer’d;
In bilking his brethren, the eft would have err’d!
To gull’d speculators, a vulcan as vile,
Stak’d too with turf-students in tangible style,
Till duped delinquents were doom’d through the day,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Their debts of dishonour on peril to pay.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Corruption creeps into both commerce and courts,
Then who can repel it from rural resorts?
As all public places are pester’d with prowlers,
The streets are stagnated with stigmatiz’d strollers;
And some sanguine swindlers, though subtile and snug,
Plunge into the pit they for others had dug;
The same at Monkseaton, the mass must admit,
(With self-satisfaction) “_The biters were bit_”!!!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Ceaseless strives a cruel race.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Youth forlorn! tho’ crowds deride thee,
Gentle minds for thee must grieve;
Back to _reason_, wish to guide thee,
And thy ev’ry want relieve,
O from this sad state to snatch thee,
Why delay the _good_ and _kind_?
_Pity_ calls them on to watch thee,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'Te them hus i’ th’ north were but ninnies.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "But aw fand ma sel blonk’d when to Lunnun I gat,
The folks they a’ luck’d wishy washy;
For gould ye may howk ’till ye’re blind as a bat,
For their streets are like wors--brave and blashy!
’Bout Lunnun then, div’nt ye mak sic a rout,
There’s nouse there ma winkers to dazzle,
For a’ the fine things ye are gobbin about,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'And built ’gain and again.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "The streets are now so num’rous grown,[81]
E’en Gothamites don’t know them;
So signs they’ve painted ’gainst the walls,
In every nook to shew them.[82]
And such the rage, for naming streets,
That gaps made in th’ Old Wall;
They Heron Street and Forster Street,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/53156'),
    array('title' => 'The strength of Plot to write in verse and prose:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Whose easie Pegassus will amble ore
Some threescore miles of Fancy in an houre;
Cloud-grapling _Chapman_, whose Aerial minde
Soares at Philosophy, and strikes it blinde;
_Danbourn_ [_Dabourn_] I had forgot, and let it be,
He dy’d Amphibion by the Ministry;
_Silvester_, _Bartas_, whose translatique part", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Twinn’d, or was elder to our Laureat:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Divine composing _Quarles_, whose lines aspire
The April of all Poesy in May, [_Tho. May._]
Who makes our English speak _Pharsalia_;
_Sands_ metamorphos’d so into another [_Sandys_]
We know not _Sands_ and _Ovid_ from each other;
He that so well on _Scotus_ play’d the Man,
The famous _Diggs_, or _Leonard Claudian_;
The pithy _Daniel_, whose salt lines afford
A weighty sentence in each little word;
Heroick _Draiton_, _Withers_, smart in Rime,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'And sent him born with bayes upon his head:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Deep in a dump _Iohn Ford_ alone was got
With folded armes and melancholly hat;
The squibbing _Middleton_, and _Haywood_ sage,
Th’ Apologetick Atlas of the Stage;
Well of the Golden age he could intreat,
But little of the Mettal he could get;
Three-score sweet Babes he fashion’d from the lump,
For he was Christ’ned in _Parnassus_ pump;
The Muses Gossip to _Aurora’s_ bed,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'You’d think his clothes were pinn’d upon his back.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Ballads', 'lyrics' => "The whole frame hung with pins, to mend which clothes,
In mirth they sent him to old Father Prose;
Of these sad Poets this way ran the stream,
And _Decker_ followed after in a dream;
_Rounce_, _Robble_, _Hobble_, he that writ so high big[;]
Basse for a Ballad, _John Shank_ for a Jig: [_Wm. Basse._]
Sent by _Ben Jonson_, as some Authors say,
_Broom_ went before and kindly swept the way:
Old _Chaucer_ welcomes them unto the Green,
And _Spencer_ brings them to the fairy Queen;
The finger they present, and she in grace
Transform’d it to a May-pole, ’bout which trace
Her skipping servants, that do nightly sing,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Thou saidst, and seald’st it with a kisse.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Oh heavens! and could so soon that tye
Relent in sad apostacy?
Could all thy Oaths and mortgag’d trust,
Banish like Letters form’d in dust, [? vanish]
Which the next wind scatters? take heed,
Take heed Revolter; know this deed
Hath wrong’d the world, which will fare worse", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'By thy example, than thy curse.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Hide that false brow in mists; thy shame
Ne’re see light more, but the dimme flame
Of Funerall-lamps; thus sit and moane,
And learn to keep thy guilt at home;
Give it no vent, for if agen
Thy love or vowes betray more men,
At length I feare thy perjur’d breath", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => '_SONNET._', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Shall I think because some clouds
The beauty of my Mistris shrouds,
To look after another Star?
Those to _Cynthia_ servants are;
May the stars when I doe sue,
In their anger shoot me through;
Shall I shrink at stormes of rain,
Or be driven back again,
Or ignoble like a worm,
Be a slave unto a storm?
Pity he should ever tast
The Spring that feareth Winters blast;
Fortune and Malice then combine,
Spight of either I am thine;
And to be sure keep thou my heart,
And let them wound my worser part,
Which could they kill, yet should I bee", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'No girdle serv’d lesse than the zodiack:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "So thick a Giant, that he now was come
To be accounted an eighth hill in _Rome_,
And as the learn’d _Tostatus_ kept his age,
Writing for every day he liv’d a page;
So he no lesse voluminous then that", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'If as increase, he could, too, multiply.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Oh how I tremble lest the tender maid
Should dye like a young infant over-laid!
For when this Chaos would pretend to move
And arch his back for the strong act of Love,
He fals as soon orethrown with his own weight,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'This Bull with his _Pasiphae_ might plow.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Have you those artificial torments known,
With which long sunken Galeos are thrown
Again on Sea, or the dead Galia
Was rais’d that once behinde St. _Peters_ lay:
By the same rules he this same engine made,
With silken cords in nimble pullies laid;
And when his Genius prompteth his slow part", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'To works of Nature, which he helps with Art:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "First he intangles in those woven bands,
His groveling weight, and ready to commands,
The sworn Prinadas of his bed, the Aids
Of Loves Camp, necessary Chambermaids;
Each runs to her known tackling, hasts to hoyse,
And in just distance of the urging voyce,
Exhorts the labour till he smiling rise", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Though for his bulk, more that sea-monster like.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Mean time the Nurse, who as the most discreet,
Stood governing the motions at the feet,
And ballanc’d his descent, lest that amisse
He fell too fast, or that way more than this;
Steeres the Prow of the pensile Gallease,
Right on Loves Harbour the Nymph lets him pass
Over the Chains, & ’tween the double Fort", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'I hope may give like Priests, which is to blesse.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "And sure in elder times the Poets were
Those Priests that told men how to hope and feare,
Though they most sensually did write and live,
Yet taught those blessings, which the Gods did give,
But you (my King) have purify’d our flame,
Made wit our virtue which was once our shame;
For by your own quick fires you made ours last,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'And dreames of delight.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "His pot and his tost in the morning he takes,
And all the day long good musick he makes;
He wanders up and down to Wakes & to Fairs,
He casts his cap, and casts his cap at the Court and its cares;
And when to the town the Tinker doth come,
Oh, how the wanton wenches run,
Some bring him basons, and some bring him bowles,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'There’s his other Deity.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "This too shewes him deeply wise,
To dwell there he left the skies;
So pure a black could _Phœbus_ burn,
He himself would _Negro_ turn,
And for such a dresse would slight
His gorgeous attire of light;
Eclipses he would count a blisse,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'And love no other, till he sees a better:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "So may the new year crown the old yeares joy,
By giving us a Girle unto our Boy;
I’ th’ one the Fathers wit, and in the other
Let us admire the beauty of the Mother,
That so we may their severall pictures see,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'To see his own shape dance in both your eyes.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Sweet Babe! my prayer shall end with thee,
(Oh may it prove a Prophecy!)
May all the channels in thy veynes
Expresse the severall noble straines,
From whence they flow; sweet _Sydney’s_ wit,
But not the sad, sweet fate of it;
The last great _Pembroke’s_ learning, sage
_Burleigh’s_ both wisdome and his age;
Thy Grandsires honest heart expresse", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'My Hostess daughter has her place.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "The maids sit up, and watch their turnes,
If I stay long the Tapster mourns;
The Cook-maid has no mind to sin,
Though tempted by the Chamberlin;
But when I knock, O how they bustle;
The hostler yawns, the geldings justle;
If maid be sleep, oh how they curse her!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'In the Fruition, as Desire.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "When I have got the fruit of pain,
Possession makes me poore again,
Expected formes and shapes unknown,
Whet and make sharp tentation;
Sense is too niggardly for Bliss,
And payes me dully with what is;
But fancy’s liberall, and gives all
That can within her vastnesse fall;
Vaile therefore still, while I divine
The Treasure of this hidden Mine,
And make Imagination tell", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'And lift the truth as with a Leaver.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "The Shark I do scorn, that’s only well born,
And brags of his antient house,
Yet his birth cannot fit, with money nor wit,
But feeds on his friends like a Louse,
That man I more prize, that by vertue doth rise
Unto some worthy degree,
That by breeding hath got, what by birth he had not,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Then she’s onely mine.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "To the Platonick that applies
His clear addresses onely to the mind;
The body but a Temple signifies,
Wherein the Saints inshrin’d,
To him it is all one,
Whether the walls be marble, or rough stone;
Nay, in holy places, which old time defaces,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'But I am dead, and cannot do.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Call for the best, the house will ring,
Sack, White and Claret, let them bring,
And drink apace, whilst breath you have,
You’l find but cold drinking in the grave;
Partridge, Plover for your dinner,
And a Capon for the sinner,
You shall finde ready when you are up,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Sing _Hony soitt qui Mal y pense_.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "To speak of the Monarchy, it were two Long to tell;
And likewise of the _Romans_, how far they did excel,
_Hannibal_ and _Scipio_, they many a field did fight;
_Orlando Furioso_ he was a valiant Knight;
_Romulus_ and _Rhemus_ were those that ROME did build,
But St. _George_, St. _George_, the Dragon he hath kill’d;
St. _George_ he was, _&c._", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Sing _Hony soit qui mal y pense_.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "_Ottoman_, the _Tartar_, _Cham_ of _Persia’s_ race,
The great _Mogul_, with his Chests so full of all his Cloves and Mace,
The _Grecian_ youth _Bucephalus_ he manly did bestride,
But those with all their Worthies Nine, St. _George_ did them deride,
_Gustavus Adolphus_ was _Swedelands_ Warlike King,
But St. _George_, St. _George_, pull’d forth the Dragon’s sting.
St. _George_ he was for _England_, St. _Dennis_ was for _France_,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'As fourteen pot of Perry.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "’Tis true, was wear him Sherkin freize,
But what is that? we have store of seize, [_i.e._ cheese,]
And Got is plenty of Goats milk
That[,] sell him well[,] will buy him silk
Inough, to make him fine to quarrell
At _Herford_ Sizes in new apparrell;
And get him as much green Melmet perhap,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'This pot had been a temple fit.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "Well then Companions is’t not fit,
Since to this Jemme we ow[e] our wit,
That we should praise the Cabonet,
And drink a health to this divine,
And bounteous pallace of our wine[?]:
Die he with thirst that doth repine!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'CHORUS.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "_Come, fill’s a cup of sherry, and let us be merry,_
_There shall nought but pure wine_
_Make us love-sick or pine,_
_Wee’l hug the cup and kisse it, we’l sigh when ere we misse it;_
_For tis that, that makes us jolly,_
_And sing hy trololey lolly._", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'And for to strengthen the back:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "Tis Wine that makes the thoughts aspire,
And fills the body with heat;
Besides ’tis good, if well understood [p. 69.]
To fit a man for the feat;
_Then call, and drink up all,_
_The drawer is ready to fill:_
_Pox take care, what need we to spare,_
_My Father has made his will._", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'And many a good fellow wants mon[e]y to spend.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "If thou wilt borrow
Come hither to morrow
I dare not part so soon with my friend[.]
But let us be merry, and drink of our sherry,
But to part with my mon[e]y I do not intend[.]
Then a t—d in thy teeth, and an old house end.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Your sad tires in a mile-a.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Your paltry mony bags of Gold,
What need have we to stare-for,
When little or nothing soon is told,
And we have the less to care-for?
Cast care away, let sorrow cease, [p. 74.]
A Figg for Melancholly;
Let’s laugh and sing, or if you please,
We’l frolick with sweet _Dolly_.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'But merrily passe the time away:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "They are mad that are sad;
Be rul’d, by me,
And none shall be so merry as we;
The Kitchin shall catch cold no more,
And we’l have no key to the Buttery dore,
The fidlers shall sing,
And the house shall ring,
And the world shall see
What a merry couple,
Merry couple,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'A greater sting than his.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "3. But chaste _Camilla’s_ vertuous fear
Was of a noble kind,
Not of her end approaching near
But to be left behind,
From her dear Love disjoyn’d;
When Death in courtesie decreed,
To make the fair his prize,
And by one cruelty her freed", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Of what we are forbid to know.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Fond humane nature that will try [p. 118.]
To sound th’ Abiss of Destiny!
Alas! what profit can arise
From those forbidden scrutinies,
When Oracles what they foretel
In such Ænigma’s still conceal,
That self indulging man still makes
Of deepest truths most sad mistakes!
Or could our frailty comprehend", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'But providence that governs all.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Reason wherewith kind Heav’n has blest
His creature man above the rest,
Will teach humanity to know
All that it should aspire unto;
And whatsoever fool relies
On false deceiving prophesies,
Striving by conduct to evade
The harms they threaten, or perswade,
Too frequently himself does run [p. 119.]
Into the danger he would shun,
And pulls upon himself the woe", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'His coming out they waited.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Then forth he came as one half lame,
All very faint and tired,
Betwixt her legs he hung his head,
As heavy heart desired;
My dogs then being refresht again,
And she of sleep bereaved,
She dreamt she had me in her arms,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'His colour shew’d he lov’d it:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "But _Dick_ his Son, as he were none,
Gav’t off, and hath reprov’d it;
But that his foes made bridge of’s nose,
And cry’d him down for a Protector,
Proving him to be a fool that would undertake to rule", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'And not drink and fight like _Hector_.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "The Grecian lad he drank like mad, [p. 13.]
Minding no work above it;
And _Sans question_ kill’d _Ephestion_
Because he’d not approve it;
He got command where God had land,
And like a _Maudlin_ Yonker,
When he tippled all and wept, he laid him down to sleep,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'She modestly answer’d to _Hockley-i’th’-hole_.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "I ask’d her her business; she had a red cheek,
She told me, she went a poor service to seek;
I said, it was pitty she should leave the City,
And settle her self in a Country Town;
She said it was certain it was her hard fortune", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'To go up a maiden, and so to come down.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "With that I alighted, and to her I stept,
I took her by th’ hand, and this pretty maid wept;
Sweet[,] weep not, quoth I: I kist her soft lip;
I wrung her by th’ hand, and my finger she nipt;
So long there I woo’d her, such reasons I shew’d her,
That she my speeches could not controul,
But cursied finely, and got up behind me,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'And back she rode with me to _Hockley-i’-th’-hole_.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "When I came to _Hockley_ at the sign of the Cock,
By [a]lighting I chanced to see her white smock,
It lay so alluring upon her round knee,
I call’d for a Chamber immediately;
I hugg’d her, I tugg’d her, I kist her, I smugg’d her,
And gently I laid her down on a bed,
With nodding and pinking, with sighing & winking,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'She told me a tale of her Maidenhead.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "While she to me this story did tell,
I could not forbear, but on her I fell;
I tasted the pleasure of sweetest delight, [p. 16.]
We took up our lodging, and lay there all night;
With soft arms she roul’d me, and oft times told me,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'A little o’ th’ t’on with t’other.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Who bids a Guest unto a feast,
To sit by divers dishes,
They please their mind untill they find
Change, please each Creatures wishes;
With beak and bill I have my fill,
With measure running over;
The Lovers dish now do I wish,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'O nay, O nay not yet.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Gold and silver is but dross, [p. 33.]
And worldly vanity;
There’s nothing I esteem so much
As my Virginity;
What do you think I am so loose, [_al. lect._, mad]
And of so little wit,
As for to lose my maidenhead?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'And he comes presently.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "A bird that can but catch a Fly,
Or prate to please his Majesty, [_al. lect._, doth please]
It’s known to every one;
The Duke _De Guise_ gave him a Parrot, [p. 67.]
And he had twenty Cannons for it", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'The Act against Fornication.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "The Country Dame, that loves the old sport,
Or delights in a new invention,
May be fitted here, if they please to repair
To this high ranting Convention;
If you are weary of your Coyn,
Or of your Chastity,
Here is costly toyes, or hot-metled boyes,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'That will ease you presently.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Both curious heads and wanton tailes
May here have satisfaction;
Here is all kind of ware, that useful are
For pride or provocation;
Here’s Drugs to paint, or Powder to perfume,
Or Ribbon of the best fashion;
Here’s dainty meat will fit you for the feat", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Beyond all expectation.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Here’s curious patches to set out your faces, [p. 89.]
And make you resemble the sky;
Or here’s looking-glasses to shew the poor Asses,
Your Husbands, their destiny;
Here’s bawbles too to play withall,
And some to stand in stead;
This place doth afford both for your brow,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'And stallions for your head.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Old Ladies here may be reliev’d,
If Ushers they do lack,
Or if they’ll not discharge their husbands at large,
But grow foundred in the back;
Green visag’d Damsels, that are sick
Of a troubled Maidenhead,
May here, if they please, be cur’d of the disease
And their green colours turn’d to red.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'To come that very day.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "When he before the Lady came, [? verse 6. p. 137.]
Disguised stood he there,
He blinked blithly, and did say,
God save you Mistris fair;
Thou’rt welcome, Tinker, unto me,
Thou seem’st a man of skill,
All broken Vessels for to mend,
Though they be ne’er so ill;
I am the best man of my Trade,
Quoth he, in all this Town,
For any Kettle, Pot, or Pan,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Which I am fain to spend.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "The Lady to her Coffer went,
And took a hundred Mark,
And gave the Tinker for his pains,
That did so well his work;
Tinker, said she, take here thy fee,
Sith here you’ll not remain,
But I must have my Cauldron now", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Take here a yearly Pension.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "And ev’ry quarter of the year
Our Cauldron thou shalt view;
Nay, by my faith, her Lord gan say, [p. 139.]
I’d rather buy a new;
Then did the Tinker take his leave
Both of the Lord and Lady,
And said, such work as I can do,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'To give her some Tobacco.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "You —— gamesters must be bound, [p. 23.]
Tobacco, Tobacco,
Their bullets must be plump and round,
Tobacco, Tobacco,
Your Stopper must be stiff and strong,
Your Pipe it must be large and long,
Or else she’ll say you do her wrong,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'In giving her Tobacco.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "And if you do not do her right,
Tobacco, Tobacco,
She’ll take a course to burn your Pipe,
Tobacco, Tobacco,
And if you ask what she doth mean,
She’ll say she doth’t to make it clean,
Then take you heed of such a Quean
For spoyling your Tobacco,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Knight of great _Diana’s_ Order.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "_Luna_ was no venial sinner,
Yet she hath a man within her,
And to cut off Cuckolds scorns,
She decks her head with Silver horns
And if the moon in heaven[’]s thus drest,
The men on earth like it are blest.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Now call’d a Church unspotted pure.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "There Milk from Springs, like Rivers, flows,
And Honey upon hawthorn grows;
Hemp, Wool, and Flax, there grows on trees,
The mould is fat, it cuts like cheese;
All fruits and herbs spring in the fields,
Tobacco it good plenty yields;
And there shall be a Church most pure,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Where you may find salvation sure.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "There’s Venison of all sorts great store,
Both Stag, and buck, wild Goat, and Boar,
And all so tame, that you with ease
May take your fill, eat what you please;
There’s Beavers plenty, yea, so many,
That you may buy two skins a penny,
Above all this, a Church most pure,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Where to be saved you may be sure.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "There’s flight of Fowl do cloud the skie,
Great Turkies of threescore pound weight,
As big as Estriges, there Geese, [p. 104.]
With thanks, are sold for pence a piece;
Of Duck and Mallard, Widgeon, Teale,
Twenty for two-pence make a meale;
Yea, and a Church unspotted pure,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'From dregs of Papistry secure.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "No Feasts nor festival set daies
Are here observed, the Lord be prais’d,
Though not in Churches rich and strong,
Yet where no Mass was ever Sung,
The Bulls of _Bashan_ ne’r met there[;]
_Surplice_ and _Cope_ durst not appear;
Old Orders all they will abjure,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'This Church hath all things new and pure.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "No discipline shall there be used, [p. 105.]
The Law of Nature they have chused[;]
All that the spirit seems to move
Each man may choose and so approve,
There’s Government without command,
There’s unity without a band;
A Synagogue unspotted pure,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Where lust and pleasure dwells secure.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Loe in this Church all shall be free
To Enjoy their Christian liberty;
All things made common, void of strife,
Each man may take anothers wife,
And keep a hundred maids, if need,
To multiply, increase, and breed,
Then is not this Foundation sure,
To build a Church unspotted, pure?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Her Fugitives and Runnagates:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Let Bedlam, Newgate, and the Clink
Disgorge themselves into this sink;
Let Bridewell and the stews be kept,
And all sent thither to be swept;
So may our Church be cleans’d and pure,
Keep both it self and state secure.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'And amongst the jovial Crew.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "I prethee leave thy scorning,
Which our true love beguiles,
Thy eyes are bright as morning,
The Sun shines in thy smiles,
Thy gesture is so prudent,
Thy language is so free,
That he is the best Student
Which can study thee;
With hey ho, _&c._", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'But that she’s a devillish backbiter.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "With Souldiers she’s often comraded
And often does them much good,
She’l save them the charge of a Surgeon
In sickness for letting them blood;
Corruption she draws like a horse-leech, [p. 150.]
Growing she’ll prove a great breeder,
At night she will creep in her cottage,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'She’s prest to death by the naile.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "She doth not esteem of your rich men,
But alwaies sticks close to the poor;
Nor she cares not for your clean shifters,
Nor for such as brave cloaths wear;
She loves all such as are non-suited,
Or any brave fellow that lacks;
She’s as true a friend to poor Souldiers,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'FAME.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "_Encreasing, as in waters we descrie_
_The circles small, of nothing that begun,_
_Which, at the length, unto such breadth do come,_
_That of a drop, which from the skies doth fall,_
_The circles spread, and hide the waters all:_
_So Fame, in flight encreasing more and more;_
_For, at the first, she is not scarcely knowne,_
_But by and by she fleets from shore to shore,_
_To clouds from th’ earth her stature straight is growne._
_There whatsoever by her trumpe is blowne,_]", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Drayton sings:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "_Next MARLOW, bathed in the ~Thespian~ springs,_
_Had in him those brave translunary things_
_That the first poets had, his raptures were_
_All air and fire, which made his verses clear;_
_For that fine madness still he did retain,_
_Which rightly should possess a poet’s brain._", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Daniel, Drayton, Shakespeare, Beaumont, and Donne:—', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "_I am not bound to honour antique names,_ [8th verse]
_Nor am I led by other men to chuse_
_Any thing worthy, which my judgment blames;_
_Heare better straines, though by a later Muse;_
_The sweet ~Arcadian~ singer first did raise_
_Our Language current, and deserv’d his Baies._", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'I love thee, and it is my love that speaks;—', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "There are a sort of men, whose visages
Do cream and mantle like a standing pond,
And do a wilful stillness entertain,
With purpose to be dress’d in an opinion
Of wisdom, gravity, profound conceit;
As who should say, ‘I am Sir Oracle,
And, when I ope my lips, let no dog bark!’”", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Written before 1659, thus:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "_Come, come away, to the Tavern, I say,_
_Whilst we have time and leisure for to think;_
_I find our State lyes tottering of late,_
_And that e’re long we sha’n’t have time to drink._
Then here’s a health to thee, to thee and me,
To me and thee, to thee and me, _&c._", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'The Devonshire Damsels’ Frollick.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Being an Account of nine or ten fair Maidens, who went one
Evening lately, to wash themselves in a pleasant River, where
they were discovered by several Young Men being their familiar
Acquaintances, who took away their Gowns and Petticoats, with
their Smocks and Wine and good Chear; leaving them a while in
a most melancholly condition.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Lute-strings, Cat-eaten,” we read:—', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "_Puss, I will curse thee, maist thou dwell_
_With some dry Hermit in a Cel,_
_Where Rat ne’re peep’d, where Mouse ne’er fed,_
_And Flies go supperlesse to bed:_
_Or with some close par’d Brother, where_
_Thou’lt fast each Sabbath in the yeare,_
_Or else, profane, be hang’d on Monday,_
_For butchering a Mouse on Sunday_, &c.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'John Taylor, the Water-Poet, so early as 1620, writes of a Brownist:—', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "_The Spirit still directs him how to pray,_
_Nor will he dress his meat the Sabbath day,_
_Which doth a mighty mystery unfold;_
_His zeale is hot, although his meat be cold._
_Suppose his Cat on Sunday kill’d a rat,_
_She on the Monday must be hang’d for that._", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Winstanley had published “A Farewell to Tobacco,” beginning:—', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "_Farewell thou Indian smoake, Barbarian vapour,_
_Enemy unto life, foe to waste paper,_
_Thou dost diseases in thy body breed,_
_And like a Vultur on the purse doth feed._
_Changing sweet breaths into a stinking loathing,_
_And with 3 pipes turnes two pence into nothing;_
_Grim ~Pluto~ first invented it, I think,_
_To poison all the world with hellish stink_, &c.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'And _Winifred_ of _Madly_.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "As _Arthur_ upon a day
Met _Winifred_ on the way,
He took her by the hand,
Desiring her to stand,
Saying I must to thee recite
A matter of [great] weight,
Of Love, that conquers Kings,
In grieved hearts so rings,
And if thou dost love thy Mother,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'And broke them of their talk.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "I tell you Dame, quoth he,
I can have as good as thee;
For when death my father did call,
He then did leave me all
His barrels and his brooms,
And a dozen of wo[o]den spoones,
Dishes six or seven,
Besides an old spade, even
A brasse pot and whimble,
A pack-needle and thimble,
A pudding prick and reele,
And my mothers own sitting wheele;
And also there fell to my lot", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'To the match I will agree.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "For [when] death doth me call,
I then will leave her all;
For I have an earthen flaggon,
Besides a three-quart noggin,
With spickets and fossets five,
Besides an old bee-hive;
A wooden ladle and maile,
And a goodly old clouting paile;
Of a chaff bed I am well sped,
And there the Bride shall be wed,
And every night shall wear
A bolster stufft with haire,
A blanket for the Bride,
And a winding sheet beside,
And hemp, if he will it break, [p. 85.]", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'That either of them should be out.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "And when that they were wed,
And each of them well sped,
The Bridegroom home he ran,
And after him his man, [p. 86.]
And after him the Bride,
Full joyfull at the tyde,
As she was plac’d betwixt
Two yeomen of the Guests,
And he was neat and fine,
For he thought him at that time
Sufficient in every thing,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'Wither’s name being earliest on the roll of Jurymen summoned:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "“_Hee, who was called first in all the List,_
_~George Withers~ hight, entitled Satyrist;_
_Then ~Cary~, ~May~, and ~Davenant~ were called forth,_
_Renowned Poets all, and men of worth,_
_If wit may passe for worth: Then ~Sylvester~,_
_~Sands~, ~Drayton~, ~Beaumont~, ~Fletcher~, ~Massinger~,_
_~Shakespeare~, and ~Heywood~, Poets good and free,_
_Dramatick writers all, but the first three:_
_These were empanell’d all, and being sworne_
_A just and perfect verdict to return_,” _&c._ (p. 9.)", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/60454'),
    array('title' => 'With lather she whitens them up to the eyes.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "No sooner the razor is laid on the face, sir,
Than painful distortions take place on the brow;
But if they complain, sir, they'll find it in vain, sir,
She'll tell them, 'there's nought but what _Patience_ can do:'
And as she scrapes round 'em, if she by chance wound 'em,
They'll cry out, as tho' she'd bereav'd them of life,
'Od smash your brains, woman! aw find the blood's comin,
Aw'd rather been shav'd with an aud gully knife!'", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Iv Jemmy Joneson\'s Whurry.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Tyneside seem'd clad wiv bonny ha's,
An' furnaces sae dunny;
Wey this mun be what Bible ca's,
'The land of milk and honey!'
If a' thor things belang'd tiv me,
Aw'd myek the poor reet murry,
An' gar each heart to sing wiv glee,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Blind Willy\'s to play on the fiddle.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "And there will be pies and spice dumplings,
And there will be bacon and peas;
Besides a great lump of beef boiled,
And they may get crowdies who please;
To eat of such good things as these are,
I'm shure you've but seldom the luck;
Besides for to make us some pottage,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'All waiting gaping to see my Lord \'Size.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Oft stretch'd were their necks, oft erected their ears,
Still fancying they heard of the trumpets the sound,
When tidings arriv'd, which dissolv'd them in tears,
That my Lord at the dead-house was then lying drown'd!
Straight left _tete a tete_ were the jailor and thief;
The horror-struck crowd to the dead-house quick hies;
Ev'n the lawyers, forgetful of fee and of brief,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Now his narrative ended--the Butler retir\'d.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Whilst Betty Watt mutt'ring (half drunk) thro' her teeth,
Declar'd, 'In her breest greet consarn it inspir'd,
That my Lord should sae cullishly come by his deeth.'
Next a keelman was call'd on, Bold Archy his name,
Who the book as he kiss d shew'd the whites of his eyes,
Then he cut an odd caper, attention to claim,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'And sell things in a huikstery way.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "And to get us a canny bit leevin,
A' kinds o' fine sweetmeats we'll sell,
Reed herrin, broon syep, and mint candy,
Black pepper, dye sand, and sma' yell;
Spice hunters, pick shafts, farden candles,
Wax dollies, wi' reed leather shoes,
Chalk pussy-cats, fine curly greens,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'We\'ll suin wesh a\' wor faces.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "There's ne'er a lad iv Percy Main
Be bet this day for five or ten;
Wor pockets lin'd wiv notes and cash,
Amang the cheps we'll cut a dash;
For X Y Z, that bonny steed,
He bangs them a' for pith and speed,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'To stand upon a cart, man:', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "The bets flew round frae side to side;
'The field agyen X Y!' they cried:
We'd hardly time to lay them a',
When in he cam--Hurraw! hurraw!
'Gad smash!' says aw, 'X Y's the steed,
He bangs them a' for pith an' speed,
We never see'd the like, man!'", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Rum te idity, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Then rising, aw went maw ways hyem,
Aw knock'd at the door, and cry'd Jenny!
Says she, Canny man, is te lyem,
Or been wading in Tyne, maw hinny?
I' troth, she was like for to dee,
And just by the way to relieve her,
The water's been wading through me,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Whack row de dow, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "He cries, My lads, you're qualified
To do such wond'rous feats,
That to Shields and Cleadon you must go,
To clear the lanes and streets;
Destroy all those who may oppose
The ships from sailing down the river,
And then our Prince will sure commend", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Tol lol de rol, de rol de rol.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Then to parade the Pitmen went,
Wi' hearts byeth stout an' strang, man;
Gad smash the French! we are sae strang,
We'll shoot them every one, man!
Gad smash me sark! if aw wad stick
To tumble them a' down the pit,
As fast as aw could thraw a coal,
Aw'd tumble them a' doon the hole,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'The thowt, by my jinkers! was funny.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "A chep wiv a fyece like a poor country bumpkin,
Sed he heurd, but may hap tisent true,
That the thing whilk they saw was a great silken pumpkin
By me eye, what a lilly-ba-loo!
Another said, Sadler (for that is the nyem
O' the man) may pay dear for his frolic,
When he's up iv the clouds (a stree for his fame!)", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'And sair the drums they\'re skelpin.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Fareweel, maw comely! aw mun gang
The Gen'ral's een to dazzle!
But, hinny! if the time seems lang,
An' thou freets about me neet and day;
Then come away,
Seek out the yell-house where aw stay,
An' we'll kiss and cuddle;
An' mony a fuddle
Sall drive the langsome hours away,
When sowgering at Newcassel.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'An\' we jigg\'d it up sae hearty, O.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Wi' mony a shiver,
An' lowp sae cliver,
Can Newcassel turn out sic a party, O?
When, wheit dyun ower, the fiddlers went,
We stagger'd a hint sae merry, O;
An thro' wor toon, till fairly spent,
Roar'd--Crowley's Crew an' glory, O!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Rum ti iddity, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "A Skipper he cam in yen day,
He coudent help luiking at Jackey,
On the coonter his money did lay,
Saying, 'Please, sir, an ounce of rag backey!'
His money Jack popt in the till,
The Skipper kept luiking at him,
A' the time on his seat he sat still,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'If she\'d awn just quarter as much.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Mister Government mun hae greet credit,
Or he ne'er wad get intiv debt;
But they tell yen he hez sike a spirit,
Aw's fish that comes intiv his net,
Says Dick, If aw wanted a shillin,
Want, then, yor certain aw must;
For, if yen was ever sae willin,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'And trump wors, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "How wad we grieve to see, Mr. Mayor, Mr. Mayor,
The grass grow on the Kee, Mr. Mayor?
So get the weighty prayers
Of the porters in the chares,
And the wives that sell the wares, Mr. Mayor, Mr. Mayor.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'He\'ll tell them, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "If the Sheels folk get the day, Mr. Mayor, Mr. Mayor,
Ah what will Eldon say, Mr. Mayor?
If he has time to spare,
He'll surely blast their prayer,
For the luve of his calf Chare, Mr. Mayor, Mr. Mayor.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'For the luve, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Then just dee a' ye can, Mr. Mayor, Mr. Mayor,
And follow up the plan, Mr. Mayor,
Else, faicks, ye'll get a spur
In your Corporation fur,
And ye'll plant at Shields wor BURR!!! Mr. Mayor, Mr. Mayor,
And ye'll plant at Sheels wor BURR!!! Mr. Mayor.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'For lettin the ships up the watter--', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "That brought ower the Cholera frev its awn hyem,
And some says that myed little matter;
But as woman's the root of all evil, ye see,
(At least, all my life aw hev thought it,)
Aw rather believe, as it's been tell'd to me,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Let them haud, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "But the Squire, canny man, he's gyen frae the toon,
And aw'm sure on't the poor sairly miss him;
For oft as aw wauk Pearson's Raw up and doon,
Aw hear the folk cry, Heaven bliss him!
Yet aw hope, an' aw trust, he'll suen find his way hyem,
And aw's sure aw'll be glad to hear tell on't;
For aw've varry oft thowt--did ye ne'er think the syem,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'A unicorn, or star, man.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Ye see, aw thowt they were to sell;
So ax'd the chep, if he cud tell,
What he wad tyek for C and L,
To nail upon maw hen hoose;
But he insisted, smash his crop!
Aw'd like a fule mistyen the shop;
And bad me quickly off te hop,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'He\'d bowt them for his awn use.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "He flang maw hump sae out o' joint,
Sae, smash! aw thowt aw'd hev a pint!
But when aw gat te Peterpoint,
The chep that sells the candy,
The folks luik'd in wiv greedy wish,
He'd bonny siller in a dish;
And just abuin, twee bits o' fish", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'For fear, when at the Races, O.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "The one was lyem'd abuin the knee,
The other freeten'd desp'rately;
\"This demm'd unlucky job!\" says she,
\"Has fairly spoil'd my Races, O!\"
He gat them in, wi' some delay,
And te Newcassel bent his way;
But oft, indeed, he curs'd the day,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'That e\'er he\'d seen the Races, O.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "Now some were singin songs so fine,
And some were lying drunk like swine,
Some drank porter, others wine;
Rare drinkin at the Races, O!
The wanton wags in corners sat,
Wiv bonny lasses on their lap;
And mony a yen gat tit for tat,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Rum ti idity, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Sic wark as we had efter that,
Wad tyek a lang day for to tell,
How we fronted, an' flankt it, an' maircht
Through the sowgers at Thropley Fell,
At the Play-house we've shin'd mony a time,
Wor scaups a' besmatter-d wi' flour;
But that neet it wad myed the deil gurn,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Weel may the keel row, that gets the bairns their breed.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "We teuk wor keel up to the dyke,
Up to the dyke, up to the dyke,
We teuk wor keel up to the dyke,
And there we gat her load;
Then sail'd away down to Shields,
Down to Shields, down to Shields,
Then sail'd away down to Shields,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Singing--Weel may the keel row, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Then we row'd away up to the fest,
Up to the fest, up to the fest,
We row'd away up to the fest,
Cheerly every man;
Pat by wor gear and moor'd wor keel,
And moor'd wor keel, and moor'd wor keel,
Pat by wor gear and moor'd wor keel,
Then went and drank wor can,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'To the Parade Ground sent it.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "Ye gowks, frae Shields ye've oft slipt up,
When ye had little 'casion,
To see wor snobs their capers cut,
Or Geordy's Coronation;
Now altogether come yence mair,
Wor blissins shall attend ye,
If ye'll but rid us o' wor Mayor,
Iv hackney's back we'll send ye.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Now a\' the lads wad fain be at her.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "The Men o' France to her advance,
And use all arts to gain her favour;
And Spaniards bold, with hearts of gold,
Vow, if she's to be had, they'll have her;
And daft John Bull, that bleth'ring cull,
About the nymph sets up his chatter;
O bonnie Lizzie Liberty!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Northumberland free o\' Newcassel.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "May it please Heav'n to grant that the sweet Flower o' Wales,[11]
Wi' Northumberland's roses entwinin',
May its fragrance shed forth i' celestial gales,
In glory unceasin'ly shinin',
In defence o' wor country, wor laws, an' wor King,
May a _Peercy_ still lead us to battle;
An' monny a brisk lad o' the nyem may there spring", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Whack, fal, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "'Aye, aye,' says Carr, 'aw ken them weel,
Tyek them out o' my seet!
Away wi' them to Mr. Scott,
And keep them there a' neet.'
Says Walton, 'Will ye hear me speak?'
Says Tommy, 'Go you to the devil!'
'Wye, wye,' says Walton, 'never mind,
But surely this is damn'd uncivil.'", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'And fand him varry kind:', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Says he, 'Young men, I'll treat ye weel,
Tho' here against your mind.'
'O Sir,' said they, 'you're very good,
But faith this place luiks dark and frightful!'
Says Walton, 'What a sweet perfume!'
Says Watson, 'Lord, it's quite delightful!'", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Th\' expences he mun pay:', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "But still there's nyen that's sorry for't;
'It sarves him reet,' they say.
So howay, lads, let's off to toon,
We'll a' put wor bit better hats on;
And if Tom Carr shops us agyen,
Me sowl! we'll give him Waller Watson.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Were e\'er sae pure as lovely Delia.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Gently blaw, thou whistlin' wind,
Along the bonny banks o' Tyne,
Where nature every grace combin'd
When she first form'd my life, my Delia!
Clear beams the eye o' Delia,
Heaven's in the smile o' Delia;
Nor flower that blaws, nor winter snaws,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Yep! fal der al dal, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Wor toon has grown se big now,
Aw ne'er saw the like before;
Live ye only lang eneugh,
Ye'll see't join'd to Tynemouth shore;
We've our Literinary Sicties,
Shops cramm'd wiv plate and diamond broaches,
But it's ne use telling ony mair,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Yep! &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Ca-la-de-scoups were yence the rage,
Sedans--were all the go;
But till the noise gets fairly ower,
They may keep them iv a row;
Gang where you will, the talk is still,
At tea or cards why all the rage is,
\"Why bless me, sir! have you not seen
Our stylish two-horse Hackney Stages!\"", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'If twe Cockneys put up to \'present us.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Times ha'e been when a body's been axt out to tea,
Or to get a wee bit of a shiver,
Wor hearts were sae leet we ne'er thowt o' the cau'd,
Or the fear o' wet feet plagu'd us niver;
But i' blanket coats now we mun get muffled up,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Weel plaister\'d byeth \'hint and afore, man.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "If a' their improvements aw were for to tell,
Aw might sit here and sing--aye, for ever;
There's the rum weak as watter, i'stead o' the stuff
That was us'd for to burn out wor liver!
Aw's fair seek and tir'd o' the things that aw've sung,
So aw think now aw'll myek a conclusion,
By wishing the cheps iv a helter may swing,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'The pink o\' the wise, and the wale o\' the brave.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "To recount all your virtues a volume 'twould swell,
So we'll just name a few, sir, in which you excel;
Your reign's been eventful, the times have gone mad,
And well might have puzzled more brains than you had;
But sufficient was Archy, well able was Archy,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'O Archy! but that was a damnable deed.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Next you went on a voyage of discovery to Shields,
And got handsomely pepper'd for meddling with keels;
Then for refuge you fled to Northumberland's Arms,
Who till now has defended your paper from harms,
Else down had gone Archy, thy paper, dear Archy,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Wi\' ginger-breed and scranchim-o.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Now cocks had crawn an hour or more,
And ower the yell-pot some did snore;
But how they luikt to hear the roar
Of Matt, the King Pit caller-o!
'Smash him!' says Ned, 'he mun be rang,
He's callin' through his sleep, aw's war'n;'", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'And learns to execute his task with ease.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Wilson,[19] desist! and Simpson,[20] take your rest!
Ease and retirement now will suit ye best;
Your brief excursions will excite no more
That admiration which they did before;
Though doubtless ye have both endeavour'd hard,
Perhaps without an adequate reward;
But such laborious journies lay aside,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Country.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Dear Bob--A sad outlaw at length I'm become,
The Tories despise me; the Whigs glump and gloom,
And scowl as they pass, which is something uncivil,
And the Radicals treat me as I would the devil;
And threaten, the next time I make my appearance,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Hoisted high on a pole, with a crown on her head--', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Spirituals', 'lyrics' => "(And her effigy more than the devil they dread)
The crowd was so dense, and the shouts so astounding,
And nothing but Radical whiskers surrounding;
Which made it becoming to bow to the Queen,
Though a damnable blot on their loyalty, I ween!
Releas'd, they drove gently, their plans to fulfill,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'By drinking the king\'s health upon the Sandhill.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "But, to their misfortune, round where it was plac'd,
The crowd was so furious, no Tory could face't;
And high on the gilded dome stood a rude fellow,
With the crown on his head!--people said he was mellow;
But I took him to be some base Radical body,
Who wish'd folk to think that the King was a noddy,
For at the mock gestures of kingly demeanour,
The people bawl'd loudly, and bow'd to his honour;
While many among them cried, Pull the knave down!
Such a bad drunken fellow's not fit for a crown!
He's as good, quoth a keelman, and blew like a porpus,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'As the London Mogul, who can drink, wh--e, and rob us.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "So near was the danger, the Mayor swoon'd away;
But Archy, more bold as they pranc'd round the fray,
To his comrades cried softly, (but not till past catching)
\"What treasonable stuff those damn'd Radicals are hatching!
D'ye see what a mess they have made of the crown,
Go call out the soldiers to pull yon knave down.\"
\"Drive on,\" quoth the Mayor, by this time come about,
\"There's no time to talk while the Philistines are out.\"
More furious grew Archy, as nearer he drew", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'The den of corruption, with th\' Noodles in view.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "\"Fetch the soldiers, I say--let the streets swim with blood!
See the crown is insulted, and all that is good,
When erected this morn, what a sight to behold!
'Twas velvet and ermine, and cover'd with gold!
'Tis sacrilege! treason! hell groans at the sight!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'From the radical scene to the loyal pig-stye.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "To St. Nicholas' Square then I posted away,
Where Typo's high window peep'd over the fray;
And such an Ox roasting was there to be seen!
'Twas a bad loyal meeting for all but the Queen.
The crowd was immense, and their spirits were high,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'For the head wearing horns was as black as the devil.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Spirituals', 'lyrics' => "St. Nicholas peal'd out as the hisses began,
And seem'd to say, \"Loyal bucks, do what you can!\"
As fast as the butchers the collops threw out,
The people return'd them with many a shout;
And many a fat lump loyal whiskers besmear'd,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'While a Radical gave them a touch of his lay.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Spirituals', 'lyrics' => "In vain the peace-officers handled their staves,
And entreated the crowd to submit like good slaves;
'Twas the Head of the Church who created the day,
And salvation attended a loyal display!
But passive obedience was basely rejected,
And the Head of the Church very little respected;
Which made Archy again for the horse soldiers shout,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Which in Gotham have made a most damnable rout:', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Mister Mayor at a trifle does not seem to stick,
With the RADS[30] he's been playing _Sir Archy Mac Syc._--
While Sidmouth he cramm'd with some _Green Bag Supplies_,
Which--alas! for his Worship--have turn'd out _all lies_!
_A stark staring Parson_,[31] to add to the store,
A budget has sent to the noble Strathmore;
And some other Arch Wag, whom all grace has forsook,
A _thumper_ has palm'd on a great Northern Duke!
Sir Matt, too, so lately the pride of the Tyne,
Against poor old Gotham did also combine;
By supporting _Bold Archy's_ most libellous letter,
He has added another strong link to the fetter!
The rivet he's clos'd, which no mortal can sever,
And set now's the \"_Bright Star of Heaton_\" for ever!
But let him beware--for \"_a Rod is in pickle_,\"
Which, sooner or later, \"_his Toby will tickle!_\"", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'About Lunnen, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Ti see the wires haggle about tripe and sheep-heads,
Or washing their greens at a fountain,
Where the bonny Nuns us'd to be telling their beads,
And had nowt but their sins ti be counting;
There the talented lords o' the cleaver and steel
May be heard on that classical grund, sir,
Loudly chaunting the praise o' their mutton an' veal,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'And he\'ll finish us off to a tee.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Baith sides of the Tyne, aw remember,
Were cover'd wi' bonny green fields,
But now there is nought but big furnaces
Down frae Newcastle to Shields;
And what wi' their sulphur and brimstone,
Their vapour, their smoke, and their steam,
The grass is all gaen, and the farmers", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'These are the days, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "For making their salts and their soda,
They formerly us'd a kail-pot,
With an awd-fashion'd bit of a chimley
They were quite satisfied wi' their lot;
But now Anty Clapham, the Quaker,
Has fill'd a' the folks wi' surprise,
For he's lately built up a lang chimley,
Within a few feet o' the skies!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Fitters, bankers, merchants, soon will follow in a row.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "The Newcastle deputation, no doubt on't, swagger'd much, sir,
Expecting our Pilgarlicks soon foiled would have been;
But too hard for them all prov'd the diplomatic Butcher,
Whose tongue, like his gully-knife, is marvellously keen,
Spite of wheedling and of sneering,
Bamboozling and queering,
He to his purpose stuck so firm, so true, and so staunch,
The Town Clerk and his chums,
Stood whistling on their thumbs,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'However for its transit Antiquarians sore may grieve.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "Then comes the grand finale, for which our souls we'd barter now;
The Regent and his ministers we'll pester night and day,
Till tranferr'd to us Newcastle sees her revenues and charter too,
And from Heddon streams to Tynemouth bar, Tyne owns our sovereign
sway.
O when our town so famous is,
Big as Hippopotamuses,
We'll strut about the Bank-top quite semi-divine;
The neighbouring coasters all,
Our greatness shall appall,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'For a fa\' down it will be for certain--', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Of a' the wiseacres and gon'rals, an' a'
That dare to oppose the great Martin;
He'll settle their hash! their necks he will smash,
A' the College-bred gowks he will dazzel;
Ne mair shall false teachers o'er him cut a dash!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'To stock them with forbidden flesh, agyen our famous laws, man:', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "A cook in France, now understand, as sure's the sun inleets wor land,
Did kidnap bairns, an' mince them down, and myed sic pies, that a' the
town
Wad eat nowt else--thowt nowt se fine; they fand him out--then, what a
shine!--", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'O wad the keel, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "That morning forget I will never,
When first I saw him on the Kee,
The 'Keel-row' he whistled se clever,
He won my affections frae me;
His drawers on his doup luik'd se canny,
His keel-hat was cock'd on his head,
And if I'd not getten my Jimmy,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Now mind ye, it isn\'t a lee--', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "My mother had gi'en me a penny,
To get her a penn'orth o' tea;
When a lad i' the street cried out, 'Bessy!'
Says I, 'Hinny, that's not my nyem.'
'Becrike! never mind,' he said, 'lassie,
'To-neet I will see thee safe hyem.'", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'But the greedy black-coats, tee.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Your bonny bells there's nane excels,
In a' the country round;
They ring so sweet, they are a treat
When they play heartsome tunes;
And when all's dark, the people mark
Ye with your fiery eye,
That tells the travellers in the street", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'It\'s a house full of pastry-cooks, bankers, and drapers--', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "At the fine fancy fair, how my marrows did stare,
On the muffs, hats, and beavers, se fam'd in the papers;
At Beasley's, where liquor's se cheap and se prime,
A bottle aw purchas'd for maw sweetheart, Fanny,
We drank nowt but brandy--and, when it was time,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Maw hinny, says aw, hae ye seen Baggy Nanny.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "The lassie she twitter'd, and look'd rather queer,
And said, in this house there is mony a dozen,
They're planted so thick, that there's no sitting here,
They smell so confounded o' cat-gut and rosin;
The curtain flew up, and a lady did squall,
To fine music play'd by a Cockney bit mannie,
Then frae the front seats I suen heard my friends bawl,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Oh! Mister Mayor, it grieves me sair--', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Alas! what mun aw dee?
Wor Oyter-tub[46] is doom'd ne mair
To grace Newcassel Kee!
Wor bonny lamp that brunt se breet,
And cheer'd each wintry neet se dreary,
Is gyen, and lots o' canny folks
Will miss it sair when cawd and weary!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'My heart still warms to think upon\'t.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "There's famous ale in yon town,
Will make your lips to smack again,
And many a one leaves yon town,
Oft wishes they were back again;
Well shelter'd from the northern blast,
Its spires and turrets proudly rise,
And boats and keels all sailing past", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'And sighed our prayer to the breeze,--', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Where we us'd to confess, ere long will we see 'em
A chaunting lewd ditties and glees;
The ground where we stand will be strew'd soon with buyers,
Pursuing their ways so mistaken;
Extinct is the race now of Holy Friars,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'To see him levelled law, man.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Blind Willie slowly led the band,
As beagle, on the way, man;
A staff he carried in his hand,
And shook his head se grey, man;
At his reet hand was Buggy Jack,
With his hat-brim se broad, man;
And on his left was Bill the Black,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Lamentin\' by his side, man.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "And roguish Ralph, and busy Bruce,
That leeves upon their prey, man,
Did not neglect, but did protect
Their friends upon the way, man;
And Jimmy Liddle, drest in black,
Behint them a' did droop, man;
He had a coat on like the Quak's,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'The farmers will forget to call, H-ll\'s Kitchen\'s very sel\' turn quiet.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "The Chronicle may doze in peace,--Lord Grainger says, \"Sleep on--\"
The bugs may tyek another lease, their race is not yet run;
Awd Nichol still may fairly say, frae Hepple's up to Humble's house
end,
He feeds a lively host each day, aw'll say, at least, a hundred
thousand.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Rom ti iddity, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "The Hawk, the Northumberland Star,
An' the Magdalen's banners wav'd sweet, man;
But the Chieftain astonish'd them all,
With his braw Highland lads dress'd sae neat, man;
The Nelson appear'd in true blue,
(There canny host Simpson belangs, man,)
An' Petrie walk'd close alangside", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'He plays a knavish part.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Now, from Hibernia's fertile shore
The thund'ring champion comes,
His country's wrongs for to deplore,
With trumpets, fife, and drums;
He tells them, too, he is most true,
Their firm, unshaken friend,
While life Shall last, he will stand fast,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'T\' implore a helping hand.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "And not unfrequent, as we stray
This wond'rous place to see,
We find it fill'd with ladies gay,
To take a cup of tea;
And many a gent, who is content
With such domestic fare,
Has often sat, in social chat,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Arcade that Grainger built.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "This is _Peregrine_, pragmatic and prim, who scouted
the hat without any brim--the hat that was all cock'd
and lac'd, according to Briggs' peculiar taste--paid for
by the horde of attorneys so bored by the rascally boys,
who, making a noise, are kick'd out by the blade, whose
only trade is to keep the Arcade that Grainger built.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Singing, fal, lal, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Last Cursmas time whe wad ha'e thowt
That wor awd priest wad leave us,
And cause sec dowly thowts to cum,
Se very much to grieve us?
We sartly thowt we had him fix'd,
And fassen'd here till death, sors;
Unless he had been prebendized", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Then drink about, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "The sailors sing their dangers o'er,
When sailing on the high seas;
Says Donald frae Fife, \"I've left the North,
Where Parry wad lost his ideas.\"
\"Come, d--n!\" says Durham lad, \"leet my pipe,
And give us nyen o' your yarn reels;
But pay the quart--Ise be the next,
We'll hev a spree at Armfield's.\"", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Hurrah for Newcassel! &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Awd Humpy-back'd Dick, and two or three mair,
Fra Shiney Raw pit to the Well did repair;
He drank of the Spaw, when the hump, in a crack,
Dissolv'd and soon vanish'd frae poor Dicky's back!
Lord bliss us! cried timber-toed tee-total Peg,
If it banishes humps, it might bring forth a leg!
She got to the Well, with the Spaw she made free,
And very soon after poor Peggy had three!!!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'Hard might be her fate if she ventur\'d to drink--', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "For most of the lasses that live in Lang Raw,
Have getten the dropsy by tasting the Spaw!
The doctors declare, that at forty weeks' end,
'Twill be in their arms, and the dropsy will mend;
The howdies are wishing the time was well o'er,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'It happen\'d in the dark, man,--', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Spirituals', 'lyrics' => "A chep cam up ga' me a freet,
'Twas little Skipper Clark, man:
His fyece was white as ony clout,
Says aw, what hae ye been about?
He gyep'd at me, and gav a shout,
O Dick, I've seen the Deil, man!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'To drink in a bumper--good health to the Queen.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Hurrah for Old England, her Queen, and her laws!
Hurrah for all hearts that are true in the cause!
Hurrah for Newcastle! Hurrah for the Mayor!
Hurrah for the Tyne--its banks bustling and fair!
Hurrah for the Freemen, that rouse at each call!
Hurrah for the Stewards, the Spirit of all!
Hurrah for the many bright days we have seen!
Hurrah for a bumper--long life to the Queen!
_God save the Queen!_", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'And well they both deserv\'d, sir.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "The time has been when bread and cheese
Was wont to be their fare, sir,
What think ye now of turkeys, geese,
A partridge, or a hare, sir!
Well I remind their many joys,
And many happy days, sir,
For O they were the bonny boys", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'And made us eat a Bear, sir.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Some talk about the Esquimaux,
And tell of Cherokees, sir,
Hottentots and Marathas,
And folks in the South Seas, sir;
'Tis said they sometimes cut a swell
In dishes odd and rare, sir,
But we from them will bear the bell,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'But we can eat a Bear, sir.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Now as you chance to walk the street,
How every dog will run, sir,
Lest you should roast him for a treat,
And eat him up in fun, sir;
The Quayside horses, loaded well,
Will scamper off like hares, sir,
To see, not Bears all eating men,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'His was the lot too few have known--to live content, and die contented.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "The Bard who sung of Starkey's death, in tearful strains and true,
And planted on Bold Archy's grave the wreath ta'en from his brow;
His local reed in dust he lays--farewell!--there trill'd its
final shiver,--
It has been tun'd in Willie's praise, it now with him lies mute
for ever.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/40048'),
    array('title' => 'With my heart’s true queen.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Yet ’tis not the rosy tint of summer,
Nor the song-birds’ joyous lay,
Nor the streamlet’s murmuring music,
That makes my heart feel gay;
’Tis her smile that beams upon me,
’Mid each flowery scene,
While I fondly wander,
With my heart’s true queen,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'Like a fine ould Irish gintleman, the boy of the oulden time.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "To Donnybrook his custom was to go to every fair,
And though he’d seen a few score years, he still was young when
there;
And while the rich they feasted him, he still, among the poor,
Would sing, and dance, and hurl, and fight, and make the spalpeens
roar.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'Like a raal ould Irish gintleman, the boy of the oulden time.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "19
But och, mavrone! once at a row ould Barney got a knock,
And one that kilt him, ’cause he couldn’t get o’er the shock,
They laid him out so beautiful, and then set up a groan,
Och! Barney, darlint, jewel dear, why did you die? och, hone!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'He vas a fine old Dietchen shentlemen von of the pestest kind.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "By de fireshtove in his bier saloon efery morning he uoold shtand,
Mit a bottle of schnapps down by his side, un a glass up in his
hand,
Un by himself he trinks dis toast, “Ich lieben die Vaderland,”
Un midout you could Dietsche vershter, for he vold nix Inglish
gasprochen ven he’d say, “Spechlebecks von-grossen-dunder un
blitzen nut-de-swimegrahdle skipoupens-die-dobbleshm,” you
couldn’t nix undershtand.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'To dis fine old Dietchen shentleman, von of de pestest kind.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "20
Dis fine old Dietchen shentlemen he vent to bed drunk efery night,
Un somedimes ven dere vas coming rount elections, mit de udder
fellers he’d fight,
Un slouck dem on de koup mit a double-barrel’d powie knife, but I
don’t tink dat vas rite,
For ven vun of dem peeples haf his head preak’d into his nose all
ofer his face, un vas nearly drownded mit a big stick, I tell
you somedings rite avay shust now dat vas a sorry sight,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'To dis fine old Dietchen shentleman, von of de goot olt kind.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "But von time dere comed some drouples, un he fight mit all his
main,
Dough he vas kilt von two ash six eight couple of times, he shumps
up un fites again,
Dill his hed vas all splitted open down pack, un den de blood comes
down like rain;
Un py and py come dere de coroner mit de shury, un sit on him apout
dwenty-two hours ash tree-quarters, un shqueeze all de preth
out of his pody, den dey prings in a verdigrass, vot he dies
from prandy and vater on de prain,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'Away, far away, to the land of the West.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "To the West! to the West! where the rivers that flow,
Run thousands of miles, sparkling out as they go;
Where the green waving forests shall echo our call,
As wide as old England, and free to us all;
Where the prairies, like seas where the billows have roll’d,
Are broad as the kingdoms and empires of old;", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'To the West! to the West, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "To the West! to the West! there is wealth to be won;
A forest to clear is the work to be done;
We’ll try it--we’ll do it--and never despair,
While there’s light in the sunshine, or life in the air;
The bold independence that labor shall buy,
Shall strengthen our hearts, and forbid us to sigh;
Away, far away, let us hope for the best,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'The shadows of evening are falling--', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Oh, where is the wanderer now?
The breeze that floats lightly around me,
Perchance may soon visit his brow;
Oh, bear on thy bosom a message,
We are watching, oh, why wilt thou roam?
The heart has grown sad and dejected,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'Publishers of the music, and owners of copyright.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "In beauty gleamed the moon last night,
And brightly star lamps shone,
The wind among the lindentrees
Made music sad and lone;
The shadows of the firelight danced
Like sprites upon the floor,
As moon and star ray gently fell
Around the cottage door;
With breathings hush’d we sat around
The couch where Ettie lay,
And wept that one so beautiful,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'My girl with the calico dress.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Your dandies and foplings may sneer,
At her simple and modest attire,
But the charm she permits to appear,
Would set the whole iceberg on fire!
She can dance--but she never allows
The hugging, the squeeze, and caress,
She is saving all these for her spouse,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'When fond recollection recalls them to view--', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "The orchard, the meadow, the deep-tangled wildwood,
And every loved spot which my infancy knew;
The wide-spreading pond, and the mill which stood by it,
The bridge, and the rock where the cataract fell,
The cot of my father, the dairy-house nigh it,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'That moss-cover’d vessel I hail as a treasure.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "For often, at noon, when return’d from the field,
I found it the source of an exquisite pleasure,
The purest and sweetest that nature can yield;
How ardent I seized it, with hands that were glowing
And quick to the white-pebbled bottom it fell,
Then soon, with the emblem of truth overflowing,
And dripping with coolness, it rose from the well,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'She seeks a watery grave.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Spirituals', 'lyrics' => "Man the life boat! man the life boat!
See the dreadful signal flies;
Ha! she has struck, and from the rock
Despairing shouts arise;
And one there stands and wrings his hands,
Amidst the tempest wild,
For on the beach he can not reach,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'He sees his wife and child.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Life-saving ark! yon doomed bark
Immortal souls doth bear,
Not gems, nor gold, nor wealth untold,
But men, brave men, are there!
Oh, speed the life boat, speed the life boat,
O God! their efforts crown!
She dashes on--the ship is gone", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'Full forty fathoms down.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Ah, see! the crew are struggling now,
Amidst the billows roar,
They’re in the boat, they’re all afloat,
Hurrah! they’ve gain’d the shore,
Bless the life boat, bless the life boat!
Oh, thou’lt hear our prayer,
Bless the life boat, bless the life boat!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'As a band of brothers joined, peace and safety we shall find.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Immortal patriots, rise once more, defend your rights, defend your
shore.
Let no rude foe, with impious hand,
Let no rude foe, with impious hand,
Invade the shrine where sacred lies, of toil and blood the
well-earned prize.
While offering peace sincere and just, in heaven we place a manly
trust,
That truth and justice will prevail, and every shame of bondage
fail.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'Firm united let us be, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Behold the chief who now commands, again to serve his country
stands--
The rock on which the storm will beat,
The rock on which the storm will beat;
But armed in virtue firm and true, his hopes are fix’d on Heaven
and you.
When hope was sinking in dismay, and glooms obscured Columbia’s
day,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'She wiped the tears I wept.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "And that same hand that held my own
When I began to walk,
And the joy that sparkled in my eyes
When I began to talk;
I remember, too, when I was ill,
She kiss’d my burning brow;
And the tears that fell upon my cheek", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'Isle of beauty, fare thee well.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "’Tis the hour when happy faces
Smile around the taper’s light,
Who will fill our vacant places?
Who will sing our songs to-night?
Through the mists that float above us
Faintly sounds the vesper bell;
Like a voice from those who love us,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'Poor Willie saw no more.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "“Forget me not, forget me not,”
The words rung in his ear;
He ask’d the neighbors one by one,
Each answer’d with a tear,
They pointed to the old churchyard,
And there his youthful bride,
With the pretty child he loved so well,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'Other changes:', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Spirituals', 'lyrics' => "“Jordon” to “Jordan” twice in Table of Contents
“ln” to “in”, Chorus, Darling Rosabel
“sigh,s” to “sighs”, last line, Darling Rosabel
“hear” to “here”, last line, Linda has Departed
“natiye” to “native”, last stanza, My Heart's in Old Ireland
removed question mark, 4th stanza, 3rd line, What Will Mrs. Grundy Say
“nas” to “has”, 5th stanza, 2nd line, What Will Mrs. Grundy Say
“Crurtin” to “Courtin”, 3rd stanza, last line, Rosa Lee
comma to period, end of 3rd stanza, Fine Old Irish Gentleman
period to comma, first line, John Jones
“forttne” to “fortune”, 4th stanza, 3rd line, Vilikins and His Dinah
“tress” to “trees”, penultimate line, The Fireman's Death
“hors” to “horses”, first line, Give ’em String and let ’em Went
“they’e” to “they’re”, last line, 2nd stanza, Give em String
“satan Stare” to “Satan stare”, 2nd line, last stanza, Few Days
“Jordon’s” to “Jordan’s”, last line of Chorus, Jordan is a Hard Road
“darke ymust” to “darkey must”, first line, Darling Jenny Bell
“rpeed” to “speed”, 5th line, 3rd stanza, Man the Life Boat
“cottaeg” to “cottage”, 6th line, 2nd stanza, Bessy was a Sailor's Bride
“ehild” to “child”, first line, 4th stanza, The American Boy
“cat” to “coat”, 3rd line, 4th stanza, My Poor Dog Tray
“neveer” to “never”, first line, 3rd stanza, Happy Hezekiah
“BAEDLE’S” to “BEADLE’S”, advertisement for DIME MILITARY SONG BOOK", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49629'),
    array('title' => 'For the honor of _Liberty Tree_.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "But hear, O ye swains, 'tis a tale most profane,
How all the tyrannical powers,
Kings, Commons, and Lords, are uniting amain,
To cut down this guardian of ours;
From the east to the west blow the trumpet to arms,
Through the land let the sound of it flee,
Let the far and the near, all unite with a cheer,
In defence of our _Liberty Tree_.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'By its own reflection in the tide.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Meanwhile his friend, through alley and street,
Wanders and watches with eager ears,
Till in the silence around him he hears
The muster of men at the barrack-door,
The sound of arms, and the tramp of feet,
And the measured tread of the grenadiers", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'And the moonlight flowing over all.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Beneath, in the churchyard lay the dead,
In their night-encampment on the hill,
Wrapp'd in silence so deep and still
That he could hear, like a sentinel's tread,
The watchful night-wind, as it went
Creeping along from tent to tent,
And seeming to whisper, \"All is well!\"
A moment only he feels the spell
Of the place and the hour, and the secret dread
Of the lonely belfry and the dead;
For suddenly all his thoughts are bent
On a shadowy something far away,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'On the opposite shore walk\'d Paul Revere.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Now he patted his horse's side,
Now gazed at the landscape far and near,
Then, impetuous, stamp'd the earth,
And turn'd and tighten'd his saddle-girth;
But mostly he watch'd with eager search
The belfry-tower of the Old North Church,
As it rose above the graves on the hill,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'A second lamp in the belfry burns.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "A hurry of hoofs in a village street,
A shape in the moonlight, a bulk in the dark,
And beneath, from the pebbles, in passing a spark
Struck out by a steed flying fearless and fleet;
That was all; and yet, through the gloom and the light
The fate of a nation was riding that night;
And the spark struck out by that steed in his flight", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'Kindled the land into flame with its heat.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "He has left the village and mounted the steep,
And beneath him, tranquil and broad and deep,
Is the Mystic, meeting the ocean tides,
And under the alders that skirt its edge,
Now soft on the sand, now loud on the ledge,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'To every Middlesex village and farm,--', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "A cry of defiance, and not of fear,
A voice in the darkness, a knock at the door,
And a word that shall echo for evermore!
For, borne on the night-wind of the past,
Through all our history to the last,
In the hour of darkness, and peril, and need,
The people will waken and listen to hear
The hurrying hoof-beats of that steed,
And the midnight message of Paul Revere.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'Ask it,--ye who will.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "Fear ye foes who kill for hire?
Will ye to your homes retire?
Look behind you!--they're afire!
And, before you, see
Who have done it! From the vale
On they come!--and will ye quail?
Leaden rain and iron hail
Let their welcome be!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'Be freedom, and science, and virtue thy fame.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "To conquest and slaughter let Europe aspire;
Whelm nations in blood, and wrap cities in fire;
Thy heroes the rights of mankind shall defend,
And triumph pursue them, and glory attend,
A world is thy realm: for a world be thy laws,
Enlarged as thine empire, and just as thy cause;
On Freedom's broad basis, that empire shall rise,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'And the east see the morn hide the beams of her star.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "New bards, and new sages, unrivalled shall soar
To fame unextinguished, when time is no more;
To thee, the last refuge of virtue designed,
Shall fly from all nations the best of mankind;
Here, grateful to heaven, with transport shall bring", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'Their incense, more fragrant than odors of spring.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Nor less shall thy fair ones to glory ascend,
And genius and beauty in harmony blend;
The graces of form shall awake pure desire,
And the charms of the soul ever cherish the fire;
Their sweetness unmingled, their manners refined,
And virtue's bright image, instamped on the mind,
With peace and soft rapture shall teach life to glow,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'Hush the tumult of war and give peace to the world.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Thus, as down a lone valley, with cedars o'erspread,
From war's dread confusion I pensively strayed,
The gloom from the face of fair heaven retired;
The winds ceased to murmur; the thunders expired;
Perfumes as of Eden flowed sweetly along,
And a voice as of angels, enchantingly sung:
\"Columbia, Columbia, to glory arise,
\"The queen of the world, and the child of the skies.\"", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'You may guess that this King is then coming to trouble.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "But when a Petition he treads under feet,
And sends over the ocean an army and fleet,
When that army, half famished, and frantic with rage,
Is cooped up with a leader whose name rhymes to _cage_;
When that leader goes home, dejected and sad;", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'Within the dark morass.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Woe to the English soldiery
That little dread us near!
On them shall light at midnight
A strange and sudden fear;
When, waking to their tents on fire,
They grasp their arms in vain,
And they who stand to face us
Are beat to earth again;
And they who fly in terror deem
A mighty host behind,
And hear the tramp of thousands", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'Peace and safety we shall find.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Immortal patriots, rise once more!
Defend your rights, defend your shore;
Let no rude foe with impious hand,
Let no rude foe with impious hand
Invade the shrine where sacred lies
Of toil and blood the well-earned prize;
While offering peace, sincere and just,
In heav'n we place a manly trust,
That truth and justice may prevail,
And ev'ry scheme of bondage fail.--_Chorus._", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'To fight, and to conquer, to conquer or die.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "To know we're resolved, let them think on the hour,
When Truxton, brave Truxton off Nevis's shore,
His ship mann'd for battle, the standard unfurl'd,
And at the _Insurgente_ defiance he hurled;
And his valiant tars cry,
While our standard shall fly,
Resolved, firm, and steady,
We always are ready", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'From the brave Yankee boys.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "'Twas on the 9th of February, at Montserrat we lay,
And there we spy'd the _Insurgente_ just at the break of day,
We raised the orange and the blue,
To see if they our signals knew,
The _Constellation_ and her crew", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'My brave Yankee boys.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Lord! our Cannons thunder'd with peals tremendous roar,
And death upon our bullets' wings that drenched their decks with gore,
The blood did from their scuppers run,
Their chief exclaimed, \"We are undone!\"
Their flag they struck, the battle won,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'By the brave Yankee boys.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Then to St. Kitts we steered, we bro't her safe in port,
The grand salute was fired and answered from the fort,
John Adams in full bumpers toast,
George Washington, Columbia's boast,
And now \"the girl we love the most!\"
My brave Yankee boys.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'Those brave Yankee boys.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Now chain-shot, grape, and langrage pierce through her oaken sides,
And many a gallant sailor's blood runs purpling in the tides;
While death flew nimbly o'er their decks,
Some lost their legs, and some their necks,
And Glory's wreath our ship be-decks,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'For brave Yankee boys.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Then homeward steered the captive ship, now safe in port she lies,
The old and young with rapture viewed our sailors' noble prize;
Through seas of wine their health we'll drink,
And wish them sweet-hearts, friends, and chink,
Who 'fore they'd strike, will nobly sink
Our brave Yankee boys.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'And the bell\'wing thunders roar.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "When Yankee meets the Briton,
Whose blood congenial flows,
By Heav'n created to be friends,
By fortune rendered foes;
Hard then must be the battle fray,
Ere well the fight is o'er;
Now they ride, side by side,
While the bell'wing thunders roar,
While her cannon's fire is flashing fast,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'When Columbia\'s thunder\'s roar.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Hence be our floating bulwark
Those oaks our mountains yield;
'Tis mighty Heaven's plain decree--
Then take the wat'ry field!
To ocean's farthest barrier then
Your whit'ning sail shall pour;
Safe they'll ride o'er the tide,
While Columbia's thunders roar,
While her cannon's fire is flashing fast,
And her Yankee thunders roar.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'By Lawrence down did go.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "Then next you sent your _Boxer_,
To box us all about,
But we had an _Enterprising_ brig
That beat your _Boxer_ out;
We boxed her up to Portland,
And moored her off the town,
To show the sons of liberty", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'By Yankees is o\'erthrown.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Use every endeavor,
And strive to make a peace,
For Yankee ships are building fast,
Their navy to increase;
They will enforce their commerce,
The laws by heaven are made,
That Yankee ships in time of peace,
To any port may trade.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'The ashes of her brave.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Thus 'neath their parent turf they rest,
Far from the gory field,
Borne to a Spartan mother's breast
On many a bloody shield;
The sunshine of their native sky
Smiles sadly on them here,
And kindred eyes and hearts watch by", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'The heroes\' sepulchre.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Rest on, embalmed and sainted dead!
Dear as the blood ye gave,
No impious footstep here shall tread
The herbage of your grave;
Nor shall your story be forgot,
While Fame her record keeps,
Or Honor points the hallowed spot", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'Where Valor proudly sleeps.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Yon marble minstrel's voiceless stone
In deathless song shall tell
When many a vanished age hath flown,
The story how ye fell;
Nor wreck, nor change, nor winter's blight,
Nor Time's remorseless doom,
Shall dim one ray of glory's light
That gilds your deathless tomb.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'The old flag.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "O the fury of the fight
Even then was at its height!
Yet no breath from noon till night
Reached us here;
We had almost ceased to wonder,
And the day had faded under,
When--the echo of the thunder
Filled each ear!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'As rushing squadrons bear ye thence.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "And ye whose homes are by her grand
Swift rivers, rising far away,
Come from the depth of her green land
As mighty in your march as they;
As terrible as when the rains
Have swelled them over bank and bourne,
With sudden floods to drown the plains", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'And sweep along the woods uptorn.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "And ye who throng beside the deep,
Her ports and hamlets of the strand,
In number like the waves that leap
On his long-murmuring marge of sand,
Come, like that deep, when, o'er his brim,
He rises, all his floods to pour,
And flings the proudest barks that swim,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'Learn how to breast the strain.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "Ho, woodsmen of the mountain-side
Ho, dwellers in the vales!
Ho, ye who by the roaring tide
Have roughened in the gales!
Come, flocking gayly to the fight,
From forest, hill, and lake;
We battle for our country's right,
And for the lily's sake!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'O\'er battles that made us a nation.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Peace, peace to the world--is our motto unfurled,
Tho' we shun not a field that is gory;
At home or abroad, fearing none but our God,
We will carve our own pathway to glory!
Then hail the true--the Red, White, and Blue,
The flag of the Constellation,
It sails as it sailed, by our fore-fathers hailed,
O'er battles that made us a nation,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'That bears a single star.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Now Georgia marches to the front,
And close beside her come
Her sisters by the Mexique Sea,
With pealing trump and drum;
Till answering back from hill and glen
The rallying cry afar,
A Nation hoists the Bonnie Blue Flag
That bears a single star!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'Lo! all the beacon-fires are lighted--', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Let all hearts be now united!
To arms! To arms! To arms, in Dixie!
Advance the flag of Dixie!
Hurrah! hurrah!
For Dixie's land we take our stand,
And live or die for Dixie!
To arms! To arms!
And conquer peace for Dixie!
To arms! To arms!
And conquer peace for Dixie!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'Smiles chase tears away to-morrow.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "To arms! To arms! To arms, in Dixie!
Advance the flag of Dixie!
Hurrah! hurrah!
For Dixie's land we take our stand,
And live or die for Dixie!
To arms! To arms!
And conquer peace for Dixie!
To arms! To arms!
And conquer peace for Dixie!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'Of Jesus, in the midnight gloom.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "\"What saw I?\" Little. Clouds of dust;
Great squares of men, with standards thrust
Against their course; dense columns crowned
With billowing steel. Then bound on bound,
The long black lines of cannon poured
Behind the horses, streaked and gored
With sweaty speed. Anon shot by,
Like a lone meteor of the sky,
A single horseman; and he shone", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'Caught from my mind significance.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "And then--why ask me? O my God!
Would I had lain beneath the sod,
A patient clod, for many a day,
And from my bones and mouldering clay
The rank field grass and flowers had sprung,
Ere the base sight, that struck and stung
My very soul, confronted me,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'Shamed at my own humanity.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "O happy dead! who early fell,
Ye have no wretched tale to tell
Of causeless fear and coward flight,
Of victory snatched beneath your sight,
Of martial strength and honor lost,
Of mere life bought at any cost,
Of the deep, lingering mark of shame,
For ever scorched on brow and name,
That no new deeds, however bright,
Shall banish from men's loathful sight!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'A wound that cannot close nor heal.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Ye perished steel to levelled steel,
Stern votaries of the god of war,
Filled with his godhead to the core!
Ye died to live, these lived to die,
Beneath the scorn of every eye!
How eloquent your voices sound
From the low chambers under ground!
How clear each separate title burns
From your high-set and laurelled urns!
While these, who walk about the earth,
Are blushing at their very birth!
And, though they talk, and go, and come,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'The vanward fragments of our host.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Can man, Thy image, sink so low,
Thou, who hast bent Thy tinted bow
Across the storm and raging main;
Whose laws both loosen and restrain
The powers of earth, without whose will
No sparrow's little life is still?
Was fear of hell, or want of faith,
Or the brute's common dread of death
The passion that began a chase,
Whose goal was ruin and disgrace?
What tongue the fearful sight may tell?
What horrid nightmare ever fell", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'Where hurrying myriads leap and rave.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Men of all arms, and all costumes,
Bare-headed, decked with broken plumes;
Soldiers and officers, and those
Who wore but civil-suited clothes;
On foot or mounted--some bestrode
Steeds severed from their harnessed load;
Wild mobs of white-topped wagons, cars,
Of wounded, red with bleeding scars;
The whole grim panoply of war
Surged on me with a deafening roar!
All shades of fear, disfiguring man,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'Onward the struggling masses bore.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Oh! had the foemen lain before,
They'd trampled them to dust and gore,
And swept their lines and batteries
As autumn sweeps the windy trees!
Here one cast forth his wounded friend,
And with his sword or musket-end
Urged on the horses; there one trod
Upon the likeness of his God,
As if 'twere dust; a coward here
Grew valiant with his very fear,
And struck his weaker comrade prone,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'Than could the prophet of God\'s choice.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "\"Back, animated dirt!\" I cried,
\"Back, on your wretched lives, and hide
Your shame beneath your native clay!
Or if the foe affrights you, slay
Your own base selves; and, dying, leave
Your children's tearful cheeks to grieve,
Not quail and blush, when you shall come,
Alive, to their degraded home!
Your wives will look askance with scorn;
Your boys, and infants yet unborn,
Will curse you to God's holy face!
Heaven holds no pardon in its grace
For cowards. Oh! are such as ye
The guardians of our liberty?
Back, if one trace of manhood still
May nerve your arm and brace your will!
You stain your country in the eyes
Of Europe and her monarchies!
The despots laugh, the peoples groan;
Man's cause is lost and overthrown!
I curse you, by the sacred blood
That freely poured its purple flood
Down Bunker's heights, on Monmouth's plain,
From Georgia to the rocks of Maine!
I curse you, by the patriot band
Whose bones are crumbling in the land!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'That flung the wet leaves to and fro.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Upon me lay a dismal woe,
A boundless, superhuman grief,
That drew no promise of relief
From any hope. Then I arose,
As one who struggles up from blows
By unseen hands; and as I stood
Alone, I thought that God was good,
To hide, in clouds and driving rain,
Our low world from the angel train,
Whose souls filled heroes when the earth", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'Was worthy of their noble birth.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "By that dull instinct of the mind,
Which leads aright the helpless blind,
I struggled onward, till the dawn
Across the eastern clouds had drawn
A narrow line of watery gray;
And full before my vision lay
The great dome's gaunt and naked bones
Beneath whose crown the nation thrones
Her queenly person. On I stole,
With hanging head and abject soul,
Across the high embattled ridge,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'And o\'er the arches of the bridge.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "So freshly pricked my sharp disgrace,
I feared to meet the human face,
Skulking, as any woman might,
Who'd lost her virtue in the night,
And sees the dreadful glare of day
Prepare to light her homeward way,
Alone, heart-broken, shamed, undone,
I staggered into Washington!
Since then long sluggish days have passed,
And on the wings of every blast
Have come the distant nations' sneers", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'The red cross fell, nor rose again.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "My humble pledge of faith I lay,
Dear comrade of my school-boy day,
Before thee, in the nation's view,
And if thy prophet prove untrue,
And from our country's grasp be thrown
The sceptre and the starry crown,
And thou, and all thy marshalled host
Be baffled and in ruin lost;
Oh! let me not outlive the blow
That seals my country's overthrow!
And, lest this woful end come true,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'From every hill and valley come.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Old men, yield up your treasured gold!
Can liberty be priced and sold?
Fair matrons, maids, and tender brides
Gird weapons to your lovers' sides;
And though your hearts break at the deed,
Give them your blessing and God-speed;
Then point them to the field of flame,
With words like those of Sparta's dame;
And when the ranks are full and strong,
And the whole army moves along,
A vast result of care and skill,
Obedient to the master will;
And your young hero draws the sword,
And gives the last commanding word", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'Oh! let them need no second blow.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "Strike, as your fathers struck of old;
Through summer's heat, and winter's cold;
Through pain, disaster, and defeat;
Through marches tracked with bloody feet;
Through every ill that could befall
The holy cause that bound them all!
Strike as they struck for liberty!
Strike as they struck to make you free!
Strike for the crown of victory!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50335'),
    array('title' => 'I used to keep my master’s LAMBS.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "With a BAA-BAA here, and a BAA-BAA there,
And here a BAA, and there a BAA,
And everywhere a BAA;
With a GEE-WO here, and a GEE-WO there,
And here a GEE, and there a GEE,
And everywhere a GEE;
Says I, My pretty lass, will you come to the banks of the Aire oh?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/61562'),
    array('title' => 'I used to keep my master’s HENS.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "With a CHUCK-CHUCK here, and a CHUCK-CHUCK there,
And here a CHUCK, and there a CHUCK,
And everywhere a CHUCK;
With a BAA-BAA here, and a BAA-BAA there,
And here a BAA, and there a BAA,
And everywhere a BAA;
With a GEE-WO here, and a GEE-WO there,
&c.,      &c.,      &c.
Says I, My pretty lass, will you come to the banks of the Aire oh?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/61562'),
    array('title' => 'I used to keep my master’s PIGS.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "With a GRUNT-GRUNT here, and a GRUNT-GRUNT there,
And here a GRUNT, and there a GRUNT,
And everywhere a GRUNT;
With a CHUCK-CHUCK here, and a CHUCK-CHUCK there,
And here a CHUCK, and there a CHUCK,
And everywhere a CHUCK;
With a BAA-BAA here, and a BAA-BAA there,
&c.,      &c.,      &c.
With a GEE-WO here, and a GEE-WO there,
&c.,      &c.,      &c.
Says I, My pretty lass, will you come to the banks of the Aire oh?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/61562'),
    array('title' => 'And on his forehead glowing.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Oh, cursed for aye that traitor’s hand,
And cursed that aim so deadly,
Which smote the bravest of the land,
And dyed his bosom redly!
Serene he lay, while past him prest
The battle’s furious billow,
As calmly as a babe may rest", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'To her and to her sighing.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Rest, patriot, in thy hill-side grave,
Beside her form who bore thee!
Long may the land thou diedst to save
Her bannered stars wave o’er thee!
Upon her history’s brightest page,
And on Fame’s glowing portal,
She’ll write thy grand, heroic rage
And grave thy name immortal.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'And the spring’s bubbling through the ground.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Along the beaten path I pace,
Where white rays mark my sentry’s track;
In formless shrubs I seem to trace
The foeman’s form with bending back,
I think I see him crouching low;
I stop and list--I stoop and peer,
Until the neighboring hillocks grow", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'We each felt all in all to each.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "And then that bitter, bitter day,
When came the final hour to part;
When, clad in soldier’s honest gray,
I pressed her weeping to my heart;
Too proud of me to bid me stay,
Too fond of me to let me go,
I had to tear myself away,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'Then onward pass, and all is well.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "But in the tent that night awake,
I ask, if in the fray I fall,
Can I the mystic answer make
When the angelic sentries call?
And pray that Heaven may so ordain,
Whene’er I go, what fate be mine,
Whether in pleasure or in pain,
I still may have the countersign.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'An’ “_All men up!_” say we,--', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "White, yaller, black, an’ brown, John;
Now which is your idee?
Ole Uncle S., sez he, “I guess
John preaches wal,” sez he;
“But, sermon thru, an’ come to _du_,
Why there’s the old J. B.
A-crowdin’ you an’ me!”", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'There’s life, though it throbbeth in silent veins,--', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "’T is vocal without noise;
It gushed o’er Manassas’ solemn plains,
From the blood of the MARYLAND BOYS!
That blood shall cry aloud, and rise
With an everlasting threat;
By the death of the brave, by the GOD in the skies,
_There’s life in the old land yet_!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'That cover the valleys of Paradise--', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "For all of the brave who rest with thee;
And for one and all who died with thee,
And now sleep side by side with thee;
And for every one who lives and dies,
On the solid land or the heaving sea,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'Shot, terror-stricken, beyond her dread sphere.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "We who are waiting with crowns for the victors,
Though we should offer the wealth of our store,
Load the _Varuna_ from deck down to kelson,
Still would be niggard, such tribute to pour
On courage so boundless. It beggars possession,--
It knocks for just payment at heaven’s bright door!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'Surf-worn boulder or sandy beach,--', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "But ooze-flats as far as the eye can reach,
With shallows of water-grass;
Reedy Savannahs, vast and dun,
Lying dead in the dim March sun;
Huge, rotting trunks and roots that lie
Like the blackened bones of shapes gone by,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'Freely enough to-night.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "“Mark well each signal I make,--
(Our life-long service at stake,
And honor that must not lag!)
What e’er the peril and awe,
In the battle’s fieriest flaw,
Let never one ship withdraw
Till the orders come from the flag!”", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'It was one of your long coal barges.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "(We had often had the like before.)
’Twas coming down on us to larboard,
Well in with the eastern shore;
And our pilot, to let it pass round,
(You may guess we never stopped to sound)
Giving us a rank sheer to starboard,
Ran the Flag hard and fast aground!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'Well, for a little it looked bad:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "But these things are, somehow, shorter,
In the acting than in the telling;
There was no singing out or yelling,
Or any fussing and fretting,
No stampede, in short;
But there we were, my lad,
All afire on our port quarter,
Hammocks ablaze in the netting,
Flames spouting in at every port,
Our fourth cutter burning at the davit
(No chance to lower away and save it).", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'Bareheaded in God’s bright sun.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Lord of mercy and frown,
Ruling o’er sea and shore,
Send us such scene once more!
All in line of battle
When the black ships bear down
On tyrant fort and town,
’Mid cannon cloud and rattle;
And the great guns once more
Thunder back the roar
Of the traitor walls ashore,
And the traitor flags come down.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'And Sheridan twenty miles away.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "And wider still those billows of war
Thunder’d along the horizon’s bar;
And louder yet into Winchester roll’d
The roar of that red sea uncontroll’d,
Making the blood of the listener cold,
As he thought of the stake in that fiery fray,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'A good broad highway leading down:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "And there, through the flush of the morning light,
A steed as black as the steeds of night
Was seen to pass, as with eagle flight,
As if he knew the terrible need
He stretch’d away with his utmost speed;
Hills rose and fell; but his heart was gay,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'Suppose for a moment, George, my friend--', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Just for a moment--you condescend
To use the means that are in your hands,
The eager muskets and guns and brands;
Take one bold step on the Southern sod,
And leave the issue to watchful God!
For now the nation raises its gorge,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'How true was the land of your fathers’ choice--', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Do you hear the traitors who bid you speak
The word that shall sever the sacred tie?
And ye who dwell by the golden peak,
Has the subtle whisper glided by?
Has it crossed the immemorial plains
To coasts where the gray Pacific roars,
And the Pilgrim blood in the people’s veins
Is pure as the wealth of their mountain ores?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'Nor came one back his wounds to tell.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "And full in the midst rose Keenan, tall
In the gloom, like a martyr awaiting his fall,
While the circle-stroke of his sabre, swung
’Round his head, like a halo there, luminous hung.
Line after line, ay, whole platoons,
Struck dead in their saddles, of brave dragoons
By the maddened horses were onward borne
And into the vortex flung, trampled and torn;", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'Vainly opposed their rush.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Through the wild battle’s crush,
With but one thought aflush,
Driving their lords like chaff,
In the gun’s mouth they laugh;
Or at the slippery brands,
Leaping with open hands,
Down they tear man and horse,
Down in their awful course;
Trampling with bloody heel", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'Rolled in triumphant blood.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "Glad to strike one free blow,
Whether for weal or woe;
Glad to breathe one free breath,
Though on the lips of death;
Praying,--alas! in vain!
That they might fall again,
So they could once more see
That burst to liberty!
This was what “freedom” lent", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'And along the lines, where’er they came, went up the ringing cheer.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "’Twas past the hour of nooning; the summer skies were blue;
Behind the covering timber the foe was hid from view;
So fair and sweet with waving wheat the pleasant valley lay,
It brought to mind our Northern homes and meadows far away;
When the whole western ridge at once was fringed with fire
and smoke,
Against our lines from seven-score guns the dreadful tempest broke!
Then loud our batteries answer, and far along the crest,
And to and fro the roaring bolts are driven east and west;
Heavy and dark around us glooms the stifling sulphur-cloud,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'The flower of all the Southern host move to the final charge.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "By heaven! it is a fearful sight to see their double rank
Come with a hundred battle-flags--a mile from flank to flank!
Tramping the grain to earth, they come, ten thousand men abreast;
Their standards wave--their hearts are brave--they hasten not, nor
rest,
But close the gaps our cannon make, and onward press, and nigher,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'Who charge anew, and welcome death, and fight us hand to hand:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Vain, vain! give way, as well ye may--the crimson die is cast!
Their bravest leaders bite the dust, their strength is failing fast;
They yield, they turn, they fly the field: we smite them as
they run;
Their arms, their colors, are our spoil; the furious fight is done!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'And to the dear Thanksgiving-feast our sons and daughters come--', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "When children’s children throng the board in the old homestead
spread,
And the bent soldier of these wars is seated at the head,
Long, long the lads shall listen to hear the gray-beard tell
Of those who fought at Gettysburg and stood their ground so well:
“’Twas for the Union and the Flag,” the veteran shall say,
“Our grand old Army held the ridge, and won that glorious day!”", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'And we swore none should reap it before us.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "That night, with the ensign who rode by my side,
On the camp’s dreary edge I stood picket,
Our ears intent lest every wind-rustle hide
A foe’s stealthy tread in the thicket;
And there, while we watched the first arrows of dawn
Through the veil of the rising mists quiver,
He told how the foeman had closed in upon", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'From a stubborn Meade and a barren field.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "I might tell how, but the day before,
John Burns stood at his cottage-door,
Looking down the village street,
Where, in the shade of his peaceful vine,
He heard the low of his gathered kine,
And felt their breath with incense sweet;
Or, I might say, when the sunset burned
The old farm gable, he thought it turned
The milk that fell like a babbling flood
Into the milk-pail, red as blood;
Or, how he fancied the hum of bees", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'Up to the pits the rebels kept--', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Round-shot ploughed the upland glades,
Sown with bullets, reaped with blades;
Shattered fences here and there,
Tossed their splinters in the air;
The very trees were stripped and bare;
The barns that once held yellow grain
Were heaped with harvests of the slain;
The cattle bellowed on the plain,
The turkeys screamed with might and main,
And brooding barn-fowl left their rest", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'With scraps of a slangy repertoire:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "“How are you, White Hat?” “Put her through!”
“Your head’s level!” and “Bully for you!”
Called him “Daddy,”--begged he’d disclose
The name of the tailor who made his clothes,
And what was the value he set on those;
While Burns, unmindful of jeer and scoff,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'And the swallow-tails they were laughing at.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "’Twas but a moment, for that respect
Which clothes all courage their voices checked;
And something the wildest could understand
Spake in the old man’s strong right hand,
And his corded throat, and the lurking frown
Of his eyebrows under his old bell-crown;
Until, as they gazed, there crept an awe
Through the ranks in whispers, and some men saw,
In the antique vestments and long white hair,
The Past of the Nation in battle there;
And some of the soldiers since declare
That the gleam of his old white hat afar,
Like the crested plume of the brave Navarre,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'And shrouds to make ready for some.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "They have gathered about you the harvest
Of death, in its ghastliest view;
The nearest as well as the farthest
Is here with the traitor and true!
And crowned with your beautiful patience,
Made sunny with love at the heart,
You must balsam the wounds of a nation,
Nor falter, nor shrink from your part!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'Alone in her pity can do.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "And the lips of the mothers will bless you
As angels sweet visaged and pale!
And the little ones run to caress you,
While the wives and the sisters cry “Hail!”
But e’en if you drop down unheeded,
What matter? God’s ways are the best;
You’ve poured out your life where ’twas needed,
And He will take care of the rest.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'Her mate might bear her through.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Forging boldly ahead,
The great Flag-Ship led,
Grandest of sights!
On her lofty mizzen flew
Our leader’s dauntless Blue,
That had waved o’er twenty fights
So we went with the first of the tide,
Slowly, ’mid the roar
Of the rebel guns ashore", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'And the _Hartford_ passed ahead.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Ahead lay the _Tennessee_,
On our starboard bow he lay,
With his mail-clad consorts three
(The rest had run up the bay);
There he was, belching flame from his bow,
And the steam from his throat’s abyss
Was a Dragon’s maddened hiss;", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'And still the fleet were astern.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "Right abreast of the Fort
In an awful shroud they lay,
Broadsides thundering away,
And lightning from every port;
Scene of glory and dread!
A storm-cloud all aglow
With flashes of fiery red,
The thunder raging below,
And the forest of flags o’erhead!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'Was growing a strange dull red,--', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "But soon, as once and again
Fore and aft we sped,
(The firing to guide or check,)
You could hardly choose but tread
On the ghastly human wreck,
(Dreadful gobbet and shred
That a minute ago were men!)
Red, from mainmast to bitts!
Red, on bulwark and wale,
Red, by combing and hatch,
Red, o’er netting and vail!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'Where her flames soon fire the night.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "And the Ram, when well up the Bay,
And we looked that our stems should meet,
(He had us fair for a prey,)
Shifting his helm midway,
Sheered off, and ran for the fleet;
There, without skulking or sham,
He fought them gun for gun;
And ever he sought to ram,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'For the mighty Gulf is ours,--', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "The bay is lost and won,
An Empire is lost and won!
Land, if thou yet hast flowers,
Twine them in one more wreath
Of tenderest white and red,
(Twin buds of glory and death!)
For the brows of our brave dead,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'When Sherman marched down to the sea.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Then forward, boys! forward to battle!
We marched on our wearisome way,
We stormed the wild hills of Resaca,
God bless those who fell on that day!
Then Kenesaw, dark in its glory,
Frowned down on the flag of the free,
But the East and the West bore our standard", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'As Sherman marched down to the sea.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Oh, proud was our army that morning,
That stood where the pine darkly towers,
When Sherman said: “Boys, you are weary,
But to-day fair Savannah is ours!”
Then sang we the song of our chieftain,
That echoed o’er river and lea,
And the stars in our banner shone brighter
When Sherman marched down to the sea.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'An’ de yar ob jubilo.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "He six foot one way an’ two foot todder,
An’ he weigh six hundred poun’;
His coat so big he couldn’t pay de tailor,
An’ it won’t reach half way roun’;
He drill so much dey calls him cap’n,
An he git so mighty tanned,
I spec he’ll try to fool dem Yankees,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'And life sits somewhere crowned.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Not Tasso’s soft persuasion unto sin
I find, dear rose, thy withered leaves within,
Nor any precept Epicurus gave;
To me thou dost not breathe
A thought of festivals, or memory
Of woven, wine-dipped wreath,
Or kisses on ripe lips, or fond regret
For bounds by time to fleeting pleasures set,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'Or wish to bring thy beauty back to thee.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "To kiss thy leaves I bend,
And lo! The crash of cannon fills mine ears;
I see the banners blend
Into the battle smoke; and the long lines
Of marching men where glint of bayonet shines
Through clouds of dust; the hopes, the hates, the fears
Of old thrill through my heart;
Again the myriad ghosts of the great war
From out their cerements start;
Again the nation in the contest strains
Its every nerve; again the deep refrains
Of groan and cheer break on us from afar!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'With many a life more precious finding doom.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Beside a farmer’s home
In shade and shine this rose of battle grew,
What time the rolling drum
Announced the crisis of the war at hand,
As Meade pressed swiftly north through Maryland,
And ever closer to Lee’s columns drew;
On that grim, weary march
Rain seldom fell; the June sun fiercely glowed
And seemed all things to parch;
The winds grew still, nor in their motion swung
The dust that round the lithe battalions clung", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'For miles, on many a winding country road.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "The women stood in groups
And watched with tear-wet eyes and smiling lips
The marching of the troops;
The smiles came at the sight of manhood stern
Moving to sacrifice with unconcern;
The tears were for the battle’s drear eclipse
That was so soon to fall", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'In sobered mood she plucked this flower and gave.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "It seems another age
When things like these were done; the rose’s bloom
He took as battle gage,
And with his laughing comrades went his way,
Well knowing that the columns wide astray
Were fast converging for the day of doom!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'Whose memory will not die.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "There lay along the outskirts of a wood
A regiment busy in the work of blood;
And he that wore the rose watched every man,
Alert, unvexed, intense,
And kept the firing cool, and fierce, and fast;
In front in column dense
Stern Southern valor stormed, and would not flinch,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'In field, and hall, and by the hearth of home.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "How proud their column moved,
Up the long slope of death with stubborn tread,
Obeying him they loved!
And still against the storm of fire that scourged
Supporting squadrons backward as it surged,
How fierce they held their way unwearièd!
Mayhap with other foes
They might have won; but ever slow to yield
And ever prompt to close
Were Hancock’s men; and the Virginian shaft
That pierced our lines was shattered, head and haft,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'Within the wound!--And Lee had lost the field.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Amid the eddied smoke,
The groans of dying men, and the glad cheer
Of victory that broke
From hill to hill, this thing of beauty died;
And he that wore and had forgot it, sighed
And thought of it again as something dear;
So from his breast he took
The rose and sent it home to have it set
Within this simple book,
The favorite of a girl he loved and lost,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'The essence I would set in melody--', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "The feelings of the time
When first it bloomed; the deeds of sacrifice,
The thoughts and acts sublime,
The scenes of battle with their woe and scaith,
The courtesy and courage, love and faith--
That I can read within it with mine eyes!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'By gory-handed war.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "What fights he fought, what wounds he wore,
Are all unknown to fame;
Remember, on his lonely grave
There is not even a name!
That he fought well and bravely too,
And held his country dear,
We know, else he had never been", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'And the fingers work of the sabre hand--', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "Oh, to bid them live, and to make them grand!
And the bugle sounds to the charge at last,
And away they plunge, and the front is passed!
And the jackets blue grow red as they ride,
And the scabbards too, that clank by their side,
And the dead soldiers deaden the strokes iron-shod", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'As they gallop right on o’er the plashy red sod--', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "Right into the cloud all spectral and dim,
Right up to the guns black-throated and grim,
Right down on the hedges bordered with steel,
Right through the dense columns--then “_Right about wheel!_”
Hurrah! a new swath through the harvest again!
Hurrah for the Flag! To the battle, Amen!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'Of freedom in our own beloved home.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "In the battle front we stood
When the fiercest charge they made,
And they swept us off a hundred men or more,
But before we reached their lines
They were beaten back dismayed,
And we heard the cry of vict’ry o’er and o’er.--_Chorus._", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/54211'),
    array('title' => 'Lord! what a Betsey Bobbin! etc.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Her roguish smile can well beguile,
Her every look bewitches;
Yet never stir, when tacked to her,
For Tim will wear the breeches;
I've face and mien, am spruce and keen,
And though my heart keeps throbbing,
There's not, in fine, one man in nine,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/34601'),
    array('title' => 'Boston, owners of the copyright.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "’Tis just one year ago to-day,
That I remember well,
I sat down by poor Nelly’s side
A story she did tell;
’Twas about a poor, unhappy slave
That lived for many a year;
But now he’s dead and in his grave,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'Oh! Willie, we have miss’d you; welcome, welcome home.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "We’ve long’d to see you nightly, but this night of all;
The fire was blazing brightly, and lights were in the hall,
The little ones were up ’till ’twas ten o’clock and past,
Then their eyes began to twinkle and they have gone to sleep at
last;
But they listen’d for your voice till they thought you’d never
come,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'Oh! kiss me quick and go my honey, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "One Sunday night we sat together,
Sighing side by side,
Just like two wilted leaves of cabbage
In the sunshine fried;
My heart with love was nigh to split
To ask her for to wed,
Said I: “Shall I go for the priest,”
And what d’ye think she said?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'I’d lay me doune and dee.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Like dew on the gowan lying,
Is the fa’ o’ her fairy feet,
And like the winds in summer sighing,
Her voice is low and sweet,
Her voice is low and sweet,
And she’s a’ the world to me;
And for bonnie Annie Laurie", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'Answer to Kate Kearney.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Oh, yes, I have seen this Kate Kearney,
Who lives near the lake of Killarney;
From her love-beaming eye, what mortal can fly,
Unsubdued by the glance of Kate Kearney?
For that eye so seducingly meaning,
Assures me of mischief she’s dreaming;
And I feel ’tis in vain to fly from the chain", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'My flowers, my companions, and me.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "How dark looks this world, and how dreary,
When we part from the ones that we love,
But there’s rest for the faint and the weary,
And friends meet with lost ones above;
But in heaven I can but remember,
When from earth my proud soul shall be free,
That no chilly winds of December,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'Takes the place of the olden din.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Do you mind the cabin of logs, Ben Bolt,
That stood in the pathless wood?
And the button-ball tree with its motley boughs,
That nigh by the door-step stood?
The cabin to ruin has gone, Ben Bolt,
You would look for the tree in vain;
And where once the lords of the forest stood,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'Ne’er has ceased to think of thee.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Don’t be angry mother, mother,
Let the world say what it will,
Though I don’t deserve thy favor,
Yet I fondly love thee still;
We have lived and loved together,
And our hearts ne’er knew a pain
But forgive me, mother, mother,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'To weep and pray for thee.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Over thy follies I have shed,
Ah! many a bitter tear,
And I have mourn’d for thee as dead
Through all the passing year;
Yet I have pray’d that thou, my son,
Might’st catch my latest breath,
That thy dear hands, and thine alone,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'To know that they miss’d me at home.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "When twilight approaches, the season
That ever is sacred to song,
Does some one repeat my name over,
And sigh that I tarry so long?
And is there a chord in the music
That’s miss’d when my voice is away,
And a chord in each heart that awaketh
Regret at my wearisome stay,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'Regret at my wearisome stay.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Do they sit me a chair near the table,
When evening’s home pleasures are nigh,
When the candles are lit in the parlor,
And the stars in the calm azure sky?
And when the “good-nights” are repeated,
And all lay them down to their sleep,
Do they think of the absent, and waft me
A whisper’d “good-night” while they weep,
A whisper’d “good-night” while they weep?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'In the West--in my own native land.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Then hail, dear Columbia, the land that we love,
Where flourishes Liberty’s tree;
The birth-place of Freedom, our own native home,
’Tis the land, ’tis the land of the free!
Yes, yes, yes, yes, yes, yes. Yes, yes, yes, yes, yes, yes,
The birth-place of Freedom, our own native home,
’Tis the land, ’tis the land of the free!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'Oh! the old farm-house, my childhood’s happy home.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Oh, the old farm-house, how I’ve sported round its hearth
With my sisters and brothers so dear;
How oft has it rung with our innocent mirth,
And hallow’d our soft evening-prayer;
But the old farm-house now is bowing to decay,
Its stones like dead friends lie apart;
But its dear, cherish’d image shall ne’er fade away", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'The sword of Bunker Hill.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "“Twas on that dread, immortal day,
I dared the Briton’s band,
A captain raised this blade on me,
I tore it from his hand;
And while the glorious battle raged,
It lighten’d freedom’s will,
For, boy, the God of Freedom bless’d", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'I am willing, brother, knowing that He doeth nothing wrong.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Tell my father when you greet him, that in death I pray’d for him,
Pray’d that I might one day meet him, in a world that’s free from
sin;
Tell my mother, God assist her, now that she is growing old,
Tell, her son would glad have kiss’d her, when his lips grew pale
and cold.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'And He will never forsake her--He has said so in His word.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "O my childern, Heaven bless them! they were all my life to me;
Would I could once more caress them, ere I sink beneath the sea;
’Twas for them I cross’d the ocean--what my hopes were I’ll not
tell,
But they have gain’d an orphan’s portion--yet He doeth all things
well.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'On victory or death.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Now, now, the dangerous storm is rolling,
Which treacherous kings confederate raise;
The dogs of war, let loose, are howling,
And lo! our fields and cities blaze;
And shall we basely view the ruin,
While lawless force, with guilty stride,
Spreads desolation far and wide,
With crimes and blood his hands embruing?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'To arms! to arms! ye brave, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "O Liberty! can man resign thee,
Once having felt thy generous flame?
Can dungeons, bolts, or bars confine thee?
Or whips thy noble spirit tame?
Too long the world has wept, bewailing
That falsehood’s dagger tyrants wield,
But freedom is our sword and shield,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'The boast of, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "The wine cup, the wine cup bring hither,
And fill you it up to the brim,
May the wreath they have won never wither
Nor the star of their glory grow dim,
May the service united ne’er sever,
And hold to their colors so true,
The army and navy forever,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'Echoes down the lake-side shore.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Now the night-bird’s song comes floating
Sweetly down the midnight air,
Waking all the depths, to listen
To the birds that thus should dare
To break the weird and solemn stillness,
That had reign’d so long before,
In the wood, and mead, and valley,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'On the silent lake-side shore.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Now the song comes swelling bolder,
And the boatman’s chant is heard,
Louder o’er the distant waters,
As it would outvie the bird;
But each song at last is finish’d,
And the bird to rest once more,
Leaves no sound to break the quiet", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'Of the happy lake-side shore.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Who can say there is no pleasure
Thus to walk the night alone,
Listening to the night-bird’s music,
Or the boatman’s solemn tone?
Where is there a spot more lovely,
Where the vail of night hangs o’er?
Where another place more lovely
Than this silent lake-side shore?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'Wait a little longer.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "There’s a good time coming, boys,
A good time coming;
There’s a good time coming, boys,
Wait a little longer;
The pen shall supersede the sword,
And right, not might, shall be the lord,
In the good time comidg;
Worth, not birth, shall rule mankind,
And be acknowledged stronger,
The proper impulse has been given,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'CONTENTS.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Seven Recipes to make BREAD,
Six Recipes to make BISCUITS or ROLLS,
Seventeen Recipes to make HOT BREAD and CAKES,
Fourteen Recipes for BREAKFAST DISHES,
Sixteen Recipes for Preparing BEEF for the Table,
Eleven Recipes for Preparing VEAL for the Table,
Fifteen Recipes for Preparing MUTTON for the Table,
Fourteen Recipes for Preparing PORK for the Table,
Twelve Recipes for Preparing POULTRY and GAME for the Table,
Ten Recipes for Preparing FISH for the Table,
Nine Recipes for NICE BREAKFAST DISHES,
Ten Recipes for SOUPS,
Eighteen Recipes for VEGETABLES,
Seven Recipes for SAUCES,
Eighteen Recipes for PIES,
Twenty-one Recipes for PUDDINGS,
Thirty Recipes for CAKES,
Five Recipes for TEA, COFFEE, and CHOCOLATE,
Twelve Recipes for JELLIES,
Sixteen Recipes for PRESERVES,
Eight Recipes to KEEP and DRY FRUITS,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'Misspelled words, below, were retained as printed:', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Children\'s songs', 'lyrics' => "Pg 12 - ‘permisson’ for ‘permission’
Pg 21 - ‘afface’ for ‘efface’
Pg 26 - ‘Jane’ for ‘Juney’
Pg 33 - ‘sororws’  for ‘sorrows’
Pg 40 - ‘tallk’ for ‘talk’
Pg 51 - ‘childern,’ possible misprint for ‘children’
Pg 57 - ‘gathere,’ for ‘gathered’ or ‘gather’
Pg 61 - ‘pnmpkins’ for ‘pumpkins’
Pg 69 - ‘comidg’ for ‘coming’
Advert, penultimate page, ‘BAEDLE’S’ for ‘BEADLE’S’", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/48494'),
    array('title' => 'I’d offer thee, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "I’ll leave thee in thy happiness
As one too dear to love;
As one I think on but to bless
As wretchedly I rove;
And oh! when sorrow’s cup I drink
All bitter though it be,
How sweet t’will be for me to think", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Comin’ thro’ the Rye.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Gin a body meet a body,
Comin’ thro’ the rye;
Gin a body kiss a body,
Need a body cry?
Ilka lassie has her laddie,
Nane they say ha’e I;
Yet a’ the lads they smile at me,
And what the waur am I?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Thou hast Wounded the Spirit.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Thou hast wounded the spirit that loved thee,
And cherished thine image for years;
Thou hast taught me at last to forget thee,
In secret, in silence, and tears,
As a young bird, when left by its mother
Its earliest pinions to try,
’Round the nest will still lingering hover,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'We Met by Chance.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "When evening brings the twilight hour,
I pass a lonely spot,
Where oft she comes to cull the flower,
We call “Forget-me-not.”
She never whispers go, nor stay;
She never whispers go, nor stay;
We met by chance, the usual way,
We met by chance, the usual way
We met by chance,
We met by chance,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'We met by chance, the usual way.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "Once, how, I can not well divine,
Unless by chance we kiss’d,
I found her lips were close to mine,
So I could not resist;
As neither whisper’d yea, nor nay,
As neither whisper’d yea, nor nay,
They met by chance, the usual way,
They met by chance, the usual way,
They met by chance,
They met by chance,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Changes must upon us come.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "For the step will lose its lightness,
And the hair be changed to grey;
Eyes once bright give up their luster,
And the hopes of youth decay
When all these have passed upon me,
And stern age has touched my brow,
Will the change find you unchanging?
Will you love me then as now?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'The Rose of Allendale.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "The morn was fair, the skies were clear,
No breath came o’er the sea,
When Mary left her highland cot,
And wandered forth with me;
Though flowers deck’d the mountain’s side,
And fragrance fill’d the vale,
By far the sweetest flower there,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Was the Rose of Allendale.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Where’er I wander’d, east or west,
Though fate began to lower,
A solace still was she to me,
In sorrow’s lonely hour;
When tempest lashed our gallant bark,
And rent her shivering sail,
One maiden form withstood the storm,
’Twas the Rose of Allendale.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Norah M’Shane.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "I’ve left Ballymornach a long way behind me,
To better my fortune I’ve cross’d the big sea;
But I’m sadly alone, not a creature to mind me,
And faith I’m as wretch’d as wretch’d can be;
I think of the buttermilk, fresh as the daisy,
The beautiful halls and the emerald plain,
And, ah! don’t I oftentimes think myself crazy", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'About that black-eyed rogue, Norah M’Shane.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "I sigh for the turf-pile so cheerfully burning,
When barefoot I trudged it from toiling afar,
When I toss’d in the light the thirteen I’d been earning,
And whistled the tune of “Erin go Bragh.”
In truth, I believe that I’m half broken-heart’d,
To my country and love I must get back again
For I’ve never been happy at all since I part’d", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'A Yankee Ship, and a Yankee Crew.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "A Yankee ship, and a Yankee crew,
Tally hi ho! you know!
O’er the bright blue waves like a sea-bird flew,
Singing hey! aloft and alow!
Her sails are spread to the fairy breeze!
The spray as sparkling thrown from her prow,
Her flag is the proudest that floats on the seas,
When homeward she’s steering now!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Sammy Slap, the Bill-Sticker.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "I’m Sammy Slap, the bill-sticker, and you must all agree, sirs,
I sticks to business like a trump, and business sticks to me, sirs;
The low folks call me plasterer, but they deserve a banging,
Because, genteelly speaking, why my trade is paper-hanging,
CHORUS.--With my paste, paste, paste,
Oh, all the world is puffing,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Roll on, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "But his grave I’ll seek out until morning appears,
And weep for my lover so brave,
I’ll embrace the cold turf and wash with my tears
The flowers that bloom o’er his grave;
But never again shall my bosom know joy
With my Edwin I hope to be soon;
Lovers shall weep o’er the grave where we sleep,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Mary of Argyle.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "I have heard the mavis singing,
His love-song to the morn,
I have seen the dew-drops clinging,
To the rose just newly born;
But a sweeter song has cheered me,
At the evening’s gentle close,
I have seen an eye still brighter,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Oft in the Stilly Night.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Oft in the stilly night,
Ere slumber’s chain has bound me,
Fond mem’ry brings the light
Of other days around me;
The smiles, the tears of childhood’s years,
The words of love then spoken,
The eyes that shone, now dimm’d and gone,
The cheerful hearts now broken!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Napolitaine.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Napolitaine, I am dreaming of thee,
I’m hearing thy foot-falls so joyous and free,
Thy dark, flashing eyes are intwining me yet,
Thy voice with its music I ne’er can forget;
I’m far from the land of thy own sunny home,
Alone in this wide world with sorrow I roam;
In the halls of the gay or wherever it be,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Still Napolitaine, I’m dreaming of thee.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Napolitaine, art thou thinking of me?
Hath absence not banished my memory from thee?
Remember our meetings, their whispers to keep,
When bright eyes were calling all lovers to sleep?
And yet would I not have a shade on thy brow,
As bright as though ’twere lit is thine on me now,
For ’tis memory that brings all thy beauty to me;
Still, Napolitaine, I’m dreaming of thee,
Napolitaine, I’m dreaming of thee,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'The Gay Cavalier.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "’Twas a beautiful night, and the stars shone bright,
And the moon o’er the waters played,
When a gay cavalier to a bower drew near,
A maid to serenade;
To tenderest words he swept the chords,
And many a sigh heaved he,
While o’er and o’er he fondly swore,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Last Week I Took a Wife.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Last week I took a wife,
And when I first did woo her,
I vow’d to stick through life,
Like Cobler’s wax unto her,
But soon we went to some mishap,
To loggerheads together,
And when my wife began to strap,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'The Monks of old.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Many have told of the monks of old,
What a saintly race they were,
But ’tis most true, that a merrier crew
Could scarce be found elswhere!
For they sung and laugh’d, and the rich wine quaff’d,
And lived on the daintiest cheer!
For they laugh’d ha! ha! and they quaff’d ha! ha!
And lived on the daintiest cheer!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Dermot Astore.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Oh! Dermot Astore, between waking and sleeping,
I heard thy dear voice, and I wept to its lay;
Every pulse of my heart the sweet measure was keeping,
’Til Killarney’s wild echoes had borne it away.
Oh, tell me, my own love, is this our last meeting?
Shall we wander no more in Killarney’s green bowers,
To watch the bright sun o’er the dim hills retreating,
And the wild stag at rest in his bed of spring flowers?
CHORUS.--Oh! Dermot Astore, &c.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Fondly I’m dreaming ever of thee.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Ever of thee, when sad and lonely,
Wandering afar, my soul joy’d to dwell;
Ah! then I felt I loved thee only;
All seem’d to fade before affection’s spell;
Years have not chill’d the love I cherish;
True as the stars hath my heart been to thee;", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Round the grave of Uncle True.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "The chaplet wreathed by Gerty’s hand,
Of roses white and red,
Unheeded in their freshness lie
Above his lowly head;
And the evening cricket’s chirp is heard,
When falls the pearly dew,
And the lamps of heaven shine brightly down,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'William of the Ferry.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Near Clyde’s gay stream there lived a maid,
Whose mind was chaste and pure;
Content she lived in humble life,
Beloved by all who knew her;
Protected ’neath her parents’ roof,
Her time pass’d on quite merry;
She loved and was beloved again,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Are gleaming o’er the earth all so calm and still.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Wake! Dinah, wake! the gentle breeze is blowing,
The bird’s notes still hush’d in the grove;
The ivy around the sturdy oak is growing,
Clinging fondly as though something still to love
The shining river views it as onward rolling by,
And as on golden sands the ripples break,
In sweet enchanting tones it seems to murmur,
Wake, now, my dearest Dinah, wake!
CHORUS.--Wake! Dinah, wake, &c.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'The Old Arm-Chair.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "I love it, I love it! and who shall dare
To chide me for loving that old arm-chair?
I’ve treasured it long as a sainted prize,
I’ve bedew’d it with tears, I’ve embalm’d it with sighs!
’Tis bound by a thousand bands to my heart;
Not a tie will break, not a link will start;
Would you know the spell?--a mother sat there!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Ned Seguin and Frazer’ll be here:', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Anguera has promis’d to bring his Guitar,
Rametti will play on the Flute,
So I’m trying a second to ’Young Lochinvar,’
Which Miss Stone will perform on her Lute!”
Oh! beware, young men, of a musical wife,
For Eliza’s fine voice is the plague of my life!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'How I long’d for a cup of green tea:', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "But, alas, neither tea nor repose could I get,
For Keyser, and Lange, were there,
And my wife was performing a fav’rite quartette,
So I went to the Club in despair,
Oh! beware, young men, of a musical wife,
For Eliza’s fine voice is the plague of my life!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'To Eliza--whilst singing a glee.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "But, surrounded, alas! by her musical choir
My wife could not think of my brother;
So the luckless appointment was toss’d in the fire,
And the office--was given to _another_,
Oh! beware, young men, of a musical wife,
For Eliza’s fine voice is the plague of my life!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'The Tail iv Me Coat.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "I larned me reading an’ writing,
At Ballyragget where I wint to school,
’Twas there I first took to fighting,
With the schoolmaster Misther O’Toole;
He and I there had many a scrimmage,
The divil a copy I wrote,
But not a gossoon in the village,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Dare thread on the tail iv me coat.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "I an illigant hand was at courting,
For lessons I took in the art,
Till Cupid, that blaggard, while sporting,
A big arrow sint smack through me heart;
Miss O’Connor, I lived straight fornnist her,
And tindher lines to her I wrote,
Who dare say a black word against her,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Why I’d thread on the tail iv his coat.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "A bog-trotter wan, Mickey Mulvany,
He tried for to coax her away;
He had money an’ I hadn’t any,
So a challenge I sint him wan day;
Next morning we met at Killhealy,
The Shannon we cross’d in a boat,
There I lather’d him with me shillely,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'For he trod on the tail iv me coat.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "Me fame spread through the nation,
Folks flock for to gaze upon me,
All cry out without hesitation,
“Och, yer a fightin’ man, Mickey Magee!”
I fought with the Finegan faction,
We bate all the Murphies afloat,
If inclined for a row or a ruction,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'A rare old plant is the ivy green.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "Fast he stealeth on, though he wears no wings,
And a staunch old head hath he;
How closely he twineth--how tightly he clings
To his friend, the huge oak tree!
And slily he traileth along the ground,
And his leaves he gently waves,
As he joyously hugs, and crawleth round", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Kind Relations.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "We all have our share of the ups and the downs,
Whatever our rank or station;
And he’s sure to get the most scoffs and frowns,
Who depends on his kind relations;
For it’s all very well once or twice to drop in,
To ask for a trifling favor,
But on the third time they are sure to begin,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Never to lend or borrow.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "I thought in my sister to find a friend,
But soon she undeceived me,
By saying--“These are not times too lend,
I would, if I could, relieve thee.”
“A trifle, dear sister, would keep me afloat,
I shall sink if you do not arrange it.”
She said she’d not less than a twenty-pound note,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'The Ocean Burial.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "“Oh, bury me not in the deep, deep sea,”
The words came low and mournfully,
From the pallid lips of a youth who lay
On his cabin couch at the close of day;
He had wasted and pined till o’er his brow
Death’s shade had slowly pass’d, and now
Where the land and his fond loved home were nigh,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'They had gather’d around him to see him die.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "“Oh, bury me not in the deep, deep sea,
Where the billowing shroud will swell o’er me;
Where no light will break through the dark cold wave,
And no sunbeam rest upon my grave;
It matters not, I have often been told
Where the body shall lie when the heart is cold,
Yet grant, oh, grant this boon to me,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Oh, bury me not in the deep, deep sea.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "“For in fancy I’ve listen’d to the well-known words,
The free wild winds and the songs of the birds;
I have thought of home, of cot, and of bower,
And of scenes that I loved in childhood’s hour,
I had even hoped to be laid, when I died,
In the churchyard there on the green hill-side,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'The Minute Gun at Sea.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Let him who sighs in sadness hear,
Rejoice to know a friend is near!
What heavenly sounds are those I hear?
What being comes the gloom to cheer?
When in the storm on Columbia’s coast,
The night-watch guards his weary post,
From thoughts of danger free!
To mark some vessel’s dusky form,
And hears amid the howling storm,
The minute gun at sea!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'And the love-light in thine eye.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "The place is little changed, Mary,
The day is bright as then;
The lark’s loud song is in my ear,
And the corn is green again!
But I miss the soft clasp of your hand,
And your warm breath on my cheek,
And I still keep listening for the words", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'With your baby on your breast.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "I’m very lonely now, Mary,
For the poor make no new friends;
But O, they love them better far,
The few our Father sends!
And you were all I had, Mary,
My blessing and my pride;
There’s nothing left to care for now,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Though you can’t hear me now.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "I thank you for that smile, Mary,
When your heart was fit to break;
When the hunger pain was gnawing there,
And you hid it, for my sake;
I bless you for the pleasant word,
When your heart was sad and sore;
O, I’m thankful you are gone, Mary,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Where grief can’t reach you more.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "I’m bidding you a long farewell,
My Mary, kind and true,
But I’ll not forget you, darling,
In the land I’m going to;
They say there’s bread and work for all,
And the sun shines always there,
But I’ll not forget old Ireland,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'The Rat-catcher’s Daughter.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Not long ago in Vestminster there lived a rat-catcher’s daughter,
And yet she didn’t live in Vestminster, ’cause she loved ’tother
side of the water,
Her father caught rats--and she sold sprats all about and around
that quarter,
And the gentle folks all took off their hats to the putty little", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Rat-catcher’s daughter.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Now lily vite sand ran in her ’ead, as she went along Strand, oh,
She forgot as she’d got sprats on her ’ead and cried, D’ye you
want any lily vite sand, oh?
The folks amaz’d all thought her craz’d, as she went along the
Strand, oh,
To see a gal with sprats on her ’ead, cry, D’ye vant any lily
vhite sand, oh?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'A chary old soul is he.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "Of Sack and Canary he never doth fail,
And all the year round there is brewing of ale;
Yet he never aileth, he quaintly doth say,
While he keeps to his sober six flagons a day;
But ho! ho! ho! his nose doth show", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'How oft the black Jack to his lips doth go.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Dame Margery sits in her own still room,
A matron sage is she;
From thence oft at Curfew is wafted a fume
She says it is “Rosemarie:”
She says it is “Rosemarie:”
But there’s a small cupboard behind the back stair,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'And Margery is often heard to declare:', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "“She ought to be settled in life!”
“She ought to be settled in life!”
But Margery has (so the maids say) a tongue,
And she’s not very handsome, and not very young;
So somehow it ends with a shake of the head,
And Simon he brews him a tankard instead;
While ho! ho! ho! he will chuckle and crow,
What! marry old Margery? no! no! no!
While ho! ho! ho! he will chuckle and crow,
What! marry old Margery? no! no! no!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50878'),
    array('title' => 'Smile on me to-day.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Though ’tis sad to leave you, darling,
I must no more stay,
Think of me, Norina, darling,
When I’m far away;
And, although to part brings sadness,
Keep your young heart light and free,
Your sweet face adorn with gladness,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'Don’t you cry so, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "Don’t you cry so, Norah, darling,
Wipe those tears away,
Don’t you cry so, Norah, darling,
Smile on me to-day;
When from work I rest a-weary,
All my thoughts on you will be,
And my life will not seem dreary,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'In the Cottage by the Sea, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "What though years rolled above me,
Though ’mid fairer scenes I roam,
Yet I ne’er shall cease to love thee,
Childhood’s dear and happy home!
And when life’s long day is closing,
Oh! how pleasant it would be;
On some faithful heart reposing", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'Through his locks of grayish brown:', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "“I’ll tell you, Kate, what I think,” said he,
“We’re the happiest folks in town.”
“I know,” said Kate, “that we all work hard
Work and health go together I’ve found,
For there’s Mrs. Bell does not work at all,
And she’s sick the whole year round,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'The old brown cot, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Though I may view the fairest land
On which the sun in glory beams,
And dwell in climes more beautiful
Than poets visit in their dreams,
Still will affection linger round
That loved and consecrated spot,
And tears will fall as I go back", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'Come gang awa’ wi’ me.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Oh! tarry not, my only love,
I’ve pledged myself to thee,
And by yon stars that shine above,
Forever thine I’ll be;
’Tis mony a night sin’ first we met
Beneath the greenwood tree,
Then say, ere yonder stars have set,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'Whispering to each other very soft and low.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "I’ve been roaming, roaming o’er the dewy grass,
Gemm’d with fairy blossoms waving as I pass,
For the breeze was flitting o’er the grassy lea,
Whispering many a story to the flowers and me;
For the breeze was flitting o’er the grassy lea,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'I’ll Hang my Harp on a Willow-Tree.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "I’ll hang my harp on a willow-tree,
I’ll off to the wars again,
My peaceful home has no charms for me,
The battle-field no pain;
The lady I love will soon be a bride
With a diadem on her brow;
Oh, why did she flatter my boyish pride,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'Oh, had I, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "Then I’ll hide in my breast every selfish care;
I’ll flush my pale cheeks with wine;
When smiles awake the bridal pair
I’ll hasten to give them mine;
I’ll laugh and I’ll sing, though my heart may bleed,
And I’ll walk in the festal train,
And if I survive it I’ll mount my steed,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'It would set the gals a talking.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "She’s fond of kissing, that I know,
So often as I meet her,
She says, “Kiss me quick, and let me go,
You’ll love me all the better.”
At evening when the room was dark,
And time was getting later,
I thought I’d steal a kiss from her,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'Is the little low room where I courted my wife.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "That low, humble room seem’d a palace of light,
As love held his torch, and illumined the scene,
With glory of state and profusion bedight,
Where I was a monarch, my darling a queen;
Ourselves were our subjects, pledged loyal were each,
And which should love best was our heartiest strife;
What tales could it tell, if possessing a speech,
That little low room where I courted my wife,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'That little low room where I courted my wife.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Warm vows has it heard, the warmest e’er spoke,
Where lips have met lips in holy embrace,
Where feelings that never to utterance woke,
It saw oft reveal’d in a duplicate face;
The sweet hours hasten’d, how quickly they flew,
With fervent devotion and ecstasy rife!
Our hearts throbb’d the hours, but how I ne’er knew,
In the little low room where I courted my wife,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'In the little low room where I courted my wife.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "26
Long years have since pass’d o’er my darling and I,
The roses have vanish’d away from her cheek,
But the merciless moments, as onward they fly,
Leave love still undimm’d in her bosom so meek;
That love is the light to our faltering feet,
Our comfort in hours with sorrowing rife,
Our blessings in joy, as with joy ’twas replete,
In the little low room where I courted my wife,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'With their last blessing, pass’d it on to you.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "Stand by the flag, though death-shots round it rattle;
And underneath its waving folds have met,
In all the dread array of sanguine battle,
The quivering lance and glittering bayonet,
Stand by the flag, all doubt and treason scorning,
Believe with courage firm and faith sublime
That it will float until the eternal morning", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'My Massa had a color’d gal--', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "He brought her from the South,
Her hair it curl’d so very tight,
She could not shut her mouth,
Her eyes they were so very small,
They both ran into one,
And when a fly lit in her eye,
’Twas like a June-bug in the sun.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'She could not shut her mouth.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Her nose, it was so very long,
It turn’d up like a squash,
And when she got her dander up,
She made me laugh, by gosh!
Old Massa had no hooks or nails
Or nothing else like that,
So on this darkie’s nose he used", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'Den commence, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "When I go to promenade,
I look so fine an’ gay,
I hab to take de dogs along
Te keep de gals away;
My busom am so full ob lub,
Dis darkey can not rest,
So I’ll bid you all good-by, at last,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'And I’m not myself at all.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Th’other day I went confessin’, and I ask’d the father’s blessin’
But says I, “Don’t give me one entirely,
For I fretted so last year,
But the half o’ me is here,
So give the other half to Molly Brierly
Oh! I’m not myself at all.”", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'Oh! I’m not myself at all.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "I’ll be not myself at all, Molly dear, Molly dear,
’Till you my own I call.
Since a change o’er me there came, shure you might change your name,
And ’twould just come to the same, Molly dear, Molly dear,
Oh! ’twould just come the same;
For if you and I were one, all confusion would be gone,
And ’twould simplify the mather entirely,
And ’twould save us so much bother
When we’d both be one another,
So listen now to rayson, Molly Brierly,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'I wish he would decide.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "I’ve thrown out many a hint, Mamma,
I’ve spoke of other beaux,
I’ve talk’d about domestic life,
And sung “They don’t propose.”
Then if he means to break, Mamma,
My passion and my pride,
Unconquer’d yet I’ll scorn regret,
Unconquer’d yet I’ll scorn regret,
Although he won’t decide,
Although he won’t decide,
Although he won’t decide,
Unconquer’d yet I’ll scorn regret,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'Had blighted childhood’s truth.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "We were boys and girls together,
When the step was firm and light,
When the voice was clear and ringing,
And the laughing eyes were bright;
Then our love sought no concealment,
And our bosoms knew no art,
And the sunshine of our childhood", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'Oh, would I were a boy again, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "’Tis vain to mourn that years have shown
How false these fairy visions were,
Or murmur that mine eyes have known
The burden of a fleeting tear;
But still the heart will fondly cling
To hopes no longer prized as truth,
And memory still delights to bring", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'Song of the Farmer.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "I have cattle that feed in the valley,
And herds that graze on the hill,
And I pride in the fruits of my labor,
For I’m lord of the land that I till,
I have plow’d the rough hill and the meadow
Till feeble with age and with toil,
And I know before long that another", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'They don’t wish Me at Home.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "They don’t wish me at home, though they miss me,
’Twould be a great assurance, I fear,
To think for a moment some soft one
Would say, “I wish Toby were here.”
Although the poor tom-cat at the fireside
May think of poor me as I roam,
Oh yes, I’d be green beyond measure", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'With his sprig of shillelah, and shamrock so green.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Who has e’er had the luck to see Donnybrook fair?
An Irishman all in his glory is there,
With his sprig of shillelah and shamrock so green;
His clothes spick and span new, without e’er a speck,
A neat Barcelona tied round his neck;
He goes to his tent, and spends his half-crown,
He meets with a friend who for love knocks him down,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'Upon a truss of hay.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "But when that hay was blooming grass,
And deck’d with flowers of spring,
No flowers were there that could compare
With the lovely girl I sing,
As she sat in the Low Back’d Car, the man at the turnpike bar,
Good-natured old soul, never ask’d for his toll,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'But look’d after the Low Back’d Car.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "In battle’s wild commotion,
The proud and mighty Mars,
With hostile scythes, demands his tythes,
Of death in warlike scars;
But Peggy, peaceful goddess,
Has darts in her bright eye,
That knock men down in the market-town,
As right and left they fly;
As she sits in the Low Back’d Car, than battle more dangerous far,
For the doctor’s art, cannot cure the heart", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'To home, dear home again.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "The sailor’s wife sinks down to rest,
But dreams disturb her sleep,
She starts to hear the hollow wind,
And turns aside to weep;
She clasps her baby, and she prays,
Through tears, like falling rain,
“O God! restore the mariner,
To home, dear home again.”", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'Upon my Gipsy tent.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "I wander freely as the fawn
Which hath not learnt to fear
The death-cry of the hunter’s voice
Resounding far and near;
And bounding through the woods
I feel as if I too could soar,
Bird-like, upon the wings of joy,
And sing for evermore!
Come out, ye pent-up toilers!
Come, from city dark and drear,
And see what gladness Nature has
In all her beauties here;
And ere ye seek your homes, ye’ll say,
Your time has well been spent,
And wish that all the world
Could be, one happy Gipsy tent;
And wish that all the world", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'Indian Hunter.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Oh, why does the white man follow my path, like the hound on the
tiger’s track?
Does the flush of my dark cheek waken his wrath? does he covet the
bow at my back?
He has rivers and seas, where the billows and breeze", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'Nelly dear, farewell.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "In the Hazel Dell my Nelly’s sleeping,
Where the flowers wave,
And the silent stars are nightly weeping,
O’er poor Nelly’s grave,
Hopes that once my bosom fondly cherished,
Smile no more for me,
Every dream of joy alas has perished,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'To sail o’er silent seas again.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "When o’er the ocean’s dreary plain,
With toil her destined port to gain,
Our gallant ship has near’d the strand,
We claim our own, our native land,
We claim our own, our native land;
Sweet is the seaman’s joyous shout,
“Land ahead! land ahead! look out! look out!”
Around on deck we gayly fly,
“Land ahead! land ahead!” with joy we cry;
Yon beacon light directs our way,
While grateful vows to Heaven we pay,
And soon our long-lost joys renew,
And bid the boisterous main adieu,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'Of orange grove and bower--', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Of winds that wake soft melody
From leaf and blooming flower;
And you may prize those far-off skies,
But tempt not me to roam;
In sweet content my days are spent,
Then wherefore leave my home?
In sweet content my days are spent,
Then wherefore leave my home?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'They’re kinder still at home.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Had you been rear’d by Alpine hills,
Or lived in Alpine dells,
You’d prize, like me, our mountain rills,
Nor fear the torrent swells;
It matters not how drear the spot
How proud or poor the dome,
Love still retains some deathless chains,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'Would I Were With Thee.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Would I were with thee, ev’ry day and hour
Which now I pass so sadly far from thee,
Would that my form possess’d the magic power
To follow where my heavy heart would be;
Whate’er thy lot o’er land or sea,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'Would I were with thee eternally.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Would I were with thee, when the world forgetting
Thy weary limbs upon the turf are thrown,
While bright and red our evening sun is setting,
And all thy thoughts belong to heaven alone;
While happy dreams thy thoughts employ,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'Would I were with thee in thy joy.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Would I were with thee, when no longer feigning
The hurried laugh, that stifles back a sigh,
When thy young lip pours forth its sweet complaining,
And tears have quench’d the light within thine eye;
When all seems dark and sad below,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'On the ruin thou hast made.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Canst thou think, as thou dost listen
To thy children’s artless songs,
Of that moment when their fond hearts,
First shall feel their mother’s wrongs?
Ha! thou shrinkest like the lightning,
To thy bosom fell remorse shall dart,
And thou yet shall know the anguish
Which hath broken my poor heart;
And thou yet shall know the anguish", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'Paddy on the Canal.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "When I landed in sweet Philadelphia, the weather was pleasant and
clear,
I did not stay long in the city, so quickly I shall let you hear.
I did not stay long in the city, for it happen’d to be in the fall,
I never reef’d a sail in my rigging, till I anchor’d out on the
canal.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'So kindly I’ll bid you adieu.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "When I came to this wonderful rampire, it fill’d me with the
greatest surprise,
To see such a great undertaking, on the like I never open’d my
eyes;
To see full a thousand brave fellows at work among mountains so
tall,
To dig through the valleys so level, through rocks for to cut a
canal.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'But now she is far, far away, &c.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "A darkey trader came one day,
And bought my gal from me,
And left me here alone to mourn
Beneaf de cypress-tree;
It fill’d my heart wid grief an’ pain,
To think dey’d treat me so,
But I live in hopes to meet again", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'Changes:', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "“evneing’s” to “evening’s”: ... bright as evening’s glow,...
“stara” to “star”s: ... Then say ere yonder stars have set,...
“brookleth” to “brooklet”: ... Where the brooklet singeth o’er...
“permisson” to “permission”: ... permission of FIRTH, POND & CO.,
(3 occasions)
“shsll” to “shall”: ... When shall I be a bride,...
“companton” to “companion”: ... my trusting companion, ...
“pleaures” to “pleasure”: ...  for her comfort with pleasure,
“BAEDLE’S” to “BEADLE’S”: ... BEADLE’S DIME MILITARY SONG BOOK,...", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/50041'),
    array('title' => 'When the banner we hail is no longer unrolled.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "Black treason shall never put foot on the flag                    6
That floated the blast when Cornwallis was taken;
And ere it give place to a Palmetto rag,
The dead on the fields of their fame will awaken,
Oh, shall it be furled,
Bringing night on the world,
While the house of our fathers in ruin is hurled!
The brigand and traitor may hear a reply", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'AIR--_To the West--to the West_.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Children\'s songs', 'lyrics' => "To the field! to the field! where our comrades now stand,
For the cause of the Union, the life of our land!
Where the sons of the North for their liberties fight,
And the men of all nations combine for the right;
Where the children of Erin with Britons conjoin,
And the Gaul and the German press loin unto loin;
And the men of Italia and Hungary true
Are surrounding the Flag of the Red, White and Blue!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'It must rise like the tempest, and surge like the sea.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "’Tis a cause--’tis a cause that makes heroes of all;
For the Union, the Union to conquer or fall!
’Tis the cause of mankind, ’tis the cause of the world,
That our swords are unsheathed for, our banners unfurled!
And the heart of the vassal on Muscovite plains,
And the soul of the Polander, weary of chains,
And the pulse of the Magyar, the brain of the Greek,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'Only when Rebels no longer contend--', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "Only when Union, Union, Union!
Shall weld a new bond that no Treason can rend!
When the dread struggle is over, over,
And Liberty’s duty is fairly done,
We will offer our hands to the vanquished, vanquished,
And bid them be once more the Many in One!
Sheathe the sword, Northland! Northland! Northland!
Only when Treason no longer lowers!
Only when Union, Union, Union!
For all the great Future, is ours, still ours!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'And quickly clear the way.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "This Union, which so long hath been
The shelt’ring home of all
Fair Freedom’s valiant, holy band,
Shall not by traitors fall;
But it will stand, through storm and strife,
The home of Freedom’s band,
And naught shall cause its overthrow,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'In tints of the White, Red and Blue.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "And far in the blue dome of heaven,
Were stars with a soft, holy ray,
That have shone in an unbroken union
While ages have mouldered away;
And Freedom, when journeying hither,
The earth with its blessings to strew,
Has gathered these trophies of glory,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'AIR--_Sprig of Shillaly_.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Spirituals', 'lyrics' => "Oh, brave is the soul of a true Union man!
He arms for the battle--he springs to the van,
To the war-shout of freemen--the Northern Hurrah!
His heart bears no malice--his lips have no lie!
For the old Constitution his pulses beat high;
And in camp or in action, in march or at rest,
’Tis the love of Our Union that leaps from his breast
In the war-shout of freemen--the Northern Hurrah!
Hurrah! hurrah! hurrah!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'And leaving behind him our patriot slain.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Thou hast not forgotten the friends that you parted,
To battle for country, for God, and our right;
And sad are thy tears for the lone broken-hearted,
Who silently languish in grief's fearful night;
Sweet Maid of Erin, they welcome thy footsteps,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'The Star-gemmed Flag our Sisters’ zones shall be.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "A seven-years’ war was past and gone,
And many a heart was left forlorn;
But prouder o’er our Western shore,
Its Eagle-Bird was seen to soar;
And in his talons, as he flies,
He bears our Flag of victories;
And ever shall that Banner be,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'The Star-gemmed Flag of brave hearts and the free.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "And on the land, and on the sea,
Wherever roam her sons from thee,
Our Nation’s Flag shall ope its fold,
The loved and honored of the world;
For right, not might shall be its claim,
As “Flag of Freedom” is its name;
While Armies shall our emblem bear,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'On the branch of the first sycamore tree.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Your pockets they are empty, poor Jeff. Davis,
And of gold you are very much in need,
While starvation mounts the throne close beside you,
And secession has just gone to seed;
And, oh, what a sad mistake, Jeff. Davis,
To think with cotton all alone
You could frighten Uncle Sam, poor Jeff. Davis,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'Unto her brave boy’s last wild breath.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Oh, proudly will his mother see
Her Country wreathe his hero-tomb,
And many a Spring nurse tenderly,
With nature’s tears, the garland’s bloom!
How sweet will be the song of praise,
Where his dear relics peaceful lie!
How grand--away exultant thoughts!
Oh God! he must not, _must not_ die!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'And there’s life in a hero’s grave.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "When the cause we serve is a righteous cause,
And the flag we bear unstained,
And our patriot steel, for the common weal,
We lift, with hands unchained,
There is never a power can bar our path,
Nor force can bid us turn,
Till we clasp our brands, with a victor’s hands,
Or they lie on the funeral urn!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'Shall wrest it from their sons.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Shade of heroic Washington!
Still guard our Native Land!
Rebuke, rebuke each wavering one,
Direct each ardent hand!
Oh, mother of a matchless race!
Hear our united cry!
’Tis noble in your cause to live,
And nobler still to die!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'Abram Lincoln O.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "When Abe took charge of our plantation,
Secesh was making preparation
To steal the half for raising cotton,
But soon found out his scheme was rotten;
Old Abe Lincoln O, Old Abe Lincoln O,
No mercy show the thieving foe,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'Is the brave young Zouave’s pride.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "The camp is the place for me,
When my country calls me there,
To fight for the Flag of the Free,
I’d live on homeliest fare;
When the tattoo beats at night,
And the reveille in the morn,
And the Zouave’s heart is light", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'We will ever be true to the Stripes and the Stars.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Three cheers for our Union, the land of our birth;
’Tis the fortress of freedom, the hope of the earth;
Arouse you, ye sons of the East and the West,
To defend it, though blood flow from each gallant breast;
Remember, a noble old poet has said,
’Tis sweet, for our country, to sleep with the dead.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'In the van of the host, on the blood-redden’d ground.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "Three cheers for Columbia, the queen of the world,
To the wind’s every quarter her flag be unfurled;
We have bowed at her feet, in the day of her pride,
Shall we basely desert her, now she is defied?
No! millions of voices will instant reply,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'And spreads her banner to the day.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "While to His Throne our hearts are swelling,
Freedom, and Law, and Truth, and Right,
May God defend by his own might,
By his right arm the treason quelling
Ye loyal sons, and true,
Sons of the brave and free,
Join hearts, join hands, to strike anew", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'AIR--_The Star-Spangled Banner_.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Oh God bless our land, and united once more,
May we gather true wisdom from war’s desolation;
From the thick curling smoke, and the fierce cannon’s roar,
Let peace in her beauty rise and smile on our nation;
To show to the world that peace is unfurled,
And war from Columbia forever is hurled,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'Still sails ’neath the banner of the Red, White and Blue.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Great God bless our land, for ’tis dyed in the gore
Of the good and the brave of a nation’s defenders;
Oh! may death’s fearful havoc molest us no more,
And Thy love fill the bosom as passion surrenders;
To show to the world that love is unfurled,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'That the proud Ark, etc.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Oh God bless our land--may our eagle still fly,
And gaze on Columbia in proud adoration;
Let the sunlight of truth ever flash from his eye,
Urging freemen to duty in dark tribulation;
To show to the world that truth is unfurled,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'AIR--_Old Oaken Bucket_.', 'author' => 'Various', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Oh, fair is the orchard, with russet fruit laden,
And bright is the cornfield, all golden with grain,
And sweet is the garden, where matron and maiden,
Sit listening at eve to the whippowil’s strain;
But fairer, and brighter, and sweeter, and dearer,
Are the orchards of crimson, the fields of bright red,
And the flow’rets immortal that hallow the wearer,
Whose blood for his country is loyally shed,
In the orchards of Union, the cornfields of Union,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/49628'),
    array('title' => 'To set thy captive children free.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Spirituals', 'lyrics' => "Arouse! and let each hill and glen
With prayer to the high heavens ring out,
Till all our land with freeborn men,
May join in one triumphant shout,
That freedom’s banner does not wave
Its folds above a single slave.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'But the grief of that mother can never be known.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "The mildew of slavery has blighted each blossom,
That ever has bloomed in her pathway below;
It has froze every fountain that gushed in her bosom,
And chilled her heart’s verdure with pitiless woe;
Her parents, her kindred, all crushed by oppression;
Her husband still doomed in its desert to stay;", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'She must weep as she treads on her desolate way.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "O, slave mother, hope! see--the nation is shaking!
The arm of the Lord is awake to thy wrong!
The slave-holder’s heart now with terror is quaking,
Salvation and Mercy to Heaven belong!
Rejoice, O, rejoice! for the child thou art rearing,
May one day lift up its unmanacled form,
While hope, to thy heart, like the rain-bow so cheering,
Is born, like the rain-bow, ’mid tempest and storm.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'AIR--Sweet Afton.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Come back to me, mother! why linger away
From thy poor little blind boy, the long weary day!
I mark every footstep, I list to each tone,
And wonder my mother should leave me alone!
There are voices of sorrow and voices of glee,
But there’s no one to joy or to sorrow with me;
For each hath of pleasure and trouble his share,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'And none for the poor little blind boy will care.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "My mother, come back to me! close to thy breast
Once more let thy poor little blind one be pressed;
Once more let me feel thy warm breath on my cheek,
And hear thee in accents of tenderness speak!
O mother! I’ve no one to love me--no heart
Can bear like thine own in my sorrows a part;
No hand is so gentle, no voice is so kind!
O! none like a mother can cherish the blind!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'AIR--Marseilles Hymn.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Ye sons of freemen, wake to sadness,
Hark! hark! what myriads bid you rise;
Three millions of our race in madness
Break out in wails, in bitter cries,
Break out in wails, in bitter cries;
Must men whose hearts now bleed with anguish,
Yes, trembling slaves in freedom’s land,
Endure the lash, nor raise a hand?
Must nature ’neath the whip-cord languish?
Have pity on the slave,
Take courage from God’s word;", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'Pray on, pray on, all hearts resolved--these captives shall be free.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "The fearful storm--it threatens lowering,
Which God in mercy long delays;
Slaves yet may see their masters cowering,
While whole plantations smoke and blaze!
While whole plantations smoke and blaze;
And we may now prevent the ruin,
Ere lawless force with guilty stride", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'Toil on, toil on, all hearts resolved--these captives shall be free.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "O Liberty! can man e’er bind thee?
Can overseers quench thy flame?
Can dungeons, bolts, or bars confine thee,
Or threats thy Heaven-born spirit tame?
Or threats thy Heaven-born spirit tame;
Too long the slave has groaned, bewailing
The power these heartless tyrants wield;
Yet free them not by sword or shield,
For with men’s hearts they’re unavailing;
Have pity on the slave;
Take courage from God’s word;
Toil on! toil on! all hearts resolved--these captives shall be free!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'AIR--Oh! Susannah.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Lo! the Northern Star is beaming
With a new and glorious light,
And its cheering radiance streaming
Through the clouds of misty night!
Freemen! in your great Endeavor,
’Tis a signal hung on high,
And will guide us on forever,
Like a banner in the sky!
Oh! Star of Freedom,
’Tis the star for me;
’Twill lead me off to Canada,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'There I will be free.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "’Tis the star that Freedom claimeth
As her emblem pure and bright,
And we watch it as it flameth
“In the dark and troubled night:”
While we march to battle glorious,
With our weapons, Truth and Love,
Freedom, as she proves victorious,
Hails the _Banner_ Star above!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'Cold blows the wind and the night’s coming on.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "Call me not indolent beggar and bold enough,
Fain would I learn both to knit and to sew;
I’ve two little brothers at home, when they’re old enough,
They will work hard for the gifts you bestow;
Pity, kind gentlemen, friends of humanity,
Cold blows the wind, and the night’s coming on;
Give me some food for my mother in charity,
Give me some food, and then I will be gone.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'AIR--Long, long ago.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Where are the friends that to me were so dear,
Long, long ago--long ago!
Where are the hopes that my heart used to cheer,
Long, long ago--long ago!
I am degraded, for man was my foe,
Friends that I loved in the grave are laid low,
All hope of freedom hath fled from me now,
Long, long ago--long, long ago!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'AIR--Is there a heart, &c.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "Is there a man that never sighed
To set the prisoner free?
Is there a man that never prized
The sweets of liberty?
Then let him, let him breathe unseen,
Or in a dungeon live;
Nor never, never know the sweets", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'That liberty can give.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Is there a heart so cold in man,
Can galling fetters crave?
Is there a wretch so truly low,
Can stoop to be a slave?
O, let him, then, in chains be bound,
In chains and bondage live;
Nor never, never know the sweets", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'Than stranger hearts and limbs without a fetter.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Yet blessings on thy Roman-mother spirit;
Could I forget it, then,
The parting scene, and struggle not to inherit
A freeman’s birth-right once again?
O noble words! O holy love which gave
Thee strength to utter them, a poor, heart-broken slave!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'AIR--Kinloch of Kinloch.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "We’re coming, we’re coming, the fearless and free,
Like the winds of the desert, the waves of the sea!
True sons of brave sires who battled of yore,
When England’s proud lion ran wild on our shore!
We’re coming, we’re coming, from mountain and glen,
With hearts to do battle for freedom again;
Oppression is trembling as trembled before", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'The slavery which fled from our fathers of yore.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Spirituals', 'lyrics' => "We’re coming, we’re coming, with banners unfurled,
Our motto is FREEDOM, our country the world;
Our watchword is LIBERTY--tyrants beware!
For the liberty army will bring your despair!
We’re coming, we’re coming, we’ll come from afar,
Our standard we’ll nail to humanity’s car;
With shoutings we’ll raise it, in triumph to wave,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'AIR--The Rose that all are praising.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "O, he is not the man for me,
Who buys or sells a slave,
Nor he who will not set him free,
But sends him to his grave;
But he whose noble heart beats warm
For all men’s life and liberty;
Who loves alike each human form,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'O, that’s the man for me.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "He’s not at all the man for me,
Who sells a man for gain,
Who bends the pliant, servile knee,
To Slavery’s god of shame!
But he whose God-like form erect
Proclaims that all alike are free
To think, and speak, and vote, and act,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'Of God’s right arm around me.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "When at the driver’s call,
In cold or sultry weather,
We slaves, both great and small,
Turn out to toil together,
I feel like one from whom the sun
Of hope has long departed;
And morning’s light, and weary night,
Still find me broken-hearted;
Thus, when the chilly breath
Of night is sighing round me,
Kneel I, and wish that death
In his cold chain had bound me.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'AIR--Martyn.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "Men! whose boast it is that ye
Come of fathers brave and free;
If there breathe on earth a slave,
Are ye truly free and brave?
Are ye not base slaves indeed,
Men unworthy to be freed,
If ye do not feel the chain,
When it works a brother’s pain?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'Earnest to make others free.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "They are slaves who fear to speak
For the fallen and the weak;
They are slaves, who will not choose
Hatred, scoffing, and abuse,
Rather than, in silence, shrink
From the truth they needs must think;
They are slaves, who dare not be
In the right with _two_ or _three_.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'When Slavery is no more.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Children\'s songs', 'lyrics' => "Come join the Abolitionists,
Ye men of riper years,
And save your wives and children dear,
From grief and bitter tears;
O that will be joyful, joyful, joyful,
O that will be joyful, when Slavery is no more,
When Slavery is no more,
’Tis then we’ll sing, and offerings bring,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'And foulest deeds, and a’ that.', 'author' => 'Brown, William Wells', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "If those who now in bondage groan,
Were white, and fair, and a’ that,
O should we not their fate bemoan,
And plead their cause, and a’ that?
For a’ that, and a’ that,
Would any say, in a’ that", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/58414'),
    array('title' => 'That lay in the House that Jack built.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "This is the Man all tattered and torn,
That kissed the Maiden all forlorn,
That milked the Cow with the crumpled horn,
That tossed the Dog,
That worried the Cat,
That killed the Rat,
That ate the Malt,
That lay in the House that Jack built.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/20777'),
    array('title' => 'Neither too hard nor yet too weak.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "If too wise you appear, folk too much will claim of you,
If too foolish, they still will be making fresh game of you,
If too conceited, vexatious they'll dub you,
If too unselfish, they only will snub you,
If too much of a tattler, you ne'er will be heeded,
If too silent, your company ne'er will be needed,
If overhard, your pride will be broken asunder,
If overweak, the folk will trample you under.\"", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Though wise not given to arrogancy.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "I promised little, though lavish of gift;
I was not reckless though I was swift;
Young, I never derided the old;
And never boasted though I was bold;
Of an absent one no ill would I tell;
I would not reproach, though I praised full well;
I never would ask but ever would give,
For a kingly life I craved to live!\"", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'The conscience thereto of a ravening hound.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Like a stately noble he answers all speakers
From a memory full as a Chronicle-maker's,
With the suave behaviour of Abbot or Prior,
Yet the blasphemous tongue of a horse-thief liar
And he wise as false in every grey hair,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Of the Maker\'s Eternal Divinity.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "I invoke, on my journey arising,
The power of Christ's Birth and Baptizing,
The powers of the hours of His dread Crucifixion,
Of His Death and Abode in the Tomb,
The power of the hour of His glorious Resurrection
From out the Gehenna of gloom,
The power of the hour when to Heaven He ascended,
And the power of the hour when by Angels attended,
He returns for the Judgment of Doom!
On my perilous way
To Tara to-day,
I, Patrick, God's servant,
Invoke from above
The Cherubim's love!
Yea! I summon the might of the Company fervent
Of Angel obedient, ministrant Archangel", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'To speed and to prosper my Irish Evangel.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "I go forth on my path in the trust
Of the gathering to God of the Just;
In the power of the Patriarchs' prayers;
The foreknowledge of Prophets and Seers;
The Apostles' pure preaching;
The Confessors' sure teaching;
The virginity blest of God's Dedicate Daughters,
And the lives and the deaths of His Saints and His Martyrs!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'The rock\'s austerity.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "I arise on my way,
With God's Strength for my stay,
God's Might to protect me,
God's Wisdom to direct me,
God's Eye to be my providence,
God's Ear to take my evidence,
God's Word my words to order,
God's Hand to be my warder,
God's Way to lie before me,
God's Shield and Buckler o'er me,
God's Host Unseen to save me,
From each ambush of the Devil,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Alone or in a multitude.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "All these Hierarchies and Powers
I invoke to intervene,
When the adversary lowers
On my path, with purpose keen
Of vengeance black and bloody
On my soul and my body;
I bind these Powers to come
Against druid counsel dark,
The black craft of Pagandom,
And the false heresiarch,
The spells of wicked women,
And the wizard's arts inhuman,
And every knowledge, old and fresh,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'May follow my mission.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Christ behind and before me,
Christ beneath me and o'er me,
Christ within and without me,
Christ around and about me,
Christ on my left and Christ on my right,
Christ with me at morn and Christ with me at night;
Christ in each heart that shall ever take thought of me,
Christ in each mouth that shall ever speak aught of me;
Christ in each eye that shall ever on me fasten,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'The countless hierarchies through Heaven\'s bright borders--', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Land, strand, and flood,
That I might search all books and from their chart
Find my soul's calm;
Now kneel before the Heaven of my heart,
Now chant a psalm;
Now meditate upon the King of Heaven,
Chief of the Holy Three;", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'And good for all manner of store.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "A few true comrades I next would seek
To mingle with me in prayer,
Men of wisdom, submissive, meek;
Their number I now declare,
Four times three and three times four,
For every want expedient,
Sixes two within God's Church door,
To north and south obedient;
Twelve to mingle their voices with mine
At prayer, whate'er the weather,
To Him Who bids His dear sun shine", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'By Aaron and Moses.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "Male and female,
The days that are seven,
The stars of heaven,
The air and the ether,
Every book and fair letter;
Fish in waters fair-flowing,
And song and deed glowing!
Grey sand and green sward
Make your blessing's award!
And all such as with good
Have satisfied stood!
While my own mouth shall bless Thee", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Take flight from all the billows.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Summer's cloister be my church
Of soft leaf-searching whispers,
From whose mossed bench the nightingale
To all the vale chants vespers!
Mellow-toned, the brake amid,
My organ hid be cuckoo!
Paters, seemly hours and psalm
Bird voices calm re-echo!
Mystic masses, sweet addresses,
Blackbird, be thou offering;
Till God His Bard to Paradise
Uplift from sighs and suffering.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'To ease me of mine anguish.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "If heroic was my youth,
In truth its powers are over;
With brain dead and force sped,
Love sets at naught the lover!
The Muse from off my lips is thrust,
'Tis long since song has cheered me;
Gone is Ivor, counsellor just,
And Nest, whose grace upreared me!
Morfydd, all my world and more,
Lies low in churchyard gravel;
While beneath the burthen frore", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Has quenched the thrill love gave me.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "My ripe grain of heart and brain
The sod sadly streweth;
Its empty chaff with mocking laugh
The wind of death pursueth!
Dig my grave! O, dig it deep
To hide my sleeping body,
So but Christ my spirit keep,
Amen! ab Gwilym's ready!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Freely flock before The Lord--', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "And His Judgment-seat is set
High on mighty Olivet,
Forthright then shall be the tale
Of the Plougher of the Vale,
If so be his tithes were given
Justly to the King of Heaven;
If he freely shared his store", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'With his daddy to and fro.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Spirituals', 'lyrics' => "His own sweet songs he'd then be singing,
Then for a nut with a shout be springing;
Holding my hand he'd trot about with me,
Coax me now, and now fall out with me,
Now, make it up again, lip to lip,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Deals my lone heart a double stab.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Bright dream beyond my own life's shore,
Proud purpose of my future's store,
My hope, my comfort from annoy,
My jewel and my glowing joy,
My nest of shade from out the sun,
My lark, my soaring, singing one,
My golden shaft of faithful love
Shot at the radiant round above,
My intercessor with Heaven's King,
My boyhood's second blossoming,
My little, laughing, loving John,
For you I'm sunk in shadow wan!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Yet stealthy as thieves at night.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Then what woe to the froward,
What joy to the just and kind!
When the Seraph band comes streaming
Christ's gleaming banner behind;
Heavenly blue shall its hue be
To a myriad marvelling eyes;
Save where its heart encrimsons
The cross of the sacrifice!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Conspire to fire Antonius\' shapely towers.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Ere long the Temple proud, surpassing all
Art's fairest gems, shall unto earth be bowed!
Lo! through the lurid gloom the lightning's lash!
And hark the unnatural thunder crash and boom!
Moriah's marvellous fane is leaning low;
With cries of woe her rafters rend in twain;", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Lasses turn pale.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Oh, why start a-fishing
Far, far and across the foam?
Give way to our wishing;
Stay, stay at home!\"
\"Now, but for King Herring,
What 'ood you be wearing,
How 'ood you be faring
How keep ye warm?
Lest loaves should be failing,
Lest children for want take harm,
Men still will go sailing
Out into the storm.\"", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Grandchildren can be none from me to you.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Therefore, my daughters, O, consider well
Since you are young, and fair and so excel
In every homecraft, were it not more wise
No longer to refuse to turn your eyes
Towards the suitors brave who, now your days
Of mourning are accomplished, fix their gaze
Upon your goings? Verily now 'twere right
That you should each a noble Moabite
Espouse, till, with another's love accost,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Your childless grief in motherhood be lost.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "And I, why should I tarry longer here
To be a burden on you year by year?
Kinsfolk and friends have I at Bethlehem
Where plenty reigns; I will go back to them--\"
Then much they both besought her to remain,
And yet her purpose neither could restrain;
Therefore her goods to gather she began", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Naomi spoke her purpose once again:', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "\"Daughters, turn back, each to her mother's house
To take the rest that there her work allows,
And in due course a second husband find,
Nor be unto the future foolish--blind!
Yet take a blessing from the heart of hearts
Of your Naomi ere she hence departs.\"", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'For where thou goest, I will surely go.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "And where thou lodgest, will I lodge also!
Thy people shall be my people evermore,
And thy God only will I now adore!
And where thou diest, I will buried be!
So may Jehovah strike me with his thunder,
If aught but only death our lives shall sunder.\"", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Then with Naomi hand in hand she went.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "But as they slept that night there came to each
The selfsame vision, though they ne'er had speech
Thereon, till Obed's birth, Ruth's only son
And David's grandsire; for they each saw one
With Mahlon's aspect seated in the skies,
And on his knees a babe with Ruth's own eyes,
And by the infant's side one with a face
Ruddy and bold, a form of Kingly grace,
And in his hand a harp wherefrom he drew
Marvellous music while his songs thereto", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Of her abased head.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "And so, when Simon looked,
And pondered, evil-eyed,
No longer Jesus brooked
His thought, but thus replied;
\"Simon, no kiss of peace
Thou gav'st me at thy door,
No oil, my head to ease,
Didst thou upon it pour,
Nay, for thy bidden guest
So little hast thou cared,
His weary feet to rest
No bath hadst thou prepared;
Yet hath this woman here,
By thee with scorn decried,
Washed them with many a tear,
And with her tresses dried,
And given them, from her store
Of spikenard, cool relief,
And kissed them o'er and o'er", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'In penitential grief.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Therefore her joy begins,
Her prayer is heard in heaven;
Though many are her sins,
They all shall be forgiven!\"
Scant mercy he receives
Whose love for God is small;
But he whom God forgives
The most, loves most of all.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Since God, remaining God, becometh Man.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Here is a mother with no mortal mate!
Here is a son that hath no earthly father!
A graft, on Adam's stock incorporate,
Who yet therefrom no mortal taint can gather!
A Babe to whom a new and glorious Star", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Darkly in icy death stifle his labouring breath.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "\"Late upon yon white height the despot his fugitives rallied,
Deeming the crest snow-crowned still inaccessibly frowned;
Idly, for instant upon him my bright-speared chivalry sallied,
Smote and far into the North swept him discomfited forth,
Therefore, from root unto hole, from hole into burgeoning branches,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Tendril and tassel and cup now let the ichor leap up:', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Therefore, with flowering drift and with fluttering bloom avalanches,
Snowdrop and silver thorn laugh baffled winter to scorn;
Primrose, daffodil, cowslip, shine back to my shimmering sandals,
Hyacinth host, o'er the green flash your cerulean sheen,
Lilac, your perfumed lamps, light, chestnut, your clustering candles,
Broom and laburnum, untold torches of tremulous gold!
Therefore gold-gather again from the honeyed heath and the bean field,
Snatching no instant of ease, bright, multitudinous bees!
Therefore, ye butterflies, float and flicker from garden to green field,
Flicker and float and stay, settle and sip and away!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'By Shakespeare\'s birth it won a second fame.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "A greater glory is its crown to-day
Since at its first and faintest uttered breath
A mighty angel rolled the stone away
That sealed His tomb Who captive now leads death,
And thereby did the great example give.
That they who die for others most shall live.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Who thus bespake them on the mountain crest:', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "\"Why stand ye, men of Galilee,
So sadly gazing on the skies?
For this same Jesus, whom ye see
Caught in the clouds to Paradise,
Shall in like manner from the starry height
Return again to greet your joyful sight.\"", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Who having seen Thee not, have yet believed.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "O, then in each succeeding year
When Thine Ascension Day draws round,
With hearts so full of holy fear
May we within Thy Church be found,
That in the spirit we may see Thee rise
And bless us with pierced hands from out the skies!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Was caught into the skies--', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "The Angels, whose harmonious breath
Erstwhile proclaimed His birth,
Now hailed Him Victor over Death,
Redeemer of the Earth;
\"Lift up your heads, ye Heavenly Gates!\"
Rang forth their joyful strain;
\"For lo! the King of Glory waits
To enter you again!\"", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'All your good gifts back again.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Till, ye faithful sons and daughters,
God your golden lives deliver,
Like the good grain to the waters
Of death's overflowing river;
Till up-caught amid His sleepers,
Heavenly fruit from earthly loam,
At the last, His angel reapers
On their bosoms bear you home.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'The king of his kind and the cream of all charity.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "How the rich and the poor, to consult for a cure,
Crowd on to his door in their carts and their carriages,
Showin' their tongues or unlacin' their lungs,
For divel wan sympton the docther disparages,
Troth an' he'll tumble for high or for humble
From his warm feather-bed wid no cross contrariety;
Makin' as light of nursin' all night", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Of doubt and danger none had brooked before.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "For while incredulous friend and foe denied him
Such possible prowess, Honour's blast he blew;
And lo! as if from out the earth beside him,
Army on army into order grew;
Till need at last was none for our retreating,
And back to Belgium and the front of France
We bore, firm gathered for our foe's defeating", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Thou gavest him back from death.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Then o'er the tempest of his pain,
His cry of perishing thrill,
Let Thy right arm go forth again,
Thy saving \"Peace! be still!\"
Until to all his strength restored
Thy Spirit lead Him down,
In solemn state, Almighty Lord,
To take from Thee his crown.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'A dying woman lay.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "\"More pure than yonder virgin snow
From God comes gently down,
I left my happy country home,\"
She sighed, \"to seek the town,
More foul than yonder drift shall turn,
Before the sun is high,
Downtrodden and defiled of men,
More foul,\" she wept, \"am I.\"", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'We come, alas! or go.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "None answering thee? thou sayest,
Nay, mourner, from thy heart,
If but in faith thou prayest,
The Voice Divine shall start;
\"I gave and I have taken,
If thou wouldst comfort win
To cheer thy life forsaken,
I knock, O, let me in!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'There stole a Presence angel-eyed.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "\"If thou wouldst heal thee of thy wound,\"
Her voice to heavenly harps attuned
Bespake me, \"Let the sovran tide
Within this glass thy future guide.\"
Therewith she gave into my hands
No hour-glass running golden sands,
Only a horologe forlorn
Set against a cross of thorn,
And cold and stern the current seemed", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'With tears that horologe forlorn.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "And all my moments by its dust
I measure now with prayerful trust,
And though my courage oft turns weak,
Fresh comfort from that cross I seek;
In wistful hope I yet may wake
To find the thorn in blossom break,
And from life's shivered glass behold
My being's sands ebb forth in gold.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Supremely sung or spoken.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "But O, our darling in his joyful dance
Tottered death-pale beneath the withering north,
Into a kinder clime, most blessed chance,
We caught him swiftly forth,
And there he bloomed again, our fairy boy,
Two year-long Aprils through in sun and shower,
Wing-footed Mercury of each merry hour,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'The Genius of our joy.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "And evermore we shared his shifting mood
Of hide-and-seek with April joy and sorrow,
Till not one shadow of solicitude
Remained to mar our morrow;
Yea, every fear had flown, lest, welladay!
The headlong heats or winter's piercing power
Should light afresh upon our radiant flower", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Upon our suffering child.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Though Earth's physicians all in vain
Have urged their utmost skill,
Yet to our prayers O make it plain
That Thou canst succour still;
Yea! through the midnight watches drear,
And all the weary day,
O be Thy Good Physician near
Our stricken one to stay;
That evermore as we succeed
In service at his side,
Each office of our darling's need
His heavenly hands may guide;
Till o'er his tempest bed of pain,
His cry of perishing thrill
The Saviour's arm go forth again,
The Saviour's \"Peace! be still.\"", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Our children from our care.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "Yet, O Good Shepherd, lead us back,
Our lamb upon Thy breast,
Safely along the narrow track,
Across the dangerous crest;
Until our aching eyes rejoice
At Salem's shining walls,
And to our thirsting souls a Voice
Of Living Waters calls.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Pour all our hearts in prayer.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Is this the end? The tired little hands
Fall by his side, the wild eyes close at last,
Breathless he sinks, almost we hear his sands
Of being ebbing past;
When, O miraculous! he wakes once more,
Love glowing in his glance, the while there slips
\"Mother, dear Mother!\" from his trembling lips,
\"Dear Mother!\" o'er and o'er.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Cheeks pale with care:', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Pulses of pain that throb from night till morrow;
Hearts of despair!
O, yet take comfort, still your joy approaches,
Dark is the hour that on the dawn encroaches,
April's own smile shall yet succeed your sighing,
April's own voice set every song-bird crying,
\"Spring is not dead!\"", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Lest the spell should be snapped in sunder.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Thus we sat awaiting a sign!
When, on a sudden, out of the distance blared the bugle that hangs at
the gate;
Loud the barbican leaped on its hinges; and the hollow porch and the
vacant hall
And the roof of the long resounding corridor echoed the advent of unknown
feet,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'Uprose Arthur, unbarred his helmet; shone confessed the countenance chaste.', 'author' => 'Graves, Alfred Perceval', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Then, for so the Spirit inspired him, set the youth on the Perilous Seat;
Brake as he pressed it a Peal of thunder and paled the firelight, paled
the lamps,
Such a sudden stream of splendour flooded the Feast with miraculous light;
Whilst, O Wonder! round the Table swathed in samite, dazzling bright,
Passed the Presence, mystical, shadowy, ghostly gliding--the Holy Grail,
Passed, though none could its shape discover, nay, not even the Virgin
Knight,
Passed, passed with strains seraphic, incense odours, rainbow hues--
Passed, passed, and where it entered, suddenly melted out of sight.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/14232'),
    array('title' => 'The family Bible.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "How painfully pleasing the fond recollection
Of youthful connections and innocent joy,
When blessed with parental advice and affection,
Surrounded with mercies—with peace from on high!
I still view the chairs of my father and mother,
The seats of their offspring as ranged on each hand;
And that richest of books which excelled every other,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'The family Bible that lay on the stand.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "2 That Bible, the volume of God’s inspiration,
At morn and at evening could yield us delight;
And the prayer of our sire was a sweet invocation
For mercy by day and for safety through night;
Our hymn of thanksgiving with harmony swelling,
All warm from the heart of the family band,
Has raised us from earth to that rapturous dwelling", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Acts 17:28.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Unchangeable, all-perfect Lord!
Essential life’s unbounded sea!
What lives and moves, lives by thy word;
It lives, and moves, and is, from thee!
Whate’er in earth, or sea, or sky,
Or shuns, or meets, the wandering thought,
Escapes, or strikes, the searching eye,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Declares thy goodness gave it birth.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "3 The moon and stars, that rule at night,
And smile upon this world of wrong,
Bear on each trembling chord of light
The notes of this sweet, sacred song;
“Thou, Lord, didst make all things that move;
All are the creatures of thy love.”", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Source of being, source of light.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Source of being, source of light,
With unfading beauties bright;
Thee, when morning greets the skies,
Blushing sweet with humid eyes;
Thee, when soft declining day
Sinks, in purple waves away;
Thee, O Parent, will I sing,
To thy feet my tribute bring!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Luke 2:14.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Hark! what joyful notes are swelling
On the quiet midnight air!
’Tis the voice of angels telling,
Jesus comes our sins to bear!
Now the music, in its gladness,
Breaks and swells, and glides along!
Now, earth, waking from her sadness,
Joins the chorus of the song!
Glory in the highest heaven!
Peace on earth, good-will to man!
Let all praise to God be given,
For Redemption’s glorious plan!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Glory in the highest heaven! etc.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Patriotic songs', 'lyrics' => "3 Rise and shine, Star of Salvation!
Spread thy beams o’er all the earth,
Till each distant land and nation
Owns and speaks thy matchless worth!
Till all tongues, thy praises singing,
Shall thy mighty wonders tell,
Till all heaven with joy is ringing,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Sacred tears.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Draw near, ye weary, bowed, and broken-hearted,
Ye onward travelers to a peaceful bourne;
Ye from whose path the light hath all departed;
Ye who are left in solitude to mourn;
Though o’er your spirits hath the storm-cloud swept,
Sacred are sorrow’s tears, since “Jesus wept.”", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'The Lord of heaven and earth.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "2 He came, not in his robe of wrath,
With arm outstretched to slay;
But on the darkling paths of earth,
To pour celestial day;
To guide in peace the wandering feet,
The broken heart to bind,
And bear upon the painful cross,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'The sins of human kind.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "3 And thou hast borne them, Saviour meek!
And therefore unto thee,
In humbleness and gratitude,
Our hearts shall offered be;
Our contrite hearts, an offering, Lord,
Which thou wilt not despise,
Our souls, our bodies, all be thine,
A living sacrifice!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'John 1:20.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "The Son of Man they did betray;
He was condemned, and led away,
Think, O my soul, on that dread day,
Look on Mount Calvary;
Behold him, lamb-like, led along
Surrounded by a wicked throng,
Accused by every lying tongue,
And then the Lamb of God they hung", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Upon the shameful tree.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "2 Now, hung between the earth and skies,
Behold! in agony he dies;
O sinners, hear his mournful cries,
Come, see his torturing pain!
The morning sun withdrew his light,
Blushed, and refused to view the sight,
The azure clothed in robes of night,
All nature mourned, and stood affright,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Christ the Way, the Truth, and the Life.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Thou art the way; and he who sighs,
Amid this starless waste of woe,
To find a pathway to the skies,
A light from heaven’s eternal glow,
By thee must come, thou gate of love,
Through which the saints undoubting trod,
Till faith discovers, like the dove,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'An ark, a resting-place in God.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "2 Thou art the Truth, whose steady day
Shines on through earthly blight and bloom;
The pure, the everlasting Ray,
The Lamp that shines e’en in the tomb;
The light that out of darkness springs,
And guideth those that blindly go;
The Word whose precious radiance flings", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Its luster upon all below.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "3 Thou art the Life, the blesséd Well
With living waters gushing o’er,
Which those that drink shall ever dwell
Where sin and thirst are known no more,
Thou art the mystic Pillar given,
Our Lamp by night, our Light by day;
Thou art the sacred Bread from heaven;", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Isaiah 4:6.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Jesus, lover of my soul,
Let me to thy bosom fly,
While the billows near me roll,
While the tempest still is high;
Hide me, O my Saviour, hide,
Till the storm of life is past,
Safe into the haven guide,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'And look to the Rock that is higher than I.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "4 And when the last trumpet shall sound thro’ the skies,
And the dead from the dust of the earth shall arise,
Transported I’ll join with the ransomed on high,
To praise the great Rock that is higher than I!
Higher than I, higher than I,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'I am Alpha and Omega.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Cling to the mighty One,    Ps. lxxxix. 19.
Cling in thy grief;    Heb. xii. 11.
Cling to the Holy One,    Heb. vii. 26.
He gives relief;    Ps. cxvi. 8.
Cling to the Gracious One,    Ps. cxvi. 5.
Cling in thy pain,    Ps. lv. 4.
Cling to the Faithful One,    1 Thess. v. 24.
He will sustain.    Ps. xxviii. 8.", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Where flowers are, in heart, but one.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "3 Soldiers of heaven! take sword and shield,
Look up to him who rules on high,
And forward to the glorious field,
Where noble martyrs bleed and die;
Press onward, scorning flight or fear,
As deep waves burst on Norway’s coast,
And let the startled nations hear", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Isaiah 5:4.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "What could your Redeemer do
More than he has done for you?
To procure your peace with God,
Could he more than shed his blood?
After all this flow of love,
All his drawings from above,
Why will you your Lord deny?
Why will you resolve to die?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Thou must either break or bow.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "2 At his presence nature shakes;
Earth, affrighted, hastes to flee;
Solid mountains melt like wax;
What will then become of thee?
Who his coming may abide?
You that glory in your shame,
Will you find a place to hide
When the world is wrapt in flame?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Come, believe.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "5 The way to heaven is straight and plain,
Will you go?
Believe, repent, be born again;
Will you go?
The Saviour cries aloud to thee
“Take up thy cross, and follow me,
And thou shalt my salvation see;
Come to me.”", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'The Eden above.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "We’re bound for the land of the pure and the holy,
The home of the happy, the kingdom of love,
Ye wanderers from God, in the broad road of folly,
O say, will you go to the Eden above,
Will you go, will you go,
O say, will you go to the Eden above?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Can more weary be than I.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "3 In the ark the weary dove
Found a welcome resting-place;
Thus my spirit longs to prove
Rest in Christ, the Ark of grace;
Tempest-tossed I long have been,
And the flood increases fast;
Open, Lord, and take me in,
Till the storm be overpast!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'I’m going home.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "3 The nearer still she draws to land,
More eager all her powers expand;
With steady helm, and free bent sail,
Her anchor drops within the vail;
And now for joy she folds her wings,
And her celestial sonnet sings,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'John 4:35.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Ho, reapers of life’s harvest,
Why stand with rusted blade,
Until the night draws round thee,
And day begins to fade?
Why stand ye idle, waiting
For reapers more to come?
The golden morn is passing,
Why sit ye idle, dumb?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Be every sigh our bosoms pour.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "2 Pure as the sun’s enlivening ray,
That scatters life and joy abroad;
Pure as the lucid orb of day,
That wide proclaims its Maker, God;
Pure as the breath of vernal skies,
So pure let our contrition be;
And purely let our sorrows rise", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'My peace I give unto you.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Lamb of God! whose bleeding love
We now recall to mind,
Send thy blessing from above,
And let us mercy find;
Think on us, who think on thee;
Every burdened soul release;
O, remember Calvary,
And bid us go in peace!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Lie the secrets of thy might.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "2 Sun, who all my life dost brighten!
Light, who dost my soul enlighten!
Joy, the sweetest man e’er knoweth!
Fount, whence all my being floweth!
Humbly draw I near to thee;
Grant that I may worthily
Take this blesséd heavenly food,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'To thy praise, and to my good.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "3 Jesus, Bread of Life from heaven,
Never be thou vainly given,
Nor I to my hurt invited;
Be thy love with love requited;
Let me learn its depths indeed,
While on thee my soul doth feed;
Let me, here so richly blest,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Hour of prayer.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Sweet hour of prayer! sweet hour of prayer,
That calls me from a world of care,
And bids me at my Father’s throne,
Make all my wants and wishes known!
In seasons of distress and grief,
My soul has often found relief,
And oft escaped the tempter’s snare,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'And wait for thee, sweet hour of prayer.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "3 Sweet hour of prayer! sweet hour of prayer!
Thy wings shall my petition bear
To him whose truth and faithfulness
Engage the waiting soul to bless;
And since he bids me seek his face,
Believe his word and trust his grace,
I’ll cast on him my every care,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'And gather here to pray.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "2 O, blesséd is the hour
That lifts our hearts on high!
Like sunlight when the tempests lower,
Prayer to the soul is nigh;
Though dark may be our lot,
Our eyes be dim with care,
These saddening thoughts shall trouble not", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Hear our humble, earnest cry.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "3 By thine hour of dark despair,
By thine agony of prayer,
By thy purple robe of scorn,
By thy wounds, thy crown of thorn,
By thy cross, thy pangs and cries,
By thy perfect sacrifice;
Jesus, look with pitying eye,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'The distant scene: one step enough for me.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "2 I was not ever thus, nor prayed that thou
Shouldst lead me on!
I loved to choose and see my path; but now,
Lead thou me on!
I loved day’s dazzling light, and spite of fears
Pride ruled my will: remember not past years!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Echo round the earth and main.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "2 Hallelujah! hark, the sound,
From the depths unto the skies,
Wakes above, beneath, around,
All creation’s harmonies!
See Jehovah’s banner furled,
Sheathed his sword; he speaks—’tis done!
And the kingdoms of this world
Are the kingdoms of his Son!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Hear the voice of war again.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "3 You, no more your suns descending,
Waning moons no more shall see;
But, your griefs for ever ending,
Find eternal noon in me;
God shall rise, and shining o’er you,
Change to day the gloom of night;
He, the Lord, shall be your glory,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Isaiah 12:6.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Spirituals', 'lyrics' => "Zion, the marvelous story be telling,
The Son of the Highest, how lowly his birth!
The brightest of angels in glory excelling,
He stoops to redeem thee—he reigns upon earth,
Shout the glad tidings! exultingly sing,
Jerusalem triumphs! Messiah is King!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Each to each th’ alternate hymn:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "2 “Lord, thy glory fills the heaven;
Earth is with its fullness stored;
Unto thee be glory given,
Holy, holy, holy Lord!”
Heaven is still with glory ringing;
Earth takes up the angel’s cry,
“Holy, holy, holy,” singing,
“Lord of hosts, the Lord most high!”", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Bring us to eternal day.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "3 Carry on thy new creation,
Pure and holy may we be;
Let us see our whole salvation,
Perfectly secured by thee;
Change from glory into glory,
Till in heaven we take our place;
Till we cast our crowns before thee,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Save through trials well sustained.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "2 Guide us while we onward move,
Linked in closest bonds of love,
Striving for the holy mind,
And the soul from sense refined;
That when life no longer burns,
And the dust to dust returns,
With the strength which thou hast given,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Doxology.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Father! glory be to thee,
Source of all the good we see!
Glory for the blesséd Light
Rising on the ancient night!
Glory for the hopes that come
Streaming through the silent tomb!
Glory for thy Spirit given,
Guiding us in peace to heaven!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Psalm 86:17.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Of thy love some gracious token
Grant us, Lord, before we go;
Bless thy word which has been spoken;
Life and peace on all bestow!
When we join the world again,
Let our hearts with thee remain;
O direct us
And protect us,
Till we gain the heavenly shore
Where thy people want no more!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Psalm 91:1.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "O this is blessing, this is rest!
Into thine arms, O Lord! I flee;
I hide me in thy faithful breast,
And pour out all my soul to thee,
Now, hushing every adverse sound,
Songs of defense my soul surround,
As if all saints encamped about", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'One trusting heart, pursued by doubt.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "2 And O, how solemn, yet how sweet,
Their one assured, persuasive strain!
“The Lord of hosts is thy retreat,
Still in his hands thy times remain.”
O tender word! O truth divine!
Lord, I am altogether thine;
I have bowed down, I need not flee;", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Psalm 57:1.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Do not I trust in thee, O Lord?
Do I not rest in thee alone?
Is not the comfort of thy word
The sweetest cordial I have known?
When vexed with care, bowed down with grief,
Where else could I obtain relief?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'O lead us gently on.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Father of love, our Guide and Friend,
O, lead us gently on,
Until life’s trial-time shall end,
And heavenly peace be won!
We know not what the path may be
As yet by us untrod;
But we can trust our all to thee,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Rest, weary heart.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Rest, weary heart,
From all thy silent griefs, and secret pain,
Thy profitless regrets, and longings vain;
Wisdom and love have ordered all the past,
All shall be blessedness and light at last;
Cast off the cares that have so long opprest;
Rest, sweetly rest!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'I will not let thee go.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "I will not let thee go; thou help in time of need,
Heap ill on ill,
I trust thee still,
E’en when it seems as thou wouldst slay indeed!
Do as thou wilt with me,
I yet will cling to thee,
Hide thou thy face; yet, help in time of need,
I will not let thee go!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'For heavén is my home.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "2 A pilgrim long I’ve wandered here;
But, with a steadfast eye,
I see a rest reserved for me,
At God’s right hand on high,
Then all the joys of earth in vain
Shall tempt my feet to roam,
To seek a dwelling-place below,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Psalm 55:6, 7.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "O that I had wings like a dove,
For, then, would I soon be at rest;
I’d fly to the mansions above;
The home of the pure and the blest;
The place where no sorrow or tears
Can ever my pleasures destroy;
But where through eternity’s years,
I’ll drink from an ocean of Joy!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Is seen through the darkness of night.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "3 I try to be humble and meek,
Leave all to my Saviour’s own will;
For, He to the tempest can speak,
The winds will obey and be still;
But now my soul flutters and cries,
And longs to be soaring away,
From darkness and gloom, to the skies,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Help thou our unbelief.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "3 And when the powers of nature fail
Upon the couch of pain,
Nor love, nor friendship can avail
The spirit to detain;
Then, Father, be our closing eyes
Undimmed by tears of grief,
And if a trembling doubt arise,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Psalm 23:3.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Holy Father, thou hast taught me
I should live to thee alone;
Year by year, thy hand hath brought me
On through dangers oft unknown;
When I wandered, thou hast found me,
When I doubted, sent me light;
Still thine arm has been around me,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Strength—the Spirit’s strength, indeed.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Work songs', 'lyrics' => "3 I would trust in thy protecting,
Wholly rest upon thine arm;
Follow wholly thy directing,
Thou, mine only guard from harm!
Keep me from mine own undoing,
Help me turn to thee when tried,
Still my footsteps, Father, viewing,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Sound redemption through the sky.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "5 See the heavenly host in rapture
Gazing on these shining bands;
Wondering at their costly garments,
And the laurels in their hands;
There upon the golden pavement,
See the ransomed march along!
While the splendid courts of glory
Sweetly echo with their song!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'O that’s the king for me.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "3 This house of death and mourning
Is not the house for me,
Where all to dust are turning,
In tears and agony;
But there’s a house not made with hands,
It ever stood and ever stands,
Beyond the world’s last burning;", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'And heavenly Father sends him here.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "2 Angel of patience! sent to calm
Our feverish brows with cooling balm,
To lay with hope the storms of fear,
And reconcile life’s smile and tear,
The throbs of wounded pride to still,
And make our own our Father’s will!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Homeward, heavenward, to my God.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "2 O how slowly have I often
Followed where thy hand would draw!
How thy kindness failed to soften!
How thy chastening failed to awe!
Make me for thy rest more ready,
As thy path is longer trod;
Keep me in thy friendship steady,
Till thou call me home, my God!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Were that joy unmixed with thee.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "5 Soul—then know thy full salvation,
Rise o’er sin, and fear, and care,
Joy to find in every station,
Something still to do or bear;
Think what Spirit dwells within thee,
Think what Father’s smiles are thine;
Think that Jesus died to save thee;
Child of heaven, canst thou repine?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'And patiently I wait his day.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "3 Whate’er my God ordains is right;
Though I the cup must drink
That bitter seems to my faint heart,
I will not fear or shrink;
Tears pass away
With dawn of day;
Sweet comfort yet shall fill my heart,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'To bear the cross and win the crown.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "3 Here may the sick and wandering soul,
To truth still blind, to sin a slave,
Find better than Bethesda’s pool,
Or than Siloam’s healing wave;
And may we learn, while here, apart
From the world’s passion and its strife,
That thy true shrine’s a loving heart,
And thy best praise a holy life!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Till I reach heaven’s blissful shore.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "2 Thou canst fit me by thy grace
For the heavenly dwelling-place;
All thy promises are sure,
Ever shall thy love endure;
Then what more could I desire,
How to greater bliss aspire?
All I need, in thee I see,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'By thy more than mortal pain.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "2 Call to mind that unknown anguish,
In thy days of flesh below;
When thy troubled soul did languish
Under a whole world of woe;
When thou didst our curse inherit,
Groan beneath our guilty load,
Burdened with a wounded spirit,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Bruised by all the wrath of God.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "3 By thy most severe temptation,
In that dark, Satanic hour;
By thy last, mysterious passion,
Screen me from the adverse power;
By thy fainting in the garden,
By thy bloody sweat I pray,
Write upon my heart the pardon,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Its winter has no spring.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "3 Lord, let thy love,
Fresh from above,
Soft as the south-wind blow!
Call forth its bloom,
Wake its perfume,
And bid its spices flow!
And when thy voice
Makes earth rejoice,
And the hills laugh and sing,
Lord! make this heart
To bear its part,
And join the praise of spring!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Psalm 23:4.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Though I walk the downward shade,
Deepening through the vail of death,
Yet I will not be afraid,
But, with my departing breath,
I will glory in my God,
In my Saviour I will trust,
Strengthened by his staff and rod,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Gloomy doubts, distressing fears.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "2 ’Mid the chorus of the skies,
’Mid the angelic lyres above,
Hark, their songs melodious rise,
Songs of praise to Jesus’ love!
Happy spirits, ye are fled
Where no grief can entrance find;
Lulled to rest the aching head,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Of our Saviour and our God:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "2 With the light of resurrection,
When our changéd bodies glow,
And we gain the full perfection
Of the bliss begun below;
When the life that flesh obscureth
In each radiant form shall shine,
And the joy that aye endureth,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Flashes forth in beams divine:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "3 While we wave the palms of glory
Through the long eternal years,
Shall we e’er forget the story
Of our mortal griefs and fears?
Shall we e’er forget the sadness,
And the clouds that hung so dim,
When our hearts are filled with gladness,
And our tears are dried by him?", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'The better land.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Children\'s songs', 'lyrics' => "I hear thee speak of the better land,
Thou callest its children a happy band;
Mother! O where is that radiant shore,
Shall we not seek it, and weep no more?
Is it where the flower of the orange blows,
And the fire-flies dance in the myrtle boughs?
Not there! not there!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'That beautiful world.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "We’re going home, we’ve had visions bright
Of that holy land, that world of light,
Where the long, dark night of time is past,
And the morn of eternity dawns at last;
Where the weary saint no more shall roam,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Where the sky is clear, and all are free:', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "Where the victor’s song floats o’er the plains,
And the seraph’s anthems blend with its strains;
Where the sun rolls down its brilliant flood,
And beams on a world that is fair and good;
Where stars, once dimmed at nature’s doom,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'And Jesus reigns, dispensing endless day.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "3 The dwellers there are not like those of earth,
No mortal stain they bear;
And yet they seem of kindred blood and birth;
Whence and how came they there?
Earth was their native soil; from sin and shame,
Through tribulation, they to glory came;
Bond-slaves delivered from sin’s crushing load,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'The home of the soul.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Sea songs', 'lyrics' => "Oh where can the soul find relief from its foes?
A shelter of safety, a home of repose?
Can earth’s highest summit, or deepest hid vale,
Give a refuge, nor sorrow, nor sin can assail?
No, no! there’s no home!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'There’s no home on earth—the soul has no home.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "2 Shall it leave the low earth, and soar to the sky,
And seek for a home in the mansions on high!
In the bright realms of bliss will a dwelling be given,
And the soul find a home in the glory of heaven?
Yes, yes! there’s a home!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'There’s a home in high heaven—the soul has a home.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "3 O! holy and sweet its rest shall be there!
Free for ever from sin, and from sorrow and care;
And the loud hallelujahs of angels shall rise,
To welcome the soul to its home in the skies!
Home, home! home of the soul!
The bosom of God is the home of the soul!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Ever-green mountains.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "There’s a land far away, ’mid the stars, we are told,
Where they know not the sorrows of time,
Where the pure waters wander through valleys of gold,
And where life is a treasure sublime;
’Tis the land of our God—’tis the home of the soul,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'On the ever-green mountains of life.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Drinking songs', 'lyrics' => "2 Here our gaze can not soar to that beautiful land,
But our visions have told of its bliss,
And our souls by the gale from its gardens are fanned,
When we faint in the deserts of this;
And we sometimes have longed for its holy repose,
When our spirits were torn with temptation and woes,
And we’ve drank from the tide of the river that flows", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'She dying gave it me.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "2 Ah! well do I remember those
Whose name these records bear;
Who round the hearth-stone used to close,
After the evening prayer,
And tell of what those pages said,
In terms my heart would thrill!
Though they are with the silent dead,", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'The shadows on our souls.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "3 Slowly the rays of daylight fade;
So fade within our heart
The hopes in earthly love and joy,
That one by one depart;
Slowly the bright stars, one by one,
Within the heavens shine;
Give us, O Lord, fresh hopes in heaven", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'And trust in things divine.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "4 Let peace, O Lord, thy peace, O God,
Upon our souls descend;
From midnight fears and perils, thou
Our trembling hearts defend;
Give us a respite from our toil,
Calm and subdue our woes;
Through the long day we suffer, Lord,
O, give us now repose!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Evening aspiration.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "God that madest earth and heaven,
Darkness and light!
Who the day for toil hast given,
For rest the night!
May thine angel guards defend us,
Slumber sweet thy mercy send us,
Holy dreams and hopes attend us,
This livelong night!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Fading, still fading.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Fading, still fading, the last beam is shining;
Father in heaven! the day is declining;
Safety and innocence flee with the light,
Temptation and danger walk forth with the night;
From the fall of the shade till the morning bells chime,
Shield us from danger and keep us from crime!
Father! have mercy, thro’ Jesus Christ our Lord! Amen!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'To save thee from their power.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "3 Thou whose yet bright and joyous eye
May soon be dimmed with tears,
To whom the hours of bitterness
Must come in coming years;
Teach early thy confiding eye
To pierce the cloudy screen,
To look above the storms, where all", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Only waiting.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "Only waiting till the shadows
Are a little longer grown;
Only waiting till the glimmer
Of the day’s last beam is flown;
Till the night of earth is faded
From the heart once full of day;
Till the stars of heaven are breaking", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'And I hasten to depart.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Folk songs', 'lyrics' => "3 Only waiting till the shadows
Are a little longer grown;
Only waiting till the glimmer
Of the day’s last beam is flown;
Then, from out the gathered darkness,
Holy, deathless stars shall rise,
By whose light my soul shall gladly", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Harvest-Home.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Come, ye thankful people, come,
Raise the song of Harvest-home!
All is safely gathered in,
Ere the winter-storms begin;
God, our Maker, doth provide
For our wants to be supplied;
Come to God’s own temple, come,
Raise the song of Harvest-home!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'In his garner evermore.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "4 Then, thou Church triumphant, come,
Raise the song of Harvest-home!
All are safely gathered in,
Free from sorrow, free from sin;
There for ever, purified,
In God’s garner to abide;
Come, ten thousand angels, come,
Raise the glorious Harvest-home!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Psalm 65:11.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "Lord of the harvest! thee we hail;
Thine ancient promise doth not fail;
The varying seasons haste their round,
With goodness all our years are crowned;
Our thanks we pay
This holy day;
O let our hearts in tune be found!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'For we thy common bounties share.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "4 Lord of the harvest! all is thine!
The rains that fall, the suns that shine,
The seed once hidden in the ground,
The skill that makes our fruits abound!
New, every year,
The gifts appear;
New praises from our lips shall sound!", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'Rushes on to our view, and eternity’s near.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Hymns', 'lyrics' => "3 O that each in the day
Of his coming, may say,
“I have fought my way through;
I have finished the work thou didst give me to do;”
O that each from his Lord,
May receive the glad word,
“Well and faithfully done;
Enter into my joy, and sit down on my throne.”", 'source_url' => 'https://gutendex.com/books/46041'),
    array('title' => 'All below is but a dream.', 'author' => '', 'year' => '', 'category' => 'Love songs', 'lyrics' => "3 Thanks for mercies past receive,
